<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Jewish Schools Opening in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- In the lands where the Nazi regime wreaked its  
deepest destruction on Jewish communities, the sound of children 
singing Hebrew is once again echoing off the walls of new Jewish 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting Sunday, three such schools are being dedicated within  
three days in Austria, Germany and Poland in the hopes of helping 
rejuvenate the Jewish culture across central and eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``They basically are rebuilding Jewish life in these communities  
from the ground up, from the children,'' said Ed Serotta, director 
of the Central Europe Center for Research and Documentation, a 
Vienna-based institute that chronicles contemporary Jewish issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The schools' dedications come at the end of a decade that has  
seen a strong Jewish resurgence in central and Eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Up until 1989, most experts in the field talked of a dying  
European civilization of ``last Jews,'' with thousands having left 
for Israel, the United States or other countries. Germany's Jewish 
population, for example, had dropped from 500,000 before World War 
II to 28,000 in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	But it has swelled to more than 75,000 today. Much of the growth  
is attributed to Jewish immigrants from the former Soviet Union and 
Jews rediscovering roots that were unknown during communism. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the resurgence, though, many of the Jews have gaps of  
knowledge about their culture. In Germany, schools and community 
groups exist in larger cities, but smaller communities have serious 
trouble finding people who can lead services and teach the lessons 
of the Torah. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jewish schools, funded by the Ronald S. Lauder Foundation,  
are trying to bridge that gap. 
</P>
<P>
	They are not the first or only Jewish education programs in the  
region. But experts say there is always a need for much more. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some needs are being met, but it's obviously insufficient,''  
said Amir Shaviv, assistant executive vice president for special 
operations at the New York-based American Jewish Joint Distribution 
Committee. The group funds programs aimed at building Jewish 
communities in former communist countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Before 1989, when Jews in communist countries had almost no  
access to information about their heritage, Shaviv's group and 
others like it worked to bring Jewish literature in as a lifeline. 
But now, with the openness of democracy in places like the former 
East Germany and Poland, the demand for assistance is huge, Shaviv 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the three Lauder Foundation schools, one is brand-new and two  
others are expanding. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the existing schools is in Warsaw, Poland. The 165  
elementary and middle school students learn a dual curriculum of 
Jewish and secular studies. Recent guests include First Lady 
Hillary Rodham Clinton, who observed a Hebrew lesson during her 
visit this week. 
</P>
<P>
	In Vienna, the Lauder Chabad School can accommodate up to 400  
students -- mostly Russian-speaking immigrants who came to Vienna in 
the 1970s. Classes at the new school will combine general secular 
subjects with Jewish history and philosophy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Berlin school is a new facility, and it is taking on a  
different mission -- serving adults. 
</P>
<P>
	It will educate teachers and offer adult education courses. A  
dormitory will house high school graduates for a one-year immersion 
program in Jewish life before they enter college. 
</P>
<P>
	Such programs are much-needed but often ignored in favor of more  
traditional philanthropy, Serotta said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the decades since the Holocaust, he said, philanthropic  
groups have focused on documenting survivors' stories and 
establishing networks of social welfare for adults. Groups like the 
Lauder Foundation that focus on the future of Jewish culture are a 
rarity, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody else is doing it,'' Serotta said. ``No one else is  
devoting an entire foundation to rebuilding Jewish life for the 
children in the lands of the Holocaust.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
