<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 8, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Fortier Jailed for 12 Years  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Going well above sentencing guidelines, a  
federal judge resentenced Michael Fortier to 12 years in prison 
today for failing to notify authorities about plans for the 
Oklahoma City bombing. Fortier has already served a little more 
than four years in prison. The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals 
ordered the resentencing because it said U.S. District Judge G. 
Thomas Van Bebber used wrong guidelines when he sentenced Fortier 
last year to 12 years in prison and a $200,000 fine. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Embassy Bombings Arrest Made  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Tanzanian whose house was allegedly used as a  
bomb factory was arrested in connection with last year's deadly 
bombings of two U.S. embassies in east Africa and brought to the 
United States for trial. The arrest brought to nine the number of 
people in custody in connection with the Aug. 7, 1998, bombings in 
Kenya and Tanzania that killed 224 people, including 12 Americans. 
Khalfan Khamis Mohamed, who was arrested yesterday in South Africa, 
pleaded innocent today during a U.S. District Court appearance. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Backs United Canada  
</P>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- In a polite rebuke to Quebec separatists,  
President Clinton said today the United States is proud to be 
partners with ``a strong, united, democratic Canada.'' The 
president dedicated a new U.S. Embassy before flying to a 
conference in Quebec, the French-speaking province whose leaders 
are dedicated to splitting off from Canada. Clinton made a point of 
stressing warm relations with Canada, which to the surprise of many 
Americans is the United States' biggest trading partner with more 
than $1 billion of commerce every day. 

</P>
<P>
	Document Links U.S., Chile Death  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The top United Nations human rights official  
today welcomed the decision by a British magistrate to allow the 
extradition of Augusto Pinochet to Spain on charges of ordering the 
torture of opponents. Mary Robinson, U.N. high commissioner for 
human rights, said the decision against the Chilean dictator was 
``a signal of hope to those fighting for justice for victims of 
human rights violations.'' Separately, the State department 
released a document today showing U.S. intelligence may have played 
an ``unfortunate part'' in the death of an American at the hands of 
Chilean security forces following Pinochet's 1973 coup. 

</P>
<P>
	Teachers' Union Endorses Gore  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's largest teachers' union today  
endorsed Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic presidential 
nomination, saying he ``understands what children need to start 
school ready to learn.'' The endorsement by the National Education 
Association is the second of its kind in three days for Gore, who 
is being challenged by former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley. On 
Tuesday, the American Federation of Teachers, the second-largest 
teachers union in the country, announced its support for Gore. 

</P>
<P>
	Michael Jackson To Divorce Wife  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- After three years of marriage and two  
children, Michael Jackson and his second wife filed for divorce 
today, a spokesman said. The couple ``mutually agreed to end their 
marriage,'' Howard J. Rubenstein said. ``Michael and Debbie remain 
friends.'' Neither Jackson, 41, nor his wife, Debbie Rowe Jackson, 
will be making any statements. Divorce papers were filed today in 
Los Angeles County Superior Court. The couple have two children: 
Paris Michael Katherine, born in April 1998, and Prince, born in 
February 1997. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Rises 63; Nasdaq Falls 2  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 63.96 points at 10,601.01. Decliners on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,449-1,304. The Nasdaq was down 1.98 at 
2,858.72. 

</P>
<P>
	Twins Owner Agrees To Sell Team  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Minnesota Twins owner Carl Pohlad has  
agreed to sell his team to Timberwolves owner Glen Taylor and Wild 
lead investor Robert Naegele Jr. for $120 million if a new stadium 
is built. ``It's been a great ride,'' Pohlad said today, recalling 
the 1987 and 1991 World Series championships during his 16 years as 
team owner. St. Paul Mayor Norm Coleman announced the proposed sale 
last night. Coleman has sought the sale as part of a plan to build 
a new stadium along the city's riverfront and entice the Twins to 
leave Minneapolis. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
