<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sultan Funds Harvard Professorship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- The Sultan of Oman is funding a new  
professorship at Harvard that will focus on international 
relations, diplomacy and the advancement of women. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming from the ruler of a country where women wear veils and  
are often segregated from men, it might seem a contradiction. 
</P>
<P>
	But Harvard officials said that under Sultan Qaboos bin Said's  
nearly 30-year leadership, Omani women have made significant 
strides in education and the workplace -- enough to give the 
university little pause about taking his money. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reality is the university would not accept a gift if there  
were hypocritical issues,'' said Brad Voigt, a fund-raiding 
director for the John F. Kennedy School of Government. 
</P>
<P>
	The school would not divulge how much money the sultan is  
donating. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvard has had ties to the Middle Eastern country for several  
years. A graduate of the Kennedy School, Frances Cook, is a former 
American ambassador to Oman and arranged three years ago to bring a 
group of young Omani scholars to visit Harvard. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
