<HEADLINE> NASCAR Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- The car driven by fourth-generation stock  
car driver Adam Petty was disqualified Friday after NASCAR 
inspectors said they found an altered part in its carburetion 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	A NASCAR official said a routine inspection following  
second-round qualifying for Saturday's All Pro Auto Parts 300 Busch 
Series race found a groove etched into the gasket below the 
carburetor, allowing extra air flow to reach the carburetor. 
</P>
<P>
	The apparent rules infraction nullified Petty's qualifying lap  
of 175.913 mph that was the fastest in Friday's qualifying session 
and had briefly placed the 19-year-old Busch Series rookie 26th in 
the 43-car field. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Petty will miss the race and everybody from 27th  
through 36th moved up one spot. That also moved Mike Dillon, who 
had failed to qualify by speed or as a provisional, into 36th. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate comment from Petty or his team.  
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAFETY ISSUE: H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler, general manager of Lowe's  
Motor Speedway, wants race fans attending the events Saturday and 
Sunday at the suburban Charlotte track to have fun and put away 
worries about security in the wake of the bombings at two area 
Lowe's Home Improvement stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheeler, joined by Earl Woodham, representing the Federal Bureau  
of Alcohol, Tobacco &AMP; Firearms, met with the media Friday at the 
track to give assurances that nobody is expecting any trouble this 
weekend, despite increased security precautions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have heightened security precautions, but we are going to  
have a good time,'' Wheeler said. ``All week, I have been out 
talking to race fans and making myself visible. I think this 
weekend is really shaping up well. 
</P>
<P>
	``These misconceptions toward what is going on with the Lowe's  
stories situations, as far as the bombings are concerned, has 
included a lot of wrong information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woodham said he would not hesitate to bring his family to the  
track. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not address the investigation (into the bombings), but  
a separation between the investigation and the events this weekend 
has to be made,'' he said. ``Everyone should have a heightened 
sense of awareness because no matter what you are doing these days, 
you risk harm. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to do it coming here. You have to do it in your  
backyard. Lowe's Motor Speedway is just as safe as your backyard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Race officials are expected a crowd close to 170,000 for  
Sunday's UAW-GM 500. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	PAIRED UP: Matt Kenseth, who will vie for Winston Cup Rookie of  
the Year in 2000, also will share time in a Busch Series car with 
hometown friend Jason Schuler. 
</P>
<P>
	It was announced Friday that Kenseth will drive the No. 17  
Reiser Racing Chevrolet in about 20 races next season, while 
Schuler, moving up from the NASCAR Re-Max Challenge Series in the 
Midwest, will drive 10 to 15 short-track and intermediate races for 
the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Kenseth and Schuler are from Cambridge, Wis., where they  
classmates in high school. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited for Jason,'' Kenseth said. ``He's run a long time  
without any help, and I'm glad to see him get something good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schuler would like to get closer to Kenseth on the track,  
</P>
<P>
	``Matt has always been a step ahead of me.'' he said. ``Now it's  
up to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team also announced a two-year sponsorship deal with Pfizer  
Consumer Health Care's Visine brand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
