<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 06:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars' Modano Not Out for Revenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- For Dallas Stars center Mike Modano, revenge is  
not the name of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Modano, who suffered strained neck ligaments after being sent  
head first into the boards last week, is urging restraint when the 
Stars play Anaheim tonight at Arrowhead Pond. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am calling on my teammates to set an example for all  
players,'' Modano said Thursday. ``I am looking forward to getting 
back on the ice and playing as soon as possible, but not to getting 
even. 
</P>
<P>
	``More importantly, I don't want anyone getting even on my  
behalf,'' he said. ``Somewhere along the road, players have lost 
respect for one another and the sport, and that is unacceptable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Modano also broke his nose and sustained a mild concussion after  
Anaheim defenseman Ruslan Salei cross-checked him from behind in 
Saturday's game. Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said afterward that the 
Stars would be forced to respond to the hits that put Modano in the 
hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars' Darryl Sydor is also out with a fractured eye socket  
from a fight with the Mighty Ducks' Jim McKenzie. 
</P>
<P>
	Modano, knocked unconscious during the game, says he might leave  
hockey if the NHL's trend toward increasing violence doesn't abate. 
His injuries left him gun-shy about taking another hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two wrongs don't make a right, and we know that,'' defenseman  
Richard Matvichuk, one of the league's hardest hitters, told The 
Dallas Morning News. ``We've got to worry about wins and not 
revenge against other players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the hit against Modano, the league suspended Salei for 10  
games, and he will forfeit $109,756 in salary. McKenzie was 
suspended for four games, and will lose close to $13,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Players say the suspensions should reduce tensions between the  
teams, which have to face each other four more times this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's extremely unprofessional to really take a run at somebody  
who wasn't even involved in the play,'' said Anaheim goalie Guy 
Herbert. ``If (Salei) was playing, he's got to expect he's going to 
be hit, but I don't think they're going to go after somebody 
else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Modano, who met with reporters after a light workout, said that  
if the career-ending or life-threatening violence doesn't stop, he 
will get off the ice for good -- even though neurological tests show 
he is recovering well. 
</P>
<P>
	``If things continue, I'm not going to play anymore,'' said  
Modano, who led the Stanley Cup champions in regular-season scoring 
with 81 points and playoff scoring with 23. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars' best offensive player also said that he considered  
retiring after watching replays of the hit by Salei and hearing 
others tell him he was inches from being paralyzed. He remembered 
waking to find doctors and trainers hovering over and yelling at 
him to try to move his arms and legs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's gone through my mind a lot, especially when you know  
you're a marked man every time you're on the ice,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 12:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Fans Sue Holdout Yashin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Ottawa Senators star Alexei Yashin may have thought his latest  
holdout would net him a big payday. 
</P>
<P>
	But by failing to honor the last year of his contract, he could  
cost himself even more. 
</P>
<P>
	An Ottawa hockey fan filed a $27.5 million lawsuit against  
Yashin and his agent this week, accusing the two of interfering 
with the contractual relationship between the Senators and their 
fans. The unprecedented claim is far from an empty-netter, but the 
plaintiffs -- the class action could grow to include 11,000 season 
ticket-holders -- want athletes everywhere to know that the public's 
tolerance is limited. 
</P>
<P>
	``No doubt your situation will be looked upon with interest by  
other professional athletes,'' Arthur Cogan, the fans' attorney, 
wrote Yashin. ``Perhaps the time will come when athletes in all 
sports will not act with impunity when the decide to intentionally 
breach their obligations and consider only themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fans who pay serious money for a first-class product are  
directly affected by arbitrary and wrongful conduct by a 
professional athlete. I strongly believe that the rights and 
interests of fans do count and must be taken into consideration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holding out is a way of doing business in the NHL these days,  
with restricted free agents using all available leverage to get the 
best contract possible. This season, Bruins goalie Byron Dafoe, 
Hurricanes forward Keith Primeau and Coyotes goalie Nikolai 
Khabibulin are among those sitting out because of stalled 
negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	But Yashin is not a free agent; he is in the final season of a  
four-year deal that guaranteed him $3.6 million. Still, he wants 
more -- $23 million more for the two seasons after this one -- and 
he's holding out for the third time in five years to get it. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll say, 'We didn't want to hurt the fans.' But who do you  
think it's hurting?'' Cogan said in a telephone interview. ``Hey, 
this is not going to be the same team anymore. It's not the same 
entertainment value.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yashin has been training in Switzerland, and his agent, Mark  
Gandler, declined to comment for this story. The NHL also declined 
to comment on the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senators suspended the 25-year-old former captain when he  
didn't show up for the start of training camp. Although they would 
not comment on the suit, the Senators did release correspondence 
notifying Yashin that they will neither renegotiate nor trade the 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the NHL's collective bargaining agreement requires  
arbitration in such disputes, the team cannot sue Yashin. And 
because the fans have a contract with the team -- but not with 
Yashin -- they have to take an indirect approach, arguing he 
intentionally interfered with their agreement with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it has never been applied in sports, the argument  
attempted by the fans is older than the NHL itself. In a 1853 
English case called Lumley v. Gye, a theater operator with an 
exclusive contract with an opera singer sued a competitor who 
induced the singer to sing elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	The approach presents two problems for the plaintiffs: One is  
showing that, by failing to produce Yashin, the Senators have 
breached the ticket contract. The other is proving that Yashin or 
Gandler intended to cause that breach. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems to me to be something of a stretch, to find an  
intention directed at the fans and not just at the team,'' said 
Harvard law professor Paul Weiler, who wrote the textbook on sports 
law and is a native Canadian. ``It depends to some extent on how 
broadly the Canadian courts will consider intention. It is a 
difficult thing to prove.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint, filed this week in Ontario's Superior Court of  
Justice, details how the Senators had their most successful season 
ever last year, and how Yashin was a big part of that. With 44 
goals with 50 assists, he accounted for 35 percent of the team's 
scoring and was a finalist for the NHL's MVP. 
</P>
<P>
	In the offseason, Yashin was the centerpiece of a marketing  
campaign that helped close 11,000 season ticket contracts at an 
average of $4,000 -- a total of more than $40 million in Canadian 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fans were aware and relied upon the fact that the defendant  
Yashin was contracted to play for the Club for the 1999-2000 NHL 
season, and as a result purchased their tickets with the 
expectation that Yashin would fulfill his contract with the Club 
for the 1999-2000 season and play hockey,'' the complaint reads. 
``Yashin and Gandler acted deliberately and maliciously and in a 
manner calculated to diminish ... the contract between the 
Plaintiff and the Club.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Weiler said, that doesn't necessarily amount to  
inducing a breach. 
</P>
<P>
	``The price of a ticket is much, much more based on the name of  
the team than the specifics of what's happening in the short run,'' 
Weiler said, ``as the Orioles or Dodgers season ticket-holders 
learned this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weiler noted that Denver fans have no right to sue John Elway  
for retiring or Terrell Davis for getting injured, even though 
their absence makes Broncos tickets worth less. However, Cogan 
noted, neither Elway nor Davis -- nor the underperforming Dodgers 
and Orioles -- violated a contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``Within the rules, these things can happen. But it's not  
provided that he can breach a contract,'' Cogan said. ``It's a 
wrongful act. That's the key thing here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The suit seeks damages of $8 million apiece from Yashin and  
Gandler, and punitive damages of $5 million and $6.5 million, 
respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Cogan said he is handling the case for expenses. Ticket-holders  
wanting to sign up must agree that they will donate any damages 
they win to charity, a condition insisted upon by Leonard Potechin, 
the name plaintiff in the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	A 73-year-old retired real estate broker, former minor leaguer  
and Senators season ticket-holder ``from day 1,'' Potechin said the 
idea for the lawsuit came while when he and his friends were having 
a beer after a round of golf. While they were complaining about 
Yashin's holdout, Cogan walked in. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter what happens in court, Potechin said, the group has  
``already won'' by forcing both sides to remember the fans. But the 
real victory for the self-described hockey nut would be to get 
Yashin back into a Senators uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guy is worth the price of admission. He's an outstanding  
player, no question about it,'' Potechin said. ``I just find it 
unacceptable that star hockey players would withhold their services 
for a buck.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Jimmy Golen covers sports and the law for The  
Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 20:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Basketball Pioneer McLendon Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND HEIGHTS, Ohio (AP) -- Basketball Hall of Famer John  
McLendon, the last surviving student of Dr. James Naismith, the 
sport's creator, died Friday at his home. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	McLendon served as a consultant to the NBA's Toronto Raptors  
from their inception. 
</P>
<P>
	``He accumulated a lot of wisdom and perspective, and he brought  
some common sense to the table,'' Raptors general manager Glen 
Grunwald said. ``He was always able to cut to the meat of an issue 
in a folksy kind of way. We'll miss him a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLendon played at the University of Kansas in the early 1930s  
under Naismith. 
</P>
<P>
	In those days, blacks were barred from the university pool even  
though swimming was a graduation requirement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I jumped in and they drained the pool,'' McLendon recalled  
several years ago. ``Dr. Naismith wasn't about to have any of that 
so he sent over three of the biggest men on the basketball team to 
sit by the pool every time I swam. The administration wasn't happy, 
but there were no problems after that. '' 
</P>
<P>
	McLendon went on to a 25-year coaching career and was inducted  
into the Hall of Fame in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the first college coach to win three consecutive national  
titles, with Tennessee State of the NAIA from 1957 to 1959. The 
following season, he became the first African-American professional 
coach with the Cleveland Pipers of the American Basketball League. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Joanna; daughters, Querida Banks of  
Silver Spring, Md., and Nanette Adams of Shaker Heights; a son, 
David Bryant of Cleveland Heights; five grandchildren; four 
great-grandchildren; two sisters and a brother. 
</P>
<P>
	Services will be Wednesday in Cleveland.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 21:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 8, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Seeks Delay for Test Ban Vote  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an effort to avert defeat, President  
Clinton Friday appealed to the Senate to delay acting on the 
nuclear test ban treaty, agreeing the vote could be put off beyond 
the 2000 presidential election. Senate Democrats, meanwhile, worked 
on a plan to force postponement of next week's vote if Republican 
leaders decline Clinton's request. Senate Minority Leader Tom 
Daschle said Democrats may invoke a seldom-used parliamentary 
procedure that would block further action. 

</P>
<P>
	Arrest Made in U.S. Embassy Bombings  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Tanzanian whose house allegedly was used as a  
bomb factory in last year's deadly attacks on two U.S. embassies in 
East Africa pleaded innocent to conspiracy charges Friday and could 
face the death penalty if convicted. Khalfan Khamis Mohamed, 26, 
was arrested Thursday in Cape Town, South Africa and brought to the 
United States for trial. 

</P>
<P>
	Mexico Floods Kill 267  
</P>
<P>
	TEZIUTLAN, Mexico (AP) -- Digging into mounds of mud with  
buckets, shovels and their bare hands, soldiers and survivors 
searched desperately Friday for people buried alive when hillsides 
collapsed in southeastern Mexico after more than a week of 
relentless rain. At least 267 people were confirmed dead from the 
floods, but the number ``is rising by the hour,'' President Ernesto 
Zedillo said Friday during a visit to this devastated city, 110 
miles east of Mexico City. Calling it ``the tragedy of the 
decade,'' Zedillo promised government help for families who have 
lost homes. 

</P>
<P>
	Search for Colo. Boy Ends Unsuccessfully  
</P>
<P>
	RUSTIC, Colo. (AP) -- Rescuers ended the search for a missing  
3-year-old boy on Friday after a week of searching the rugged 
Colorado mountains. Jaryd Atadero vanished while on a hike with his 
6-year-old sister and 11 members of a Christian group who were 
staying at a cabin resort run by their father, Allyn Atadero, a 
physical education teacher. Larimer County Sheriff Jim Alderden 
called off the search after a half-dozen searchers and a couple of 
dogs again failed to turn up any evidence of the boy's location. 
Investigators believe he probably died from a fall in the rocky 
terrain or from exposure, as the nights have been in the 20s. 

</P>
<P>
	Floyd Causes Sewage-Tainted Floodwaters  
</P>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Sewage-tainted floodwaters from Hurricane  
Floyd are creating a growing ``dead zone'' in Pamlico Sound where 
fish and other aquatic life cannot survive. The brown freshwater 
plume sits atop the salt water, robbing it of oxygen from surface 
air and reducing its salinity. Both ingredients are essential for 
aquatic life. ``What we're seeing is an ecological event on the 
catastrophic scale,'' said Hans Paerl, a marine scientist at the 
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. 

</P>
<P>
	$1.2B Award in State Farm Lawsuit  
</P>
<P>
	MARION, Ill. (AP) -- A damage award to State Farm auto insurance  
customers swelled to nearly $1.2 billion after a judge ruled that 
the nation's largest auto insurer committed fraud by its use of 
generic replacement parts in auto-body repairs. Today's $730 
million award of actual and punitive damages came on top of a 
jury's $456 million verdict. 

</P>
<P>
	Deadline Nears for UAW and Ford  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- With a battle line drawn, the United Auto  
Workers continued negotiations with Ford Motor Co. as a midnight 
strike deadline approached. Both sides remained tightlipped about 
the status of the negotiations. UAW officials have said they were 
opposed to Ford's plans to spin off or sell its parts unit, which 
employs 23,500 UAW workers. The new contract would cover about 
100,000 hourly workers. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Climb: Dow Ends Up 112.71  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials gained 112.71 to close at  
10,649.76 today. The Nasdaq gained 21.76 to 2,882.46. 

</P>
<P>
	CBS Show To Strand 16 Americans  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A new CBS game show will strand 16 Americans  
on an uninhabited island in the South China Sea to fend for 
themselves among the pythons and other wild animals -- including 
each other. The last contestant on the island wins $1 million. The 
players must work together to survive, but every three days they 
will hold secret ballots to expel a fellow contestant. When the 
group is whittled down to the final pair, those most recently 
kicked off the island will decide who ends up the winner. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets Rock Diamondbacks 9-2  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets overcame the absence of Mike  
Piazza, with John Olerud driving in three runs and keying a big 
sixth inning for a 9-2 victory over the Arizona Diamondbacks and a 
2-1 lead in the NL division series. Rick Reed, pitching to backup 
Todd Pratt, worked six strong innings. After Olerud and Darryl 
Hamilton hit two-run singles in the sixth, the Mets' bullpen and a 
loud crowd of 56,180 closed out the first postseason game at Shea 
Stadium since 1988. New York gets its chance to advance to the next 
round tomorrow afternoon in Game 4. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  








  	   	
</P>
