<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bombing Defendant Seeks Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A survivor of the Oklahoma City bombing  
says he believes that Michael Fortier is genuinely sorry for not 
telling authorities what he knew about the bomb plot before the 
blast. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dr. Paul Heath said Fortier's remorse is not enough to  
justify releasing him from prison after 4 years and two months. 
Fortier is scheduled to appear before a federal judge for a 
resentencing hearing today. 
</P>
<P>
	``My family prays that the judge certainly doesn't let him out  
for time served,'' said Heath, a Veterans Administration 
psychologist who heads a survivors group. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier, 30, of Kingman, Ariz., has been in prison since  
pleading guilty in August 1995 to having advance knowledge of the 
plot to bomb the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building. The April 19, 
1995 bombing killed 168 people and injured hundreds more. 
</P>
<P>
	He also pleaded guilty to trafficking in guns the government  
says were stolen to finance the bombing, hiding evidence and lying 
to FBI agents. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge G. Thomas Van Bebber sentenced Fortier to 12  
years in prison -- a sentence that was set aside by the 10th U.S. 
Circuit Court of Appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	The appellate court granted Fortier a new sentencing hearing in  
June, ruling that Van Bebber used the wrong guidelines to decide 
the length of his prison term. It said that involuntary 
manslaughter guidelines should have been used, not those for 
first-degree murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier's attorneys maintain that his cooperation with  
government prosecutors at the trials of convicted bomber Timothy 
McVeigh and co-conspirator Terry Nichols qualify him to be 
``released immediately for time served.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier's initial sentencing was delayed nearly three years  
until after the trials of both men. 
</P>
<P>
	McVeigh was convicted of murder, conspiracy and weapons charges.  
He is appealing his death sentence. Nichols was convicted of 
involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy and sentenced to life in 
prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
