<HEADLINE> Alabama Cities To Vote on Mayors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Thanks to the resignation of city's  
longtime mayor, the political dialogue here has come to resemble 
something out of the Jerry Springer show. 
</P>
<P>
	It hasn't come to fisticuffs or broken chairs yet. But at weekly  
City Council meetings, members shout, interrupt each other, call 
each other names, point fingers and stage walkouts -- all of which 
can be seen on the local cable channel. 
</P>
<P>
	It is against this raucous backdrop that voters in Alabama's  
largest city are being asked to choose among 14 candidates who want 
to succeed Richard Arrington, the city's first black mayor and 
dominant political figure for 20 years. Polls show William Bell, 
who became interim mayor when Arrington quit, is the odds-on 
favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	In Montgomery, meanwhile, another long-dominant figure, Mayor  
Emory Folmar, faces six opponents in his bid for a seventh term. It 
is the biggest field of challengers since Folmar whipped more than 
40 candidates to be elected the first time in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Elections in both cities are Oct. 12, the same day voters  
statewide decide on Gov. Don Siegelman's proposal for a state 
lottery. If no candidate gets a majority, a runoff between the top 
two vote-getters will be held three weeks later. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell is relying on his two decades of City Council service and  
close ties to Arrington in his quest for the mayor's seat in 
Birmingham. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrington resigned in July after two decades, handing the job to  
Bell, the council president, for a trial run. Arrington's move gave 
Bell the benefit of incumbency. 
</P>
<P>
	A poll last month showed Bell with a 2-to-1 lead over his  
closest opponent, Councilman Bernard Kincaid, an Arrington foe. But 
more than 40 percent of the likely voters were undecided. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell's ties to the ex-mayor could become a liability among those  
undecided voters because of a string of questions that have emerged 
involving city contracts under Arrington and a land deal between 
the city and one of Arrington's friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Some City Council members have moved to rein in Bell's power  
because of what they say was Arrington's almost unlimited control. 
That has prompted wild council meetings in which black ministers 
have claimed white council members are trying to usurp Bell's 
authority because he is black. 
</P>
<P>
	``You (can) call it a race card if you like. But it's right!''  
the Rev. Abraham Woods preached to the council, drawing a standing 
ovation from a crowd full of Bell supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The scene disgusted Roberta and Franklin Wood, who have been  
coming to council meetings for a month in hopes of getting paving 
and other improvements in their neighborhood, to no avail. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's ridiculous. There's no togetherness here,'' said Wood,  
74, who backs Kincaid. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
