<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: Tight Race on Ala. Lottery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- With ministers united against Gov. Don  
Sigelman's plan for a lottery and a ticket-fixing scandal leaving 
critics warning about government corruption, Siegelman has gone 
back on the campaign trail to push the issue that got him elected 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Voters decide Tuesday whether to expand gambling in this Bible  
Belt state to help pay for school programs and college 
scholarships. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lottery is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to change  
education in Alabama forever,'' Siegelman tells voters on swings 
across the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent polls have shown a tight race, with enough undecided  
voters to give either side a victory -- a change from the summer, 
when polls showed the lottery favored by more than 60 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Lottery supporters outspent opponents 3-1, but church ministers  
have crossed denominational lines to preach against the ballot 
measure. Nothing else has so united the state's ministry, said the 
Rev. Joe Bob Mizell of the Alabama Baptist Convention. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even the abortion issue -- the sanctity of human life -- has not  
come as close to bringing denominations together,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Jim Bennett is predicting nearly 60 percent  
turnout, which would eclipse the 1998 governor's race and set a 
record for a ballot with no state or national offices up for grabs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've never had one this controversial before. There is a lot  
of emotional feeling in the lottery election that will bring out 
lots of voters on both sides,'' Bennett said. 
</P>
<P>
	Siegelman, a Democrat, handily defeated Republican incumbent Fob  
James last year by promising to copy Georgia's lottery and use an 
estimated $150 million a year in proceeds to fund free college 
tuition, purchase computers for every school and start a voluntary 
pre-kindergarten program. 
</P>
<P>
	The Legislature quickly approved his proposal and sent it to  
voters for a statewide referendum. It must receive a majority to 
pass. 
</P>
<P>
	Siegelman's effort has been dogged, however, by a scandal over  
the fixing of traffic tickets for friends of state officials. The 
state police director was forced to resign, and three of 
Siegelman's aides have been suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics warn that the scandal should leave voters wary about how  
the lottery would be run. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people understand what is going on here,'' Siegelman  
responded. ``They can separate this ticket-fixing stuff from the 
future of the children of this state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In South Carolina, a Nov. 2 referendum that would either ban  
video gambling or secure its legal standing has also unified 
religious groups in opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	In that battle, Gov. Jim Hodges hasn't campaigned for either  
side, despite the video gambling industry's significant help in 
defeating his predecessor, who tried to outlaw the games. Hodges 
has only said he will vote to ban the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Video gambling became legal in South Carolina through a  
little-noticed legislative amendment in 1986. Now there are 33,000 
machines across the state, and opponents claim it destroys families 
and exploits the poor. 
</P>
<P>
	Video operators claim the tax revenue their industry brings in  
helps fund education and can help eliminate a much-disliked car 
property tax. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
