<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hispanics Groom Talent for Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- With predictions that Hispanics will become the  
largest U.S. minority early in the next millennium, their leaders 
are looking to groom young talent to add political clout to the 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, as many as 8,000 people -- most of them between the  
ages of 18 and 34 -- are gathering in Chicago for the U.S. Hispanic 
Leadership Conference, which runs through Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people are afraid of change and some people are afraid of  
Latino progress. But Americans have nothing to be afraid of,'' 
former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros said Friday during a speech 
before thousands of high school students. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love this country,'' he said. ``We don't want to hurt it; we  
only want to help it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The numbers are clear -- if not a bit astounding.  
</P>
<P>
	Hispanics make up about 11 percent of the U.S. population -- half  
of them younger than age 20. That means that by 2050, one out of 
every four Americans will be of Hispanic descent, according to U.S. 
Census estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros told the students that such numbers place a great deal  
of responsibility on them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not want us to be a poor, hostile, angry, uneducated  
population in America. ... You can be the ones to break the 
pattern,'' he said. ``Can you do it?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In response, the students broke into uproarious applause.  
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros was one of many Hispanic leaders who encouraged  
conference attendees to go to college, register to vote and 
organize politically -- all goals backed up at the conference by 
workshops and a college and job fair. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to keep people accountable,'' said Cisneros, who now  
heads Univision, a major Spanish-language television network. ``We 
also, from time to time, have to defend ourselves when people come 
after us just because we are Latino.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Cisneros, officials attending the conference  
included everyone from Aida Alvarez, head of the U.S. Small 
Business Administration, to Raymond Anrecio, a manager at General 
Motors' Public Policy Institute. President Clinton was scheduled to 
speak at the conference Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being here, I feel everyone is a role model. All of them give  
me good goals,'' said Davina Gonzalez, an 18-year-old high school 
senior from Santa Ana, Calif., who was one of many to swarm 
Cisneros to get photos or autographs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez -- who wants to be a child psychologist and made her  
first plane trip to take part in the conference -- said being chosen 
to participate was inspiring. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes me very proud. It makes me feel like I will be able  
to be happy -- to live in a nice house with a yard, to have a family 
and to be able to buy them things they need,'' she said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
