<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NatWest Chief Executive Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The hostile takeover bid of National Westminster  
Bank PLC's by the Bank of Scotland has resulted in the resignation 
of Natwest's chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest said Friday that Derek Wanless' departure was part of  
wider boardroom shakeup that was a direct response to the Scottish 
bank's $34.4 billion bid, launched last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Against the background of an unsolicited and hostile bid from  
the Bank of Scotland, the board has decided to restructure the 
senior management team to place the bank in the best possible 
position to deal with this unwelcome offer,'' NatWest said in a 
statement to the London stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Sir David Rowland, currently NatWest chairman, will take on the  
additional role of group chief executive, the company said, and Ron 
Sandler, formerly chief executive of Lloyds of London, has been 
appointed chief operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes take effect immediately, NatWest said.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, Natwest dropped its controversial offer to  
buy British life insurance firm Legal &AMP; General Group PLC. The Bank 
of Scotland cited the Legal &AMP; General offer as proof that NatWest 
was straying outside its core banking business. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland made its offer for NatWest, a rival more than  
twice its size, on Sept. 24. NatWest quickly rejected the bid. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
