<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mitsubishi, Volvo Join Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's Mitsubishi Motors Corp. and Sweden's Volvo  
AB are forging stronger ties in an effort to become a more 
formidable force in the global market for trucks and buses. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Mitsubishi still needs to resolve a bigger  
problem: its passenger car business. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement announced Friday, Volvo will buy a 5 percent  
stake in Mitsubishi for $270 million. Mitsubishi will buy up to 5 
percent of Volvo by the end of 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese automaker also plans to make its truck and bus  
operations a new subsidiary by 2001, with Volvo taking a stake of 
up to 19.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Details of the new subsidiary are still being worked out, and  
Volvo has not said whether it will contribute any truck- or 
bus-making operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined production and sales of trucks and buses by  
Mitsubishi, Volvo and Scania AB -- a Swedish truckmaker Volvo is 
acquiring -- will surpass that of the current world leader 
DaimlerChrysler, according to Mitsubishi. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is part of a wave of increasing foreign involvement in  
Japan's auto sector, which is striving to become more globally 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Mitsubishi posted a profit for the fiscal year ended  
March 31 in contrast to a loss the previous fiscal year, its car 
sales have not picked up. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsuyoshi Mochimaru, auto analyst with Dresdner Kleinwort Benson  
in Tokyo, said the Volvo-Mitsubishi alliance fails to address 
Mitsubishi's problems with car sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mitsubishi's outstanding problem is in passenger cars, not  
trucks,'' Mochimaru said. ``There are way too many unprofitable 
models.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Motor Co. bought Volvo's passenger car division earlier  
this year. Rich from that sale, Volvo acquired a majority share in 
rival truckmaker Scania, although that merger still needs the 
approval of the European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi said it would benefit from the new alliance because  
the two automakers will be able to exchange technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope that this will make us more competitive at a time when  
severe demands from the world's consumers are expected in 
technology, in ecology and safety,'' company spokesman Noriaki 
Okoshi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Without ruling it out, Volvo Chief Executive Leif Johansson said  
there was no plan to acquire all of the new Mitsubishi trucks and 
bus company. ``A 20 percent share is large in Japanese terms for a 
foreign owner,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of Volvo Trucks, Karl Erling Trogen, said that  
including Scania in the cooperation with Mitsubishi is a 
possibility and that he could see potential in such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	The two automakers have already been cooperating in their truck  
business. Starting last year, the Mitsubishi Canter, a small truck, 
has been sold through Volvo outlets in England, France and Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	They have also been studying the possibility of developing  
medium-sized trucks together as well as of using Volvo parts in 
Mitsubishi large trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	``This agreement strengthens this cooperation further and  
creates possibilities for more cooperative ventures,'' Johansson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi Motors President Katsuhiko Kawasoe said the alliance  
is complementary, because Mitsubishi is strong for small- and 
mid-sized trucks in Asia while Volvo leads the European, North 
American and South American markets with its heavy trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	After the new share issue, Volvo will be the third-biggest  
shareholder in Mitsubishi Motors, after Mitsubishi Heavy Industries 
and Mitsubishi Corp. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
