<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Gains vs. Euro and Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar gained ground against the euro and  
the yen Friday, reacting to a rally in U.S. stocks and a potential 
lack of harmony within the European Economic Union. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0622, down  
from $1.0710 late Wednesday while the British pound fell to $1.6520 
from $1.6523. The dollar rose to 107.56 Japanese yen from 107.49 
yen late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose against the euro in early trading in response to  
comments from Dutch Central Bank President Nout Wellink, who said 
his country would have raised interest rates Thursday if the 
Netherlands weren't part of the EEU. 
</P>
<P>
	Wellink spoke shortly after the European Central Bank left its  
key borrowing rate unchanged at 2.5 percent on Thursday. The 
central bank's actions govern monetary policy for the 11 nations 
that have adopted the single currency known as the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement ``is an indication that there's no longer harmony  
within the euro zone,'' said Hillel Waxman, chief currency trader 
at Bank Leumi in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	A big gain in the U.S. stock markets, where the Dow industrials  
had its biggest weekly point gain in three months, helped increase 
interest in the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	A drop in oil prices and a mixed reading from a U.S. government  
report on unemployment also cooled some inflation jitters that have 
plagued American markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported that employers cut their payrolls  
by 8,000 jobs in September, the first drop since January 1996. 
Analysts had expected companies to add 220,000 jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, wage pressures rose in September despite the loss of  
jobs. Average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures, 
grew by 0.5 percent to $13.37 in September, much sharper than the 
0.2 percent increase in August. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department also said the nation's unemployment rate  
was unchanged at 4.2 percent in September, a 29-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	The report had been keenly awaited because the Federal Reserve  
said earlier this week it is prepared to raise interest rates for a 
third time this year if inflationary pressures grow. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were ``befuddled'' but eventually emboldened with the  
report, Waxman said. The inflationary influence of rising wages had 
to be balanced against a drop in jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the stock market goes up, ``that always puts steam in  
the dollar,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5022 Swiss francs on Thursday,  
up from 1.4872 Wednesday, and 1.4715 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4714. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8412  
German marks, up from 1.8259; 6.1752 French francs, up from 6.1239; 
and 1,822.80 Italian lire, up from 1,807.77. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
