<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wallace Looking for Win No. 50 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Milestones are hard to come by for Roger  
Penske's teams these days. 
</P>
<P>
	In CART, his team has been stuck on 99 victories since midway  
through the 1997 season. For NASCAR Winston Cup driver Rusty 
Wallace, it's No. 50 that has been illusive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm starting to think that No. 50 is jinxing me,'' said  
Wallace, who would like nothing better than to get Penske Racing 
South back to victory lane Sunday in the UAW-GM 500 at Lowe's Motor 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	The CART team is making major changes for 2000, with new drivers  
-- Gil de Ferran and Greg Moore -- as well as a new chassis and 
possibly a change of engine manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't need that kind of change in NASCAR,'' Penske said.  
``We're close there. We think we've got what we need to win for 
Rusty in Winston Cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 43-year-old Wallace, one of the top stars in NASCAR's  
Winston Cup series since taking Rookie of the Year honors in 1984, 
has only one victory each of the past two seasons, after piling up 
25 in the four previous years. 
</P>
<P>
	He won No. 49 in April, winning from the pole in Bristol, Tenn.  
Since then, his best finish has been third in August on the road 
course in Watkins Glen, N.Y., and Wallace is coming off a 
fourth-place finish last Sunday in Martinsville, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	To help in Wallace's quest for another victory, the team has  
gone back to building its own chassis -- and is debuting one this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	This one was built specifically for high-banked 1 1/2- or 2-mile  
ovals. Penske also has another new one ready for the race on the 
one-mile oval in Phoenix and a third for the inaugural race at 
Homestead's almost-flat 1 1/2-mile oval. 
</P>
<P>
	``This should help because I think we lost our way a little  
bit,'' Wallace said. ``With the other cars, we didn't have a base 
to work from in our handling. When you've got a great-handling car, 
you bring that same set-up back and you work on it a little bit. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we've been bringing different chassis with different  
setups to the racetracks, and our base has been completely gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace got off on the right foot Wednesday, putting the team's  
No. 2 Ford Taurus second in the 43-car lineup, right alongside the 
Pontiac of pole-winner Bobby Labonte. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody has a good outlook when you qualify good and  
get a good place to pit,'' Wallace said. ``Your team morale is real 
high and it keeps a smile on your face all week long. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're sitting there 30th, and you've got to go qualify the  
next day, you're worried about how you're going to run and stuff 
like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no Winston Cup activity on the 1 1/2-mile speedway oval  
on Friday, but the teams will get one hour of practice today, 
following the conclusion of the All Pro Auto Parts 300 Busch Series 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Always at Charlotte, it's a week-long process and it's a lot  
of fun,'' Wallace said. ``But, in a way, I wish we would get here 
on Friday and run Friday, Saturday and Sunday, like we do almost 
everywhere else.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
