<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capitals 3, Sabres 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Alexei Tezikov scored the game-winner with  
a goal similar to the controversial play that decided last season's 
Stanley Cup championship, giving Washington a 3-2 victory over 
Buffalo on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	In Buffalo's first home game since Brett Hull's controversial  
goal in triple overtime of Game 6 last season gave the Dallas Stars 
the Stanley Cup, the winner again came with an attacking player in 
the crease. 
</P>
<P>
	This time the rules allowed him to be there, but Sabres  
goaltender Dominik Hasek insisted that Capitals forward Jaroslav 
Svejkovsky interfered with him on the power-play goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Bondra and Jan Bulis also scored for Washington (1-1), and  
goaltender Olaf Kolzig made 26 saves. Wayne Primeau and Brian 
Campbell scored for the Sabres, who are still looking for their 
first win after a season-opening 2-0 loss to Detroit in which Hasek 
made 42 saves. 
</P>
<P>
	Tezikov, traded by Buffalo to Washington for Joe Juneau last  
March, scored the game-winner midway through the second period. The 
goal, which would have been reviewed last season, rattled in off 
the post. 
</P>
<P>
	Standing in the front of the same goal where Hull scored his  
Cup-clincher with a skate in the crease, Hasek slammed his glove 
against the post and argued that Capitals forward Svejkovsky 
interfered with him on the play. 
</P>
<P>
	A change in the rules prompted by Hull's goal allows an  
attacking player to be in the crease when a goal is scored as long 
as the goalie is not interfered with. Svejkovsky stood next to 
Hasek on the play but did not appear to touch the goaltender. 
</P>
<P>
	Tezikov's goal would have been reviewed last year. Under this  
season's rules, on-ice referees make the calls and there are no 
video replays to decide a man-in-the-crease situation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres scored first when Primeau knocked in a loose puck  
during a scramble in front of Kolzig at 5:56 of the first period. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Bondra tied it at 14:19 on a five-on-three when he batted  
in Curtis Brown's giveaway. Olaf Kolzig made 10 saves in the first 
and robbed Michael Peca in front with 2:06 left. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek made 25 saves but only three in the third. His 12 saves in  
the first included big stops with 1:24 on Konowalchuk and Bulis. 
</P>
<P>
	Bulis, a native of Hasek's hometown of Pardubice, Czech  
Republic, put the Capitals up 2-1 at 5:10 of the second period, 
with a slap shot that trickled in between Hasek and the near-side 
post. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell tied it at 7:37 of the second, pushing in Brian  
Holzinger's rebound, and Tezikov put Washington back in front, 3-2, 
with the Capitals' second power-play goal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 08:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FSU Moves Forward Without Warrick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- The loss of wide receivers Peter  
Warrick and Laveranues Coles, both arrested in a department store 
theft scam, will not change Florida State's game plan for Miami 
Saturday, but it will mean a new focus for the top-ranked 
Seminoles. 
</P>
<P>
	``We lost a lot of firepower,'' coach Bobby Bowden said. ``Now  
we find out if we have a team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A leading candidate for the Heisman Trophy, Warrick was  
indefinitely suspended and Coles kicked off the team because he had 
a record of prior legal and academic trouble. Warrick will miss at 
least the game against No. 19 Miami and possibly the rest of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick was Florida State's offensive leader, averaging 15.5  
yards every time he touched the ball during his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Those touches this year included 36 catches for 508 yards and  
seven touchdowns -- four receiving, two running and one on a punt 
return. He also has passed for a touchdown and ranks 12th 
nationally with 16.2 yards per punt return. 
</P>
<P>
	It will take more than one player to replace him. Little-used  
Germaine Stringer, along with Marvin Minnis, who missed the season 
opener because of an injury, will share time at Warrick's flanker 
position. Cornerback Reggie Durden will get more action returning 
punts, a duty he shared with Warrick. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles was the team's fastest player, clocked at 4.2 seconds in  
the 40-yard dash. He had 12 catches this season for 179 yards and 
one touchdown after being suspended in the opener for missing a 
final exam during the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Morgan will replace Coles at split end. Florida State  
substitutes often at nearly every position and has several 
experienced backups at receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time for a new star to be born,'' quarterback Chris  
Weinke said. ``We're not changing our game plan. We're not changing 
anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Well, maybe one thing, Bowden said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can't run the reverse pass,'' he said, referring to a play  
that has Warrick, a former high school quarterback, throwing the 
ball. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrests of Warrick and Coles have overshadowed an intense  
rivalry between Florida State (5-0) and Miami (2-2), smarting from 
identical 27-23 losses to No. 2 Penn State and No. 16 East 
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden once lamented that the words ``he played Miami'' would be  
carved on his tombstone because losses to the Hurricanes might have 
cost him at least one national championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seminoles, however, have had the better of the rivalry in  
recent years, winning four straight from the Hurricanes. Florida 
State also will be trying to extend a 44-game unbeaten streak at 
Doak Campbell Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The last home loss was to Miami in 1991. It was the the famous  
``wide right'' game the Hurricanes won 17-16 when Seminoles walk-on 
Gerry Thomas missed a 34-yard field goal by inches with 25 seconds 
left. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami coach Butch Davis plans no changes because of the absences  
of Warrick and Coles, saying he was sure Florida State had capable 
replacements. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of his players, however, were disappointed Warrick and  
Coles would not be playing. Tight end Bubba Franks said he wished 
they would be in the lineup ``so nobody will have any excuses when 
we win.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
