<DOCNO> APW19991008.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 06:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Exec on Payroll After Conviction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- A General Motors marketing executive was kept on  
the payroll nearly two years after he pleaded guilty to defrauding 
a Little Caesars subsidiary, though he says he didn't tell GM about 
the conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Dean Rotondo, 38, left GM on Oct. 1.  
</P>
<P>
	Court records show that Oakland County prosecutors charged  
Rotondo and his associate, former brother-in-law Adalgiso ``Nick'' 
Mancini, in February 1997 with four counts each of false pretenses. 
</P>
<P>
	They were accused of generating false purchase orders totaling  
$168,000 from Blue Line Distributing, a Farmington Hills company 
that delivers pizza dough and other supplies to Little Caesars 
franchisees. 
</P>
<P>
	Rotondo, GM's director of marketing operations, pleaded guilty  
in November 1997. He was sentenced to three years probation. 
</P>
<P>
	GM spokesman Terry Sullivan declined to say whether Rotondo  
resigned or was fired. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't get into that,'' Sullivan told The Oakland Press for  
a Friday story. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which has an ethics policy, was unaware of the  
case, an official said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure this matter is being taken very seriously. This is a  
very serious issue and we understand that,'' a senior GM official 
told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Rotondo said he decided that it was time to leave GM.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was an unfortunate situation that happened. I had tried to  
do the right thing by cooperating with the authorities and I made 
full restitution,'' said Rotondo, who acknowledged keeping GM in 
the dark about his legal difficulties. 
</P>
<P>
	According to prosecutors, Mancini, who was a buyer for Blue  
Line, generated 11 phony purchase orders to buy kiosks from 
Pinnacle Production, a Bloomfield Hills company created by 
Rotondo's cousin but later turned over to Rotondo. 
</P>
<P>
	The kiosks were to be shipped to a third company. An audit of  
the Blue Line account showed that $168,000 had gone out for kiosks 
that never appeared. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
