<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> E. Timor Refugees Return to Capial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Tears of joy and sorrow cascaded down  
the cheeks of East Timorese refugees on Friday as they returned to 
their ravaged capital -- their delight to be home tempered by the 
knowledge that militias were still threatening thousands of others 
still stuck in Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	The 166 refugees arrived from West Timor, where refugee camps  
house an estimated 256,000 people who fled violence unleashed by 
pro-Indonesian militias after East Timorese voted overwhelmingly on 
Aug. 30 to break away from Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	Their return on two chartered U.N. flights from  
Indonesia-controlled West Timor set off a wild celebration in Dili, 
East Timor's capital, where charred buildings still stand as grim 
reminders of the recent chaos. 
</P>
<P>
	People raced through the city to welcome the refugees, some of  
whom kissed the ground as they got off the planes. Others simply 
wept or hugged the priests and nuns who greeted them at the 
airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Joao da Silva waited in a soccer field, looking for his  
brother's family. He bounded up to his sister-in-law and her 
children after they passed through a makeshift clinic, then hugged 
his brother tightly. 
</P>
<P>
	There were also tales of woe. One teen-age girl and her younger  
brother were told their grandmother had died while they were away. 
They leaned against a wall and wept. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's strong emotions were tempered, however, by fear for the  
refugees who remained behind. 
</P>
<P>
	``The militias are still hunting pro-independence people in the  
camps,'' said Amando Sarmento, 29, who arrived on the second flight 
Friday with 11 relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations planned to charter two flights a day to  
return refugees until arrangements could be made to ship people by 
sea. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not known yet how many East Timorese were killed by the  
militias, which, backed by parts of the Indonesian army, went on a 
spree of looting, killing and burning after the U.N.-backed vote. 
</P>
<P>
	But hundreds of thousands of East Timorese were driven from  
their homes, some to West Timor and many more into the nearby 
hills. 
</P>
<P>
	The commander of the international peacekeeping force,  
Australian Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, was to have his first meeting 
late Friday with Matan Ruak, head of the pro-independence Falintil 
guerrillas who have fought Indonesian rule since the 1975 invasion 
of East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	Falintil has agreed with the peacekeepers' demand to disarm, but  
refused to do so until the 1,400 remaining Indonesian soldiers have 
left. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Indonesian troops have gone, but more than 1,000 are to  
remain until the independence vote is endorsed by Indonesia's 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Several hundred people flocked to Dili's port on Friday,  
shouting ``Get out of our country, you scum!'' as Indonesian troops 
loaded trucks onto a ship. 
</P>
<P>
	Cosgrove has also sent a second letter to the Indonesian  
military, insisting that four officers be available to work on the 
investigation into the slaying of Dutch journalist Sander Thoenes. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoenes, who worked for The Financial Times and The Christian  
Science Monitor, was shot and killed in Dili, allegedly by men in 
Indonesian uniforms, the day after the peacekeeping force landed on 
Sept. 20. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
