<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Top Horses To Face New Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lemon Drop Kid and Silverbulletday will take on  
new challenges Sunday at Belmont Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kid, who moved into the 3-year-old championship picture by  
adding a victory in the Travers to his win in the Belmont Stakes, 
will make his debut against older horses in the 1 1/4-mile Jockey Club 
Gold Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday, a 3-year-old filly who has won eight of nine  
starts this year and 14 of 16 career outings, will race for the 
first time against older fillies and mares in the 1 1/8-mile Beldame. 
</P>
<P>
	``Always respect your elders,'' said Scotty Schulhofer, trainer  
of Lemon Drop Kid. 
</P>
<P>
	Especially when some of those elders are 5-year-old Behrens,  
winner of four of his last five starts, including two Grade I 
stakes; 4-year-old Almutawakel, winner of the Dubai World Cup and 
second last month in the Woodward at Belmont, and 7-year-old River 
Keen, second in Pacific Classic at Del Mar and winner of the 
Woodward. 
</P>
<P>
	``Behrens is probably at the top of those,'' Schulhofer said.  
``He's an excellent horse, and he's doing very well. I'm not 
confident I can beat him, but I'm sure going to try.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $1 million Gold Cup and $500,000 Beldame are two of three  
Grade I stakes Sunday at Belmont. The other is the $400,000 
Frizette for 2-year-old fillies. 
</P>
<P>
	In two Grade I stakes Saturday, More Than Ready, winner of five  
of six starts, and Hopeful winner High Yield are among seven 
2-year-olds in the $400,000 Champagne at 1 1-16 miles; and Val's 
Prince, the Man o'War winner, will meet seven rivals in the 
$600,000 Turf Classic over 1 1/2 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Also entered Friday for the Gold Cup, a weight-for-age stakes,  
were Back Ring Al, Catienus, Jack Grandi and two other 3-year-olds 
-- Stephen Got Even, third in the Woodward, and Vision and Verse, a 
close second to Lemon Drop Kid in the Belmont and Travers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any horse who wins the Belmont and the Travers and was the  
2-year-old he was has got to be a good horse,'' said Jim Bond, 
trainer of Behrens, whose four-race winning streak ended when he 
lost by a nose to Victory Gallop in the 1 1/8-mile Whitney Handicap. 
``But he has to run an A-plus race to beat older horses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 3-year-olds will carry 123 pounds, the others 126.  
</P>
<P>
	John Ward, trainer of Beldame starter Beautiful Pleasure, feels  
the same way about Silverbulletday's challenge to older fillies and 
mares. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like Silverbulletday has been running in the college  
ranks,'' he said. ``Now she's moving into the pros. I don't think 
Silverbulletday can make any mistakes and win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday's only defeat this year was a seventh against  
males in the 1 1/2-mile Belmont Stakes. She is trained by Bob Baffert, 
who also prepares River Keen. 
</P>
<P>
	Beautiful Pleasure, winner of the Personal Ensign, will be one  
of Silverbulletday's four rivals in the Beldame. The others are 
Catinca, winner of the 1 1-16-mile Ruffian at Belmont, and Rap and 
Dance and 3-year-old Queen's Word. The 3-year-olds will carry 119 
pounds, and rest 123. 
</P>
<P>
	Finder's Fee, winner the Matron last month at Belmont, will face  
four other juvenile fillies in the 1 1-16-mile Frizette. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
