<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't. Says Grain Glut Worsening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The stockpiles of grain that have kept  
commodity prices depressed for two years are growing, the 
government said Friday. That could mean another tough year for 
growers in 2000 and keep the cost of federal farm programs soaring. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's bumper crops will push the corn surplus to nearly 2  
billion bushels -- more than 20 percent of the nation's total 
production -- and boost wheat stocks to 987 million bushels, the 
Agriculture Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's expected to knock 10 cents off the price farmers get per  
bushel of corn, dropping it to $1.85, and a nickel off the price of 
wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall, we've still got big production in the United States,  
big production around the world, and you're going to have to see 
some change in weather or in the farm program to reduce supply,'' 
said Don Roose, president of U.S. Commodities Inc. of West Des 
Moines, Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Next week, the Senate is expected to send President Clinton an  
$8.7 billion package of emergency farm-income assistance and 
disaster relief, the second multibillion-dollar bailout package in 
as many years. 
</P>
<P>
	The way things stand, additional such assistance will likely be  
necessary in 2000, said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., 
who would like to change the farm program. 
</P>
<P>
	``The concept of so-called emergency funding is going to start  
wearing thin with nonagricultural senators and congressman,'' he 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	With the latest aid package, direct government payments to  
farmers are expected to reach $21 billion this year, eclipsing the 
old record of $17 billion in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Commodity prices collapsed in 1998 because of the financial  
crisis in Asia and Russia and strong crop production worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The Agriculture Department expects farm exports -- down $10  
billion this year from their record of just under $60 billion in 
1996 -- to improve only slightly next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Government price supports are just high enough to encourage  
farmers to continue planting crops already in surplus, but the 
subsidies aren't enough to keep many producers in business without 
other sources of income, said Howard Doster, an agricultural 
economist at Purdue University. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we grow another big crop (next year) and the Asian economy  
stays the way it is, the conditions could stay the way they are. 
But I still have hope for next year,'' said Nathan Johnson, who 
grows corn and soybeans near Lowry, Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	Drought and flooding have taken their toll on some crops,  
especially soybeans and cotton in the East and South, but USDA 
increased its forecast of this year's corn crop by 1 percent from 
last month because of higher-than-expected yields in the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	The department lowered its forecast of the cotton crop by 6  
percent and reduced its estimate for soybeans by 3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA said it expects soybean prices to be 20 cents a bushel  
higher than previously thought this year, reaching an average of $5 
a bushel, because of the decline in production. The government is 
not allowed to estimate cotton prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The drought started in the East and spread across portions of  
the Midwest and down across much of the South. It turned out to be 
a boon for some growers in the East. 
</P>
<P>
	New York is expected to harvest 1.2 million pounds of apples  
this year, up 160,000 pounds from last year, because the drought 
reduced insect and disease problems and September rains came in 
time to increase the size of the fruit. Production also is up in 
Pennsylvania and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Eastern grape crops also are better this year because of the dry  
weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, USDA says this year's orange crop will hit 12.1  
million tons, up 22 percent from last year when a freeze badly 
damaged California's production. Orange prices are unlikely to 
change much, however, because of low inventory and high demand for 
juice, said Andy LaVigne, chief executive officer of Florida Citrus 
Mutual. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
