<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Germans Offers $3.3B to Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Everyone says they want to get it over as  
quickly as possible. But that was one of the few things both sides 
agreed on when German negotiators and Nazi labor camp survivors met 
to settle compensation for wartime atrocities. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany offered Thursday to pay $3.3 billion to former slave  
laborers and other victims of Adolf Hitler's World War II regime, 
calling it ``a considerable amount.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives for survivors termed the offer ``shameful,''  
``an insult'' and ``disgusting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the offer ``represents a basis for serious discussion,''  
said the main U.S. negotiator, Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart E. 
Eizenstat. 
</P>
<P>
	Another round of talks is planned in several weeks in Bonn, with  
an eye toward completing an agreement by year's end and starting 
payments in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides noted that survivors are elderly and more are dying  
every day. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's money offer came on the closing day of a  
multinational meeting aimed at working out compensation for people 
who worked in forced or slave labor camps to the benefit of 
Hitler's war machine -- as well as other victims of the Nazi period. 
</P>
<P>
	German industry says the number of surviving forced and slave  
laborers is about 900,000; estimates from the other side are as 
high as 2.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	German envoy Otto Lambsdorff, who presented Germany's joint  
government and industry offer, said a new foundation would 
administer the funds. About a third of the money is from the 
government and two-thirds from German industry, negotiators said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an insult,'' Rudy Kennedy of London, whose mother, sister  
and father were killed in the Holocaust, said outside the State 
Department, which served as meeting host. 
</P>
<P>
	``The world will judge the morality of this offer and ... will  
condemn it,'' said Mel Weiss, an attorney for some survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	Lambsdorff acknowledged that the money ``is not enough to help  
all those who feel they suffered during that period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he added: ``It is not easy to make the case to German  
citizens'' for such payments while they are suffering cutbacks in 
social services and other financial problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	German diplomats accompanying Lambsdorff also stressed that the  
new money comes on top of more than $55 billion in compensation 
that Germany already has paid for various Holocaust-related crimes 
since 1949. 
</P>
<P>
	Lambsdorff said 20 companies beyond the 16 originally sued in  
the United States had agreed to contribute to the foundation. He 
said the foundation would receive claims not only against 
contributing companies, but against any wartime German company, 
even if it no longer exists. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies that have been sued in the United States on forced  
labor and related claims include Bayer pharmaceuticals, carmakers 
DaimlerChrysler and Ford Motor Co. and chemical conglomerate 
Hoechst AG. Names of all companies that have pledged contributions 
have not been publicly released. 
</P>
<P>
	The bulk of the money in the new offer, about $2.3 billion,  
would go to slave and forced laborers, Lambsdorff said, with slave 
laborers getting $5,500 each. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department says an estimated 12 million workers were  
forced to work in German industry and agriculture during World War 
II. Some produced materials for the war, and some took over jobs 
from German men, freeing them to fight. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the United States and Germany, the other  
countries involved in the negotiations are Israel, Poland, Belarus, 
Ukraine, Russia and the Czech Republic. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
