<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Jersey Pushes for Tycoon's Take </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Former tycoon Robert E. Brennan has failed  
to pay a penny of the $45 million he owes New Jersey, so the state 
is asking a judge for a cut of his income, contending he is living 
in luxury. 
</P>
<P>
	A hearing on the state's motion is scheduled today before State  
Superior Court Judge Philip M. Freedman, who shepherded the June 
settlement of stock fraud charges against Brennan and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan avoided a trial by agreeing to pay $45 million and  
accepting a lifetime ban on participating in the securities 
industry in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan, 56, a longtime New Jersey resident now living in Juno  
Beach, Fla., did not return a message left Thursday at Due Process 
Golf Club. 
</P>
<P>
	The club is in Colts Neck, N.J., and is operated by Pirates  
Associates, which pays Brennan $388,000 a year in consulting fees, 
according to court papers filed Monday by the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Divorced and with three adult children, Brennan has ``few  
expenses other than travel and entertainment,'' and has not let 
bankruptcy cramp his style, the state contended. 
</P>
<P>
	He ``pays no rent, travels by chauffeur driven limousine, owns  
no property, pays no salaries, travels abroad with some degree of 
regularity and appears to have no extraordinary expenses related to 
ill health or day to day living,'' the state argued. 
</P>
<P>
	It listed Brennan's ``lifestyle expenditures'' in June and July,  
which included $2,829.10 at a liquor store and more than $1,900 in 
fees at three golf courses. 
</P>
<P>
	The state contends that it could be entitled to Brennan's entire  
income, or just 25 percent, depending on which guidelines are used. 
</P>
<P>
	But even if the state collects $388,000 for 20 years -- the  
maximum period the debt is owed under state law -- it would reap 
just $7.76 million of the $45 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The state claims that since Brennan is not paid hourly, it is  
properly seeking an ``order to pay out of income.'' It is also 
seeking money from any personal bank accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The money is to compensate the investors state regulators  
believe Brennan swindled. In the settlement, Brennan denied 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan became nationally known in the 1980s through television  
commercials for his First Jersey Securities Inc. in which he 
stepped from a helicopter and told investors to ``come grow with 
us.'' The company has been inactive since 1987. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
