<DOCNO> APW19991008.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 17:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ito: Courts Need More Interpreters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The judge who presided over O.J. Simpson's  
criminal trial made a rare public appearance Friday to encourage 
support for his pet project -- bringing more court interpreters into 
a system populated by many minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge Lance Ito told an American Bar Association  
gathering on race and ethnicity that he has been working for six 
years to integrate more interpreters into the court system. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our court deals with 200 languages on a daily basis,'' Ito  
told the group, adding that census estimates show that in the year 
2000, some 40 million Americans will speak a language other than 
English. 
</P>
<P>
	There has been a lack of understanding of the widespread need  
for interpreters, particularly in federal immigration courts, which 
require interpreters only for the testimony of an immigrant but not 
for the entire proceeding, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal in the justice system is that any person who comes  
into the system who does not speak English will be in the same 
position as someone who does speak English,'' Ito said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ethnic bar associations have dropped the ball on this,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge opened his remarks with a joke: ``My claim to fame is  
not having tried a certain football player a number of years ago. 
It's that for the past six years I've chaired the court panel on 
interpreters.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
