<DOCNO> APW19991008.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 15:22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HMO Bill Faces Fight in Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly one in three House Republicans joined  
with Democrats to approve a controversial new right to sue health 
insurance plans, part of a wide-reaching patient protection bill. 
But in the Senate, the GOP has held together, and the legislation 
faces an uphill struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	As the issue heads to a conference committee, where lawmakers  
from both chambers will try to work out the differences, Democrats 
and their allies are hoping that Thursday's strong House vote will 
pressure the Senate to cave. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, backed by insurance and business groups, are  
counting on the Senate to hold the line. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see how Republicans can stand in the way of this kind  
of groundswell,'' said a hopeful Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., who 
led his party when the Senate debated the issue in July. ``The 
Senate flunked its test earlier in the year but we have a second 
chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Don Nickles, the No. 2 Republican in the Senate, vowed  
to stop many of the provisions passed by the House. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will work aggressively to ensure that this Congress does not  
pass any legislation that would cause a dramatic increase in health 
care costs (or) increase the number of uninsured,'' said Nickles, 
R-Okla. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest groups on both sides promised to keep up the pressure.  
</P>
<P>
	``The fight is not over,'' said Karen Ignagi, president of the  
American Association of Health Plans, the HMO trade group, which 
was intensely involved in the debate. 
</P>
<P>
	The House and Senate versions have two major differences. The  
Senate includes no new rights to file lawsuits. And many of the 
Senate provisions apply only to the 48 million Americans in health 
plans that fall under a 1974 federal benefits law. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're clearly miles apart,'' said Larry Levitt, an analyst  
at the Kaiser Family Foundation, an independent policy group in San 
Francisco. ``The Senate had plenty of opportunity in their debate 
to go as far as the House did and decided pretty forcefully not 
to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He suggested the Senate and the House might agree on many minor  
differences between their bills, and possibly how many people are 
covered. However, he said, ``The right to sue is still very 
tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, many issues that were contested only a year ago are now  
essentially givens. Democrats have won the most basic question: 
Whether there should be new federal regulations at all for health 
insurance companies, which are traditionally regulated by states. 
</P>
<P>
	And many of the patient protections found in both bills were  
once a source of much debate. 
</P>
<P>
	The House bill would guarantee access to reasonable emergency  
room care, give patients the right to see pediatricians and 
obstetricians without permission from primary care doctors, and 
require HMOs to pay for routine care associated with clinical 
trials. It would require HMOs to disclose a lot of information and 
let patients take their complaints to outside arbitrators. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill is nearly identical.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think mountains have been moved here,'' said Ron Pollack,  
president of Families USA, a liberal consumer group. Still, he 
said, ``It's far from clear we're going to end up with a bill 
that's enacted into law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's because the right to sue has overwhelmed all else. And no  
one is sure whether the 2000 election politics will stiffen each 
side's spine or encourage a compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert downplayed the differences.  
</P>
<P>
	``Ninety-five percent of that bill was stuff that I've been  
working on for years to try to get passed,'' Hastert, R-Ill., told 
reporters Friday in Topeka, Kan. He called the right-to-sue issue, 
which tangled his leadership team in knots for months, ``a little 
issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically what happened yesterday was a bipartisan issue that  
was passed on a bipartisan basis,'' Hastert said. ``We've taken a 
step forward.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
