<HEADLINE> Xerox Warns of Earnings Shortfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Shares of Xerox Corp. plunged 24 percent  
Friday after the company said its third-quarter earnings would fall 
due to increased pressure from competitors and lower productivity 
from its sales force. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox said it expects a 10 percent to 12 percent drop in  
earnings per share from 53 cents in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had been expecting Xerox to earn 58 cents a share for  
the three-month period ending Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's stock fell $10.25 to close at $32.50 a share as  
the most active issue on the New York Stock Exchange, with more 
than 46 million shares changing hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox announced in April that it was reorganizing its  
14,000-person sales force in a push to boost sales of ``bundled'' 
services to corporate customers, integrating fax machines, 
printers, copiers and personal computer software. The company said 
it planned to move its sales force away from geographical coverage 
toward coverage of specific industries. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just taken longer to implement and it's caused more  
disruption than we anticipated,'' said Xerox spokesman Judd 
Everhart. ``The disruption has an impact on their ability to get in 
front of our customers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox said third-quarter results were also hurt by economic  
weakness in Brazil, which was forced to devalue its currency 
earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue was also weaker than anticipated both in the United  
States and Europe, particularly in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The company plans to announce third quarter results on Oct. 18.  




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
