<HEADLINE> Puppy-Killing Mayor Won't Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILFORD, Ill. (AP) -- The mayor here has decided to stay on the  
job after all -- despite the public outcry that arose when he killed 
a beagle puppy named Snoopy with a shovel. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor James Cook, who faces an animal cruelty charge, had said  
he would resign Friday because of the hate mail and death threats 
he had received since the Aug. 22 incident. 
</P>
<P>
	But at a special village board meeting on Friday, Cook said many  
town residents had asked him to stay on as mayor of Milford, about 
90 miles south of Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook also said a legal defense fund had been started for him at  
a bank. He said the town support had ``renewed my faith in the 
basic goodness of our Milford community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cook said he struck the puppy with a shovel to shoo it away from  
workers who were building a grain bin at the elevator he manages in 
nearby Bryce. He said when he saw how badly he had injured the 
6-month-old dog, he felt the kindest thing would be to put it out 
of its misery. 
</P>
<P>
	The mother of the 6-year-old boy whose puppy Cook killed shook  
his hand after the meeting and said she had forgiven him. 
</P>
<P>
	``God forgives, so I will, too,'' said Christy Miller. ``It's  
been blown way out of proportion. When he gets death threats, 
that's not right. What he did was wrong, but he's paid too much for 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police reports indicate Cook paid the owners $150 as  
compensation to the family. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said her son still misses his dog.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a little boy,'' she said. ``He's still hurting, but he'll  
get over it in time.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
