<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 19:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Continental, Delta Raise Fares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Continental Airlines and Delta Airlines have both  
increased excursion fares requiring advance purchase by up to $20 
per round trip. Separately, American Airlines announced Friday it 
will join United Airlines in cutting commissions for travel agents, 
which also could lead to additional costs for travelers. 
</P>
<P>
	The ticket increases posted late Thursday by Houston-based  
Continental and matched Friday by Delta range generally from 3 to 7 
percent for a round trip ticket requiring seven, 14- or 21-day 
advance purchase. The increases don't apply to top-dollar business 
fares. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona-based America West Airlines also increased its fares,  
but it was unclear whether other large carriers would match 
Continental's move. Previous Continental-led fare hikes this year 
have collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	Repeated calls to Continental and America West were not  
returned. A Delta spokesman said the Atlanta-based carrier raised 
its fares ``to remain competitive'' with Continental. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas-based Southwest Airlines does not plan a fare hike, said  
spokeswoman Linda Rutherford. 
</P>
<P>
	United, the largest carrier, No. 2 American and Northwest said  
Friday they had not raised fares but declined to rule out 
increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Samuel Buttrick, an analyst with Paine Webber, said other  
airlines want to raise fares, partly to cover the rising cost of 
jet fuel, but could find reason to hold back. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only impediment I see (to an industry-wide fare increase)  
is a decision on the part of one or two other airlines to avoid 
simultaneously cutting commissions and raising fares,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the week, United Airlines cut the commission it will  
pay travel agents who sell its tickets from 8 percent to 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	American issued a statement saying it too was cutting the  
commissions and capping them at $50 per round trip ticket and $25 
for one-way tickets for domestic travel. American did not 
immediately return phone calls. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Parsons, editor of Bestfares.com, said a commission cut and  
fare increase would amount to double-dipping by airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Travel agents will start charging a processing fee because  
they can't survive on 5 percent. The fare increase is like a double 
whammy for air travelers,'' Parsons said. 
</P>
<P>
	David Stempler, president of the Air Travelers Association, said  
the commission cut is the airlines' response to customer demands 
for the lowest fares. 
</P>
<P>
	Stempler agreed that travel agents will start charging fees,  
``but the flip side is that people who weren't using travel agents 
were overpaying for something they weren't using.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
