<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Donald Eyes the White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Donald Trump is very, very rich. Which doesn't  
mean that his talk can't be cheap. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, he announced that he'd formed an exploratory  
committee to determine his viability as a presidential candidate 
for the Reform Party -- and would like to have Oprah Winfrey as a 
running mate, although he hasn't discussed it with her. But in the 
past, the billionaire developer's done a lot of talking about a lot 
of things -- remember the United States Football League? 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, Trump has amassed a $1.6 billion fortune through savvy  
projects like the Grand Hyatt Hotel, Trump Tower and his Atlantic 
City casinos. But Trump occasionally has -- how to say this? -- made 
announcements that didn't amount to much. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many news-making projects exist only in his imagination,''  
read the headline on a November 1996 Trump article in the New York 
Post. 
</P>
<P>
	Take 1990, when Trump floated word that he might build a  
125-story tower -- the world's largest -- on the Los Angeles site of 
the old Ambassador Hotel. Simultaneously, city officials were 
knocking down Trump's plans for a similar edifice in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics howled that Trump was playing one city against the  
other. Trump was unmoved -- the massive building ``will only go to 
one,'' he promised. 
</P>
<P>
	It went to neither.  
</P>
<P>
	After a protracted legal battle, Trump sold his stake in the Los  
Angeles property without building anything. His Manhattan plans for 
a 150-story tower, announced in 1985, were wildly downscaled; 
construction on that West Side project continues today. Now absent 
the Television City office tower, the first of the apartment 
buildings in the complex are being occupied. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, the Trump Organization announced plans for a possible  
Trump Tower Moscow. They're still waiting, comrade. Trump made 
similar comments about Trump Towers in Tokyo and Sao Paolo; none 
materialized. 
</P>
<P>
	Ditto an announced 1994 foray into Las Vegas. Five years later,  
Trump's casino holdings remain strictly in Atlantic City, N.J. 
Ditto a 1992 proposal for a high-tech theme park in the New Jersey 
Meadowlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics point to a common theme: publicity, spelled T-R-U-M-P.  
Trump creates headlines to feed a massive ego, they carp. And Trump 
certainly has enjoyed the attention. 
</P>
<P>
	In March 1991, for example, Trump stood outside a Manhattan  
courthouse waving a $10 million check and announcing that his 
divorce from wife Ivana was final. He made all the papers, but the 
divorce wasn't finalized until more than two years later. 
</P>
<P>
	In October 1989, Trump made an unsolicited takeover offer of $7  
billion for AMR Corp., the parent of American Airlines. Eleven days 
after the bid created headlines, Trump withdrew it -- before it was 
ever formally presented to stockholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Publicity is always good, but candidate Trump would bring other  
things to the table. 
</P>
<P>
	He has experience with debt; he wrote ``Trump: The Art of the  
Comeback,'' a whole book about his return from a $975 million 
financial black hole. 
</P>
<P>
	He's quite the spin doctor; when a jury awarded the USFL just $1  
in its $1.3 billion lawsuit against the NFL, New Jersey Generals 
owner Trump called it ``a great moral victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trump also had predicted a USFL-NFL super-duper bowl by 1990,  
perhaps played in the modestly named Trump Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Oh, well.  
</P>
<P>
	While politicians and unfulfilled promises are not strange  
bedfellows, Trump has at least one more political drawback: his 
germ-phobia keeps him from shaking hands, much less kissing babies. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the curses of American society is the simple act of  
shaking hands,'' the potential politico wrote in his ``Comeback'' 
book. ``I happen to be a clean-hands freak.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 22:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Mailings Net Many Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- ``This may be the longest shot of my life,''  
former basketball star Bill Bradley writes to prospective 
contributors. ``But I've had some experience making long shots, and 
I know that this one is within my abilities -- as long as I have 
your help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of people are giving Bradley that help -- so many, in  
fact, that he is raising $4 for every $1 he spends on direct mail 
in his bid for the Democratic presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	For $237,000 worth of mailings, he has raised more than $1  
million in campaign contributions. That's an unusually high success 
rate that helped him take in more money than Vice President Al Gore 
during the last three months. 
</P>
<P>
	Candidates often lose money when they send out letters in search  
of contributions, considering it an investment in building a donor 
list they can use again and again. In presidential elections, such 
a list is doubly valuable because the government will match 
contributions of $250 or less. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, candidates have to send out thousands of solicitations  
just to find a few donors; more than 95 percent of those who 
receive requests for donations simply throw the letter away. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why list building and list development and that fund  
raising is so expensive,'' fund-raising consultant Keith Davis 
said. ``The return is so low.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Bradley has defied the odds, according to the fund-raising  
figures released by his campaign. He has collected an estimated 
$6.7 million during the last three months, to $6.5 million for 
Gore, and has found more than 25,000 people willing to give to his 
campaign for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Contributors responded to letters like this one from Bradley,  
which included a veiled reference to Gore: 
</P>
<P>
	``I offer a life experience that reaches well beyond the  
corridors of Washington and the trappings of privilege. Voters see 
a candidate who left Washington by choice after 18 years, 
determined to work on the challenges facing our society, and to 
address them in a meaningful way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the $1 million in direct mail contributions, Bradley has  
raised $760,000 through his campaign Web site. Earlier this year, 
he got the Federal Election Commission's approval for donations 
made by credit card -- the only way someone can contribute through 
the Internet -- to be eligible for federal matching funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shows there is a steadily growing level of grass-roots  
support for Bill Bradley,'' campaign spokesman Tony Wyche said. 
</P>
<P>
	And Bradley is already asking his new friends to give again.  
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to people who already gave, he predicted the  
nomination in both parties may be wrapped up by March, a timetable 
he said he can accept. ``But I must have your financial help now,'' 
he wrote. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
