<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals Give La Russa 2-Year Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Tony La Russa will be minding the St. Louis  
Cardinals' dugout for at least another two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals announced Friday afternoon that the club has  
extended La Russa's contract through the 2001 season. The former 
Oakland A's and Chicago White Sox manager joined the Cardinals in 
1996. He's posted a 319-and-328 record with St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased to announce that Tony will remain the  
Cardinals' manager into the next century,'' Cardinals general 
manager Walt Jocketty said. ``I know that Tony wants nothing more 
than to reward the Cardinals' fans for their unmatched support 
which has led to record attendance totals each of the past two 
seasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This year, La Russa became the eleventh winningest manager of  
all time. He leads all active major league managers with 1,639 
wins. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals finished 11 games below .500 this year, 75-86,  
fourth place in the NL Central and 21 1/2 games behind first-place 
Houston. The team lost starting pitcher Matt Morris during spring 
training with an arm injury and another starter, Donovan Osborne, 
early in the season. Outfielder Eric Davis was lost for the season 
with an injury suffered making a diving catch to preserve rookie 
Jose Jiminez's no-hitter on June 25. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's last appearance in the post-season came in La Russa's  
first year in St. Louis. The Cardinals lost the 1996 NLCS to 
Atlanta in seven games. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Tony) won't be satisfied until he can get the Cardinals back  
to the post-season,'' Jocketty said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
