<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 08:47:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> King Abdullah Carries Iraqi Message </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- King Abdullah of Jordan, in a weeklong U.S.  
visit, will ask for duty-free access to American markets and more 
weapons while backing Israeli-Arab peace accords. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was bringing a message from Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein  
to President Clinton, but administration officals said they doubted 
it would be a serious overture. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdullah, stepping smoothly into the shoes of his late father,  
King Hussein, is projecting Jordan as a moderate Arab regime that 
is aligning itself with peace moves as beneficial to his kingdom 
and the region at large. 
</P>
<P>
	He was pressing his case for a bigger share of American markets  
with Commerce Secretary William Daley today and will see President 
Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright next Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 37-year-old king also hopes to get a promised $300 million  
financial aid package that Congress has so far refused to approve. 
The aid was promised to Jordan as part of last year's Wye River 
peace accord in exchange for Hussein's diplomatic efforts to 
promote an Israeli pullback on the West Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional skepticism based on Jordan's support for Iraq in  
the Persian Gulf War diminished in a spirited campaign by his 
father to support U.S. diplomacy in the Middle East. The cut in new 
aid to Jordan more likely reflects widespread reservations with 
foreign aid, generally, on Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	Over a three-day weekend, the king intends to enjoy autumn in  
New England and attend the wedding of a private school classmate. 
His father also usually mixed business with pleasure on trips here. 
</P>
<P>
	Before taking off for the United States, Abdullah told Jordanian  
reporters he was carrying a message from to Clinton from Saddam 
Hussein. He declined to provide details. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't comment on that, but I have a message to pass on,''  
Abdullah was quoted as saying by Jordanian newspapers Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials doubted Iraq would make a serious offer  
to the United States through Abdullah. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said this week that  
the Iraqis regularly seek talks with U.S. officials but that the 
United States is not interested as long as Iraq remains in 
violation of U.N. Security Council resolutions. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Arab newspaper Al-Hayat, the message promises  
major political reforms in Iraq, offers to stop threatening Israel, 
proposes unconditional talks with the United States and offers 
assurances Iraq will play an effective role in Middle East peace 
process. 
</P>
<P>
	On his last visit here, in July, the king pledged economic and  
bureaucratic reform at home as well as a drive against corruption. 
Since then, he has moved against the radical Palestinian Islamist 
group Hamas by ordering the arrest of local leaders. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 14:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Garner Interviews for Cubs Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Phil Garner, fired this season in Milwaukee,  
interviewed Friday for the Chicago Cubs' vacant managerial job. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner, ousted in August in the midst of Milwaukee's seventh  
straight losing season, met with Cubs President Andy MacPhail and 
general manager Ed Lynch for about three hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had an open and honest exchange,'' Garner told ESPN Radio  
from O'Hare International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Cubs' mystique is something that we all in baseball are  
amazed by. The fans are tremendous. One of the things you try to do 
is help the organization be a winner and that's a challenge. A 
challenge that looks like fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Riggleman was fired by the Cubs on Monday after five years.  
Chicago was 67-95 this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner had a 563-617 record with the Brewers. He was hired in  
October 1991 with no previous managing experience, and was 
runner-up for the AL Manager of the Year award in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Garner was at least the second person to interview, joining Cubs  
bench coach and Hall of Famer Billy Williams, who met with MacPhail 
and Lynch on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Published reports say the Cubs have received permission from the  
Atlanta Braves to talk to hitting coach and former Colorado manager 
Don Baylor and will also interview Minnesota Twins third base coach 
Ron Gardenhire. Gardenhire was once a New York Mets teammate of 
Lynch and worked under MacPhail when he was GM in Minnesota. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
