<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Education Association Endorses Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's largest teachers' union endorsed  
Al Gore for president Friday, saying he ``understands what children 
need to start school ready to learn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The endorsement by the National Education Association was the  
second of its kind in three days for the vice president, who is 
running against former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley for the 
Democratic presidential nomination. On Tuesday, the American 
Federation of Teachers, the second-largest teachers union, 
announced its support for Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president is still courting the endorsement of the  
AFL-CIO, the federation backed by 13 million labor members. Gore 
was once thought to be assured of the endorsement, but Bradley has 
been aggressive in seeking its backing and some of the federation's 
member organizations have questioned Gore's ability to win in a 
general election. 
</P>
<P>
	Outwardly optimistic but privately nervous that the odds of an  
AFL-CIO endorsement were no better than 50-50, Gore campaign 
chairman Tony Coelho asked House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt 
to use his labor ties on Gore's behalf, labor and political 
operatives said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt made several calls in the last week to union presidents  
asking them to support an early AFL-CIO endorsement, said the 
sources, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFL-CIO is holding its biennial convention next week in Los  
Angeles. On Thursday, President Clinton met with Teamsters 
President Jim Hoffa in New York, although he denied he was trying 
to spur support for Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	The Teamsters are the largest union in the AFL-CIO, and Hoffa  
has been critical of an early endorsement and the administration's 
support for the North American Free Trade Agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also won the endorsement Friday of the National Treasury  
Employees Union, representing some 155,000 federal workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore ``has been a leader on issues important to federal workers  
and their families,'' said the union president, Colleen M. Kelley. 
</P>
<P>
	In its endorsement, the 2.5-million-member NEA said it was  
backing Gore because of his support for full funding of Head Start, 
a preschool program for poor children, as well as for expanded 
preschool and after-school programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The association also praised Gore for ``leading the charge'' for  
smaller class sizes and school reconstruction. 
</P>
<P>
	``Al Gore has earned our support,'' said NEA President Bob  
Chase. ``Time and again he has stood up for children and public 
education. Now it is time -- proudly and enthusiastically -- for us 
to stand with Al Gore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bradley campaign said it was not surprised by the  
endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was long expected,'' said Bradley spokesman Eric  
Hauser. ``We've gotten a lot of support from teachers. We're going 
to continue to talk about issues that are important to them and the 
rest of the country.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
