<DOCNO> APW19991008.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 19:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 8, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Mexico Floods Kill 230  
</P>
<P>
	TEZIUTLAN, Mexico (AP) -- Soldiers and survivors, searching  
desperately for people buried alive when hillsides collapsed in 
southeastern Mexico after more than a week of relentless rain, 
pulled the bodies of at least 15 children from an elementary school 
that was buried during class. Calling it ``the tragedy of the 
decade,'' Zedillo promised government help for families who have 
lost homes. Hundreds of small mountain communities had yet to be 
contacted since the storm cut communication links and blocked roads 
with mud. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Wants Test-Ban Vote Delayed  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton appealed to the Senate today  
to delay acting on the nuclear test ban treaty, agreeing to put off 
the vote -- possibly until after the 2000 presidential election -- 
instead of facing defeat next week. Clinton said a vote rejecting 
the treaty would severely damage efforts to curb the spread of 
nuclear weapons. Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said a vote 
on the treaty is still on track for next Tuesday or Wednesday but 
that he would listen to anything the president has to say. 

</P>
<P>
	Bombing Suspect Appears in Court  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Tanzanian whose house allegedly was used as a  
bomb factory in last year's deadly attacks on two U.S. embassies in 
East Africa pleaded innocent to conspiracy charges today and could 
face the death penalty if convicted. U.S. District Judge Leonard B. 
Sand ordered Khalfan Khamis Mohamed held without bail under tight 
security as a flight risk and a danger to the community. Mohamed 
was arrested yesterday in South Africa and brought to the United 
States for trial. He has pleaded innocent. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Batters Chechnya, Killing 32  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian tanks and artillery battered  
Chechnya after an air attack on a village caught people by 
surprise, reportedly killing dozens. Elistanzhi village 
administrator Ismail Dagayev said 32 people were killed, 60 others 
injured and 200 houses destroyed. Russia has informed the United 
States it has violated an international conventional arms agreement 
by sending more armored equipment to southern Russia in its battle 
against Chechen rebels than the accord permits. 

</P>
<P>
	Book Documents N. Ireland's Troubles  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- A new comprehensive study of  
violence in Northern Ireland raises the death toll from the 
political struggle over the past three decades. The study, put 
together by four Belfast journalists, broadens the official 
definition of who is a victim, adding people who had fatal heart 
attacks after bombings or hearing about the slaying of a loved one, 
and also those who committed suicide in grief. In all, 3,377 people 
are identified as fatalities within Northern Ireland, 124 in 
England, 118 in the Irish Republic, and 18 in continental Europe. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Plays Good Neighbor  
</P>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- Tending neighborly relations, President Clinton  
dedicated a new embassy, agreed on exchanging military technology 
and went golfing with Canada's prime minister today. The defense 
technology agreement preserves license-free access to defense and 
aerospace technology, and allows for easier exchange of technical 
data. Clinton also met briefly with Quebec's separatist premier but 
said the United States values ``a strong and united Canada.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Lee Seeks End to Racial Profiling  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The acting head of the Justice Department's  
civil rights division called on the American Bar Association to 
help eradicate racial profiling by police departments and to 
support affirmative action in law school admissions. Bill Lann Lee 
decried the breakdown of trust between police and minority 
communities and traced much of it to the practice of racial 
profiling, the practice of stopping motorists solely on the basis 
of their race. 

</P>
<P>
	$1.2B Award in State Farm Lawsuit  
</P>
<P>
	MARION, Ill. (AP) -- A damage award to State Farm auto insurance  
customers swelled to nearly $1.2 billion after a judge ruled that 
the nation's largest auto insurer committed fraud by its use of 
generic replacement parts in auto-body repairs. Today's $730 
million award of actual and punitive damages came on top of a 
jury's $456 million verdict. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Climb: Dow Ends Up 112.71  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials gained 112.71 to close at  
10,649.76 today. The Nasdaq gained 21.76 to 2,882.46. 

</P>
<P>
	Braves Beat Astros in 12 Innings  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Brian Jordan's two-run double in the 12th inning,  
gave the Atlanta Braves a 5-3 win tonight over the Houston Astros 
and a 2-1 lead in their best-of-5 NL division series. The Braves 
can advance to their eighth straight LCS with a victory tomorrow. 
Showing they don't intend to play a fifth game Sunday, Atlanta used 
both Greg Maddux and Kevin Millwood in relief. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
