<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colorado's Top Officials Feud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Colorado Lt. Gov. Joe Rogers and his boss, Gov.  
Bill Owens, work just 60 paces apart under the gold-domed Capitol. 
But they haven't spoken face-to-face in months. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute between Owens, a buttoned-down Texan, and Rogers, a  
lawyer who was Colorado's first black candidate for Congress, has 
had racial overtones. It includes accusations of improper spending, 
sniping over personnel policies and even a family feud. 
</P>
<P>
	For months, their bickering was awkward enough, but it mostly  
was kept inside the Statehouse. This week, it became painfully 
public, played out in newspapers and in court. The spat is even 
more embarrassing considering that both are Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're sitting back and kind of chuckling now and kind of  
enjoying the fight,'' said Mike Feeley, the state Senate's 
Democratic leader. ``There's not much mileage to be gained for the 
Democrats, other than letting them look ridiculous, which they're 
doing quite well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, on Friday, staff members arranged an Owens-Rogers  
meeting for Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to try to find a way to work through this thing  
together,'' Rogers told The Associated Press on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens' staff director, Roy Palmer, said he hoped relations could  
be smoothed. ``We have had trouble having a conversation with the 
(Rogers) office. They have been angry for many months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Owens and Rogers reclaimed the Colorado governor's  
office after 24 years of Democratic control. Their election 
thrilled Republicans, who dominate the Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
	But there already had been problems. Rogers was humiliated  
during the campaign after Owens decided to send Rogers in his place 
to a debate with the Democrat gubernatorial candidate. The debate 
never went off. 
</P>
<P>
	This June, Rogers criticized Owens for scheduling a youth  
violence summit -- arranged after the Columbine High School 
shootings -- during the Juneteenth celebration, which commemorates 
the time Texas slaves learned of the Emancipation Proclamation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers was miffed he wasn't consulted about the timing and  
wanted Owens to apologize to the black community; Owens refused. 
Owens rode in the Juneteenth parade, but many black leaders were 
angry. 
</P>
<P>
	Then this week, even as Owens was insisting that he and Rogers  
have a ``professional and proper relationship,'' he announced that 
he has asked the state controller to investigate Rogers' use of 
state funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens' people point to $350 spent on gifts for Taiwanese  
officials who had paid for Rogers' trip to Taiwan; $291 in 
undocumented meal expenses during the trip when meals were free; 
$241 in telephone calls from Washington, D.C., on a hotel phone 
when Rogers had his state phone; and $600 for cheap cufflinks for 
gifts for office visitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers denied wrongdoing, and his people say Owens is too  
authoritarian about budgeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens also questioned Rogers' recommendation that a staffer  
caught driving 103 mph -- with the lieutenant governor in the car -- 
not be ticketed. The governor's office suspended the staffer for a 
week without pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to it all, a member of Rogers' staff is suing Owens for  
denying her a paycheck because she refused to submit to a criminal 
background check Owens demands of all staff members. Latisha 
Kinslow claimed Owens' rules don't apply to Rogers' staffers. Ms. 
Kinslow has since been paid, and both sides think the lawsuit will 
be dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer, Owens' staff director, recently disclosed that Rogers  
asked the governor to put Rogers' brother on the state parole 
board. Owens balked, saying Tracy Rogers was unqualified. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Tracy Rogers has turned on his brother, and in an  
e-mail sent to Owens and circulated by Owens' staff this week, 
Tracy said the lieutenant governor was disloyal and insensitive, 
even mentally disturbed. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers, who originally split over a campaign debt, have  
not spoken since May. The lieutenant governor is reluctant to 
discuss it, but said he thinks his rift with Owens can be repaired. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow Republicans hope so. Owens and Rogers have three years  
left in their term. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not good for the party,'' said House Majority Leader Doug  
Dean. ``It's not good for the state.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
