<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Gives Bombing Figure 12 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A federal judge went well above sentencing  
guidelines today as he again gave Michael Fortier 12 years in 
prison for failing to notify authorities about plans for the 
Oklahoma City bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge G. Thomas Van Bebber said the bombing was  
``widespread and far more serious'' than was contemplated by the 
commission that set the federal sentencing guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier has already served a little more than four years in  
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	In Fortier's first sentencing last year, Van Bebber started with  
first-degree murder guidelines and came up with a sentence of 17 1/2 
years, then took into account Fortier's cooperation with federal 
prosecutors. He wound up imposing a sentence of 12 years and a 
$200,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ordered Van Bebber to  
start over with involuntary manslaughter guidelines, which put the 
baseline sentence at 51 months, or about what Fortier has already 
served. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Van Bebber noted the 168 deaths and the $80 million in  
damage that the April 1995 bombing caused. The judge noted that he 
could have come up with a sentence even greater than 12 years but 
said that would have appeared vindictive. 
</P>
<P>
	He did impose a lower fine, however: $75,000.  
</P>
<P>
	He issued his ruling after hearing arguments from defense  
attorneys, prosecutors and a law professor representing victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Michael McGuire, who unsuccessfully urged a  
sentence of time served, immediately filed an appeal. ``Might as 
well just get the ball rolling on the appeal,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	McGuire said outside the courthouse that Fortier had been ``cast  
aside conveniently'' by the government and given no credit for his 
help with the cases against bomber Timothy McVeigh and 
co-conspirator Terry Nichols. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Sean Connelly said the sentence reflects  
the serious of the bombing. ``This case is extraordinary,'' he 
said. Although the government recommended a lighter sentence than 
the judge imposed, Connelly said the government would defend the 
judge's sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Twelve years sounds pretty good this time around,'' said  
Jannie Coverdale, who had not been happy last year when Van Bebber 
first sentenced Fortier. Ms. Coverdale lost two grandsons in the 
bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I have to say is one day my son will be released and we'll  
be right there for him like we always have,'' said Fortier's 
mother, Irene. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier, 30, has been in prison since pleading guilty in August  
1995 to failing to notify authorities of the plot to bomb the 
Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building and other charges. 
</P>
<P>
	His sentencing was delayed nearly three years until after the  
federal trials of McVeigh and Nichols. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting Fortier's cooperation at the trials, he said, McGuire  
said, ``This man was the difference in both of those cases, your 
honor. This man has given a lot. I don't know if he'll be credited 
for it. He should be given credit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also took exception to a presentencing report by probation  
officer Daniel Muller that asked for a harsh sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel like he's represented the facts accurately,''  
McGuire told the court. 
</P>
<P>
	The government wanted a sentence in the range of 70 to 87  
months. The prosecutor said the government wasn't asking for more 
because of Fortier's cooperation. 
</P>
<P>
	But Paul Cassell, a law professor representing victims, said  
that ``only a substantial upward departure'' from the guideline 
could accommodate the magnitude of the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just punishment demands that the death of 168 people be  
reflected somewhere in the sentence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, survivors and relatives of victims of the bombing  
arrived under a steady rain to hear Van Bebber's sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to the original 12-year sentence, Tom Kight said, ``I  
think 144 months is pretty cheap for 168 lives.'' His stepdaughter 
died in the blast. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal jury in Denver convicted McVeigh on murder, weapons  
and conspiracy counts and recommended he die for his crimes. Judge 
Richard Matsch formally sentenced him to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Another federal jury convicted Nichols of involuntary  
manslaughter and conspiracy. He is serving a life sentence for 
conspiracy and involuntary manslaughter. Matsch sentenced Nichols 
to life in prison. He faces a state trial on 160 counts of murder. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
