<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Flood Survivors Blame Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	POZA RICA, Mexico (AP) -- Victims of massive flooding along  
Mexico's Gulf Coast blamed the government Friday for allowing 
houses to be built -- and sometimes even building them -- on 
riverbanks, swamps and marshes. 
</P>
<P>
	Others said the government had failed to build needed drainage  
projects, and accused rescue workers of arriving too late to save 
any lives. 
</P>
<P>
	Nature played a big role in this week's tragic flooding, which  
has killed at least 230 people in southeastern Mexico. A tropical 
depression in the Gulf dumped almost as much rain in four days as 
many states see in a year, and a waxing moon created high tides. 
</P>
<P>
	But victims said official incompetence was also a major factor.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a crime. Why did the government build on muddy land  
near the river?'' asked Irma Moreno Rodriguez, 48-year-old social 
worker who lived in Poza Rica, 125 miles northeast of Mexico City. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreno bought a small house in a government low-income project  
two years ago. Her home, on the bank of the Cazones River, is now 
filled with several feet of mud. She and her three children are 
living at an improvised shelter at an elementary school. 
</P>
<P>
	President Ernesto Zedillo, who flew to the stricken area Friday,  
appealed for ``the understanding of the people, because we can't 
get there quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to make every effort,'' he said, ``and we're going  
to help families get their houses back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But many victims said the houses should never have been there in  
the first place. 
</P>
<P>
	``The land was a swamp when (state-owned oil company) Pemex  
built our houses here,'' said Gloria Moreno Trueba, another Poza 
Rica resident. 
</P>
<P>
	Early this year, the local government filled in parts of the  
streambed and asked residents to contribute money for a 
flood-containment wall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we're glad we didn't give any money,'' Moreno Trueba said.  
``It wouldn't have stopped the river, and the water would have 
probably come in all at once.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An environmental organization, the Group of 100, accused  
authorities of failing to build the drainage projects needed to 
avoid such flooding. 
</P>
<P>
	``The streets of towns and cities are in a truly disgraceful  
state,'' the group said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Downstream, where the Cazones River nears the Gulf, the problems  
were worse -- and the criticism was directed at rescue workers as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tecolutla, a resort town on a lip of land between the Cazones  
River and the Gulf, survivors said hotels tipped on their 
foundations, houses were washed away and bodies floated by on the 
river. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaking with sobs, Lauren Valverde Lechuga said rescue workers  
had not yet arrived -- two days after the disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are fields for the helicopters to land on, and they  
haven't come,'' she said. ``There are children going hungry, and 
there's nobody to help us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
