<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Fire Mananger and GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The only constant about the Baltimore Orioles  
under owner Peter Angelos is an unwavering lack of continuity. 
</P>
<P>
	Angelos fired manager Ray Miller and general manager Frank Wren  
on Thursday, forcing the once-proud franchise to essentially start 
from scratch in its bid to reach the World Series for the first 
time since 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Orioles begin spring training next season, they will  
have their fifth manager in seven years and their third GM in three 
years. Miller was fired after two straight losing seasons. Wren was 
dumped with two years left on a three-year contract he signed last 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning with the dismissal of manager Johnny Oates in 1994,  
Angelos has fired either his manager or general manager after every 
season except 1996, when Baltimore advanced to the playoffs for the 
first time in 13 years. This is the second time he's canned both 
his manager and GM -- in 1995, he said farewell to manager Phil 
Regan and GM Roland Hemond. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe they ought to install a revolving door on the warehouse  
behind the baseball diamond at Camden Yards, where the players come 
and go almost as often as the front office personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Brown, Rafael Palmeiro, Roberto Alomar, Bobby Bonilla,  
Eric Davis and a host of other stars have worn the Orioles' orange 
and black before going elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller took over the team in November 1997 after Angelos forced  
the resignation of Davey Johnson, who twice took the Orioles to the 
AL championship series, but lost both times. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Miller, the team's former pitching coach, the Orioles went  
79-83 in 1998, then slumped to 78-84 this year despite a $78.5 
million opening-day payroll, third-highest in baseball behind the 
New York Yankees and Los Angeles Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	Wren was cited for several incidents in which he rubbed  
management the wrong way. The most notable offense came last month, 
when Wren ordered the team flight to Anaheim to leave on time after 
Cal Ripken called to say he would arrive late. Ripken had to 
scramble to make his own arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Orioles management cannot and will not abide having a  
general manager operate in such an unreasonable, authoritarian 
manner and treat anyone in this way, especially someone such as Cal 
who has done so much for the Orioles and for baseball,'' vice 
chairman and chief operating officer Joe Foss said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wren declined comment, saying he was in the process of  
negotiating a settlement. He replaced Pat Gillick last October. 
</P>
<P>
	Wren made several fine trades, getting starter Jason Johnson for  
Danny Clyburn and obtaining a handful of good pitching prospects 
for Juan Guzman and Harold Baines. But he also put together a 
bullpen consisting of Seattle Mariners rejects Heathcliff Slocumb, 
Mike Fetters and Mike Timlin. 
</P>
<P>
	The bullpen had 20 blown saves by the All-Star break, leaving  
Baltimore with a 36-51 record and nothing to play for but third 
place in the AL East. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, 54, did not return phone calls Thursday. But during the  
final weekend of the regular season he cited poor pitching for the 
team's lack of success and compared himself to several fine 
managers who also struggled this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you bring a reliever in and he blows a save, you look  
bad. If he does well, you're a brilliant tactician,'' he said. 
``Did Jimmy Leyland all of a sudden get stupid in Colorado this 
year? Did Davey Johnson get dumb when he hit the west coast? Is 
last year's manager of the year, Jim Riggleman, stupid or did his 
club get old on him?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to Miller, Angelos lauded his contributions to the  
1997 team as a pitching coach. But 1998 and 1999 were another 
story. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel bad for Ray,'' Orioles shortstop Mike Bordick said.  
``He obviously wasn't the one throwing the ball or hitting the 
ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Milwaukee Brewers manager Phil Garner is considered the  
leading candidate to replace Miller. Garner was in the midst of his 
seventh straight losing season when he was fired by the Brewers in 
August, but he didn't have much talent to work with for the 
low-budget Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Trebelhorn, the Orioles' director of player development and  
former manager of the Brewers and Chicago Cubs, also is a 
possibility. So is former Orioles star Don Baylor, who managed the 
Rockies from 1993-98, and Riggleman, fired by the Chicago Cubs on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the second time that Miller failed to field a winner as  
a major league manager. He went 50-50 with the Minnesota Twins in 
the second half of the 1985 season and was fired in September 1986, 
with the team struggling at 59-70. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles had a club-record .279 batting average and set a  
franchise record with 1,572 hits, but Baltimore lost 24 games when 
it scored six runs or more. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a good year, and things happen after you don't  
produce the way you're expected to,'' infielder Jeff Reboulet said. 
``It's tough to blame one person for everything going on, but the 
finger usually ends up pointing at the manager. It's part of the 
game.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
