<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Interested in Ron Harper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) -- Ron Harper could join the Los  
Angeles Lakers before the regular season begins. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are hoping to get something done before the end of training  
camp,'' general manager Mitch Kupchak said Friday. ``We have spoken 
to (his) representatives on a consistent basis and continue to have 
a dialogue. Right now, he has some personal obligations he has to 
tend to. Additional week or two of rest will probably help as well. 
He really isn't missing anything he doesn't know already.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harper, a starting point guard on the Chicago Bulls'  
championship teams, is still contemplating retirement or joining 
his old coach, Phil Jackson, on the Lakers' roster. 
</P>
<P>
	He would provide the Lakers' backcourt some much needed  
experience in the triangle offense, but is still recovering from 
surgery he had on his knee two months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Lakers granted rookie Melvin Levett's request to  
be released. 
</P>
<P>
	Levett, an honorable mention All-America in 1998 with the  
University of Cincinnati, was acquired from the Detroit Pistons 
after the 1999 NBA draft in exchange for disgruntled guard Derek 
Harper. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he does not feel his team is ready for it, Jackson also  
held a 5-on-5 scrimmage in their night practice to see exactly 
where his players stand with the new offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have only six practices in and we have to be patient,''  
said Jackson. ``They are not ready. It takes getting physically 
getting ready and mentally getting ready. But, we had a combination 
of guys playing together and move some combinations out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The only way to get better is to get out there on the court,''  
said veteran forward A.C. Green. ``We may not necessarily be ready, 
but it will be a good marker for where we are.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
