<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Rate Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's unemployment rate remained at a  
29-year low of 4.2 percent in September, even though total jobs 
fell for the first time in more than three years as Hurricane Floyd 
played havoc with business hiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Reflecting the impact of the storm that raked the East Coast,  
businesses cut payroll jobs in September by 8,000, the Labor 
Department said Friday. That was the first decline since January 
1996 when a winter blizzard disrupted hiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Even without the storm's effects, the growth in September's  
payroll jobs would have been small compared with brisk gains for 
much of the year. The department estimated employers would have 
added 50,000 jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said, ``Our nation's economy,  
obviously from this report, remains solid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, many analysts had expected companies to add 220,000 jobs  
last month. In August, employers added 103,000, somewhat less than 
the government previously estimated. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hurricane Floyd huffed and puffed and blew a lot of jobs away  
in September,'' said KeyCorp economist Ken Mayland. 
</P>
<P>
	Some economists viewed the weaker-than-expected job growth as a  
possible sign that the economy may be slowing and, thus, could 
reduce pressure on the Federal Reserve and Chairman Alan Greenspan 
to raise interest rates at the next policy meeting in November. 
</P>
<P>
	The report sent mixed signals to Wall Street. There was relief  
over the decline in job growth but concern that rising wages could 
mean inflation was picking up momentum. The Dow Jones industrial 
average closed 112.71 points higher at 10,649.76 as investors 
turned their focus toward the positive earnings news expected next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures,  
grew by a bigger-than-expected 0.5 percent to $13.37 in September 
compared with the 0.2 percent increase in August. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Fed is on the hot seat now,'' said Bill Cheney, chief  
economist for John Hancock. ``Weak employment growth but higher 
hourly earnings point Greenspan and the Fed in two different 
directions. Either the economy is slowing down and the Fed needs to 
sit tight or inflation is starting to take off and another tap on 
the brakes may be necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But some economists said September's wage-growth jump may be a  
fluke, caused by the storm, which reduced weekly hours worked. 
``Whenever hours contract sharply, hourly wages tend to jump but 
that effect does not persist,'' said Merrill Lynch's chief 
economist Bruce Steinberg. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the Fed will just sort of set this report aside, mark  
time and wait for the next one,'' said Robert Dederick, economic 
consultant to The Northern Trust Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong wage growth is a good development for workers, but  
economists and members of the Federal Reserve worry that it could 
spark inflation. Their fear: Employers seeking qualified workers 
woo them with higher wages and benefits, costs likely to drive up 
consumer prices if not constrained by other forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Fed policy-makers on Tuesday decided not to raise interest rates  
for now. But expressing concerns that the tight labor market could 
lead to inflation down the road, they left open the possibility of 
a third rate increase later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In September, manufacturers, who have seen demand for their  
products rebound somewhat from a global financial crisis that began 
in 1997, lost an additional 21,000 jobs. Even the service sector, 
normally the driving force of job creation, suffered a decline of 
9,000 jobs last month, reflecting a drop of 49,000 jobs at retail 
businesses. Job loss was particularly heavy where businesses were 
forced to close because of the hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	The hurricane -- along with a drought -- took a bite out of the  
nation's soybean and cotton crops. The Agriculture Department on 
Friday lowered its forecast of this year's cotton crop by 6 percent 
to 16.4 million bales and reduced its estimate for soybeans by 3 
percent to 2.7 billion bushels. The government expects soybean 
prices to go up, but didn't estimate the impact on cotton prices. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
