<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Barrels Leak Radiation in N. Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A small amount of radiation leaked from barrels at  
a disposal center for contaminated materials, officials said today, 
just a week after Japan's worst-ever nuclear accident. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount of radiation released was far below the level set by  
law as safe, said Shuetsu Shimaya, an official with Japan Nuclear 
Fuel, the company that discovered the leaks. 
</P>
<P>
	The leaks follow a nuclear accident at a uranium reprocessing  
plant outside Tokyo that exposed 49 people to radiation and 
heightened already rising fears in Japan about lax safety standards 
at nuclear facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Shimaya said the leaks, at a disposal center in Rokkasho, 360  
miles northeast of Tokyo, were discovered during an inspection. 
</P>
<P>
	The barrels contained radioactive material from a Tokyo Electric  
Power Co. nuclear power plant in Fukushima prefecture (state). One 
barrel was found leaking on Sept. 28 and the second one was 
discovered Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The disclosure came as authorities were mounting inspections of  
the nation's nuclear facilities to check on safety standards and 
prevent further accidents. 
</P>
<P>
	An investigation into last week's accident, in Tokaimura, 70  
miles northeast of Tokyo, found that operator JCO Co. regularly 
skipped crucial security steps and ordered employees to cut corners 
to save time. 
</P>
<P>
	Fears about the Tokaimura plant are causing more suffering for  
residents by driving down prices for farm goods produced there and 
prompting a rash of cancellations at the region's tourist hotels. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices for sweet potatoes, green onions, carrots and other  
vegetables fell nearly 30 percent after the accident, local 
officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The tourist industry is also hurting. While Tokaimura has few  
sightseers, hotels closer to nearby beaches, mountains and lush 
parklands are losing money. 
</P>
<P>
	September and early October are not busy times for the area, but  
hotels and inns might feel the real pain later in the autumn, when 
tourists usually come to bathe in hot springs and admire the 
mountain foliage, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're worried about what's going to happen in the fall  
season,'' said Nobuko Yamakoshi of Ibaraki prefecture's tourist 
section. ``People in the area surrounding the plant, of course, are 
not doing well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Workers at the fuel reprocessing plant inadvertently started an  
uncontrolled nuclear reaction last week, releasing radioactivity 
into the atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of those exposed were hospitalized and people living close  
to the plant were evacuated, while others were told to stay inside. 
An order to farmers not to harvest their crops was in force for 
three days, and radioactive materials have reportedly been found in 
soil outside the plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Though government officials say the area is now safe, serious  
doubts remain among residents, who are still flooding health 
centers to get checked for radioactivity exposure. Many are 
reportedly suffering from post-traumatic stress. 
</P>
<P>
	A high school in the town conducted a health survey of its  
nearly 700 students today after rising complaints of diarrhea and 
headaches, Kyodo News service reported. School officials could not 
be reached this evening. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation into the accident has focused on slipshod  
practices by the operator of the plant, JCO Co. Reports say the 
government is likely to revoke JCO's operating license. 
</P>
<P>
	A former JCO president, Toshiki Takagi, quit his job today at  
the government-affiliated Metal Mining Agency of Japan to express 
symbolic remorse, an agency official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese media reported today that JCO's parent company,  
Sumitomo Metal Mining Co., planned to get out of the nuclear fuel 
business. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
