<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Finish Narrowly Mixed / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices finished narrowly mixed Friday as  
the September employment report flashed conflicting signals for the 
fixed-income market -- a decline in jobs but an unexpectedly strong 
rise in wages. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 3-16  
point, or $1.87 1/2 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, edged up to 6.19 percent from 6.18 
percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	But prices of short-term Treasury securities were up 1-32 point  
while intermediate maturities were steady, reported Bridge 
Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond markets held an abbreviated trading session to give traders  
a head start on the Columbus Day weekend, and the government's 
unemployment report dominated trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department reported the nation's unemployment rate  
remained at 4.2 percent in September, the lowest level in 29 years, 
but that total jobs fell by 8,000 for the first decline in more 
than three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Even without the impact of Hurricane Floyd, job growth in  
September would have been a relatively small 50,000, the government 
estimated. Many analysts had expected companies to add 220,000 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Some economists saw the job data as a sign the economy may be  
slowing, a development that could reduce pressure on the Federal 
Reserve to raise interest rates in an attempt to stop a resurgence 
of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	But others were bothered by an unexpectedly strong 0.5 percent  
rise in average hourly earnings, interpreting it as a sign 
inflation may be accelerating. The Fed is watching inflation trends 
closely and indicated this week it is inclined to push rates higher 
on signs of rising prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott Platt, director of economic research for Donaldson  
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities, said long-term bond prices rallied in 
immediate reaction to the decline in jobs but reversed course on 
concerns about the wage figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``It raised the nervous expectation in a lot of people's minds  
that the Fed will make a move'' to boost rates at its November 
meeting, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The threat of inflation seems to be there. There is a tight  
labor market too,'' Platt said. He expects a quarter percentage 
point rise in the federal funds rate in November. The federal funds 
rate is what banks charge each other for overnight loans. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the federal funds rate held steady at 5.31 percent,  
the same as late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.79 percent as the  
discount lost 0.03 percentage point from Thursday to 4.67 percent. 
Six-month yields were 5.09 percent, as the discount slipped 0.02 
percentage point to 4.89 percent. One-year yields were 5.29 percent 
as the discount fell 0.02 percentage point to 5.03 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 111 7-32 from 111 9-32 late 
Thursday. The average yield to maturity held at 5.95 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond markets will be closed Monday in observance of the federal  
holiday, although stock markets will be open. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
