<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rules on Cable Ownership Eased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government added flexibility today to its  
restrictions on the number of cable customers a single company can 
serve, hoping to hasten the roll-out of high-speed Internet 
connections and a new generation of telephone services to 
consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission decision also gives AT&AMP;T  
more options for how to complete its proposed $58 billion purchase 
of MediaOne, a deal that would create the nation's largest cable TV 
company and provider of high-speed cable Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC slightly loosened its 30 percent cap limiting a  
company's share of total cable households. The commission also more 
narrowly defined what interests from a limited partnership would 
count against a company toward this audience limit. 
</P>
<P>
	Those changes will help cable companies who want to offer  
high-speed Internet access and local phone service, but who say 
they need to grow in order to do so, the commission said. But the 
rules will also prevent cable companies from having too much 
control in their core business -- television programming. 
</P>
<P>
	``If cable companies want to enter into arrangements with each  
other to pursue new competitive ventures, like local phone service 
and high-speed Internet access, that's no threat to competition,'' 
said FCC Chairman Bill Kennard. ``It could be a boon for 
competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission voted 5-0 to adopt the rules, with two  
commissioners dissenting in part. 
</P>
<P>
	After the vote, Kennard said the commission's decision is in  
line with his ``passion to get high-speed Internet access into 
every home in America as soon as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The original rules -- called for by a 1992 communications law --  
were developed primarily to prevent a cable company from having too 
much control over programming and to ensure diversity in what 
people can watch. 
</P>
<P>
	But now that cable companies are beginning to offer high-speed  
Internet access and local phone service over their pipes, the FCC 
wants to help them enter these markets more quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	Recognizing the rise of competitors to cable like  
direct-broadcast satellite, the FCC voted to apply the 30 percent 
limit to a wider market. That in effect would enable a single 
company to control up to nearly 37 percent of cable subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	There are 66 million cable subscribers nationwide, according to  
the FCC. The multichannel video market -- which more broadly 
includes cable and its competitors -- has 80 million subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules, which have been challenged in court, won't be  
enforced pending a decision. After that, companies will have six 
months to come into compliance. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable companies, like AT&AMP;T, could benefit from some of the  
changes. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the FCC's actions, AT&AMP;T may have more leeway of how  
to complete its planned purchase of MediaOne without losing 
possessions. The rules give AT&AMP;T room to make its case that certain 
interests should not count toward the subscriber limit. 
</P>
<P>
	``What the FCC has to do is take current conditions in the  
market into account in developing a rule that clearly relates to 
the statutory purpose of protecting video programmers,'' said Mark 
Rosenblum, vice president of law for AT&AMP;T Corp. ``We don't think 
that logical and sensible ownership rules should impede our 
transaction with MediaOne.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers groups disagree and fear a few players will end up  
controlling the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``It only takes a small stake in a broadly held company to  
influence its decisions on programming,'' said Gene Kimmelman, 
co-director of Consumers Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Others say the possibility of cable companies getting into the  
local phone market is not an adequate tradeoff for reducing 
diversity of ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is anybody who wants to deliver telephone or Internet  
services over cable can do it without owning the systems,'' said 
Andrew Schwartzman, president of the Media Access Project. ``It's 
blackmail.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
