<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Mulls Fortier's Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Michael Fortier's sentencing judge said  
today that he is considering giving Fortier more than the four 
years he has already served for failing to notify authorities about 
the plans for the Oklahoma City bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge G. Thomas Van Bebber is presiding over a  
resentencing hearing ordered by the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of 
Appeals. The court said Van Bebber used wrong guidelines when he 
sentenced Fortier to 12 years in prison and a $200,000 fine last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said Van Bebber should have used guidelines for  
involuntary manslaughter instead of first-degree murder. The 
manslaughter guidelines call for 51 months in prison; Fortier has 
already served around 50 months. 
</P>
<P>
	But a sentencing brief filed on behalf of bombing victims says  
the judge can impose a longer sentence than the manslaughter 
guidelines call for because of the extraordinary nature of the 
case, and the judge indicated he was learning toward such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am contemplating an upward departure in this case,'' Van  
Bebber said at the start of the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Michael McGuire, who is seeking to have Fortier  
sentenced to time served, objected to a harsher sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier, 30, has been in prison since pleading guilty in August  
1995 to failing to notify authorities of the plot to bomb the 
Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building and other charges. The April 19, 
1995, blast killed 168 people and injured hundreds of other. 
</P>
<P>
	His sentencing was delayed nearly three years until after the  
federal trials of bomber Timothy McVeigh and co-conspirator Terry 
Nichols. 
</P>
<P>
	McGuire took exception to a presentencing report by probation  
officer Daniel Muller that asks for a harsher sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel like he's represented the facts accurately,''  
McGuire told the court. 
</P>
<P>
	McGuire also asked the judge to reconsider the fine imposed  
against Fortier. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Mr. Fortier received a fine, I want the court to know that  
he is not able to pay a fine,'' McGuire said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sean Connelly, assistant U.S attorney, said the government  
wanted a sentence in the range of 70 to 87 months. He said the 
government isn't asking for more than that because of Fortier's 
cooperation. 
</P>
<P>
	But Paul Cassell, a law professor representing victims, said  
that ``only a substantial upward departure'' can accommodate the 
magnitude of the bombing. He suggested the judge reinstate the 
sentence of 12 years and a $200,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just punishment demands that the death of 168 people be  
reflected somewhere in the sentence,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, survivors and relatives of victims as well as of  
Fortier arrived under a steady rain to hear Van Bebber's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think 144 months is pretty cheap for 168 lives,'' said Tom  
Kight, whose stepdaughter Frankie Merrell died in the blast. ``I 
don't know what is a fair sentence for 168 lives. It's never going 
to be enough, OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier's attorneys maintain that his cooperation with  
government prosecutors who made Fortier their star witness at the 
trials of McVeigh and Nichols qualify him to be released 
immediately for time served. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal jury in Denver convicted McVeigh on murder, weapons  
and conspiracy counts and recommended he die for his crimes. Judge 
Richard Matsch formally sentenced him to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Another federal jury convicted Nichols of involuntary  
manslaughter and conspiracy. He is serving a life sentence for 
conspiracy and involuntary manslaughter. Matsch sentenced Nichols 
to life in prison. He faces a state trial on 160 counts of murder. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
