<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar, Gold Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mixed against most other major  
currencies in European trading Friday. Gold rose in London but fell 
in Zurich. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro fell to $1.0671 from $1.0730 Thursday and the British  
pound fell to $1.6517 from $1.6524. But the dollar lost ground to 
the Japanese yen, slipping to 107.49 yen from 107.60. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in New York trading, the dollar bought 107.56 yen, the  
euro was worth $1.0622 and the pound was trading at $1.6520. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,  
included 1.4947 Swiss francs, up from 1.4840; and 1.4692 Canadian 
dollars, down from 1.4698. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth: 1.8328 German marks, up from 1.8231; 
6.1471 French francs, up from 6.1139; 2.0651 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0536; and 1,814.52 Italian lire, up from 1,804.37. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $323.00 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$322.50 on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $320.05, down from $322.30.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold was unchanged in Hong Kong, closing at $321.50.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.62 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.63. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
