<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mount Union Approaches Win Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Oklahoma teams that set an NCAA record  
with 47 straight victories aren't worried that Mount Union is one 
victory away from matching the feat. If fact, they want to see the 
streak continue. 
</P>
<P>
	Several members of those Sooners teams who were contacted this  
week wished good luck to Mount Union in Saturday's game against 
Heidelberg at Columbian High School Stadium in Tiffin. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure they know everybody's gunning for them, but if they  
play as hard while the streak continues as they did to get to this 
point, there's no telling how far they'll go,'' said Ken Northcutt 
of Bethany, Okla., a lineman with the Sooners from 1955 to 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I can give this Mount Union team one piece of advice, it's  
this: Go win this game for yourselves. Don't win it for the school, 
don't win it for the fans, don't win it for the school, but win it 
for yourselves,'' said Joseph Oujesky, also a lineman on those same 
three Oklahoma teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``You'll never forget this accomplishment and you'll realize  
just how significant it was the older you get,'' said Oujesky, an 
executive with the Winn-Dixie supermarket chain in Fort Worth, 
Texas. He officiated football games for 40 years and now is an 
observer of officials for Conference USA. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen this team play on television in the Division III  
championship game and they've got a lot to be proud of,'' he said. 
``I hope they do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If they win Saturday, the three-time defending Division III  
champions can surpass Oklahoma's mark at home against Otterbein. 
What may have been the biggest scare in their last 46 games came 
last Saturday as they held on for a 57-51 victory over John Carroll 
in three overtimes. 
</P>
<P>
	No one else has come within 10 games of the Oklahoma record in  
the four decades since it was set, and it's understandable that the 
Purple Raiders might be feeling some pressure. But the former 
Sooners said they didn't think that much about the importance of 
what they were doing at the time they were doing it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a wonderful time for all of us,'' said Jerry Thompson,  
who is in the oil and gas business in Denver and later coached at 
Oklahoma and the St. Louis Cardinals with Bud Wilkinson, head coach 
of the Sooners during the record-setting period from 1953 to 1957. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson was a sophomore lineman when Notre Dame ended the  
streak with a 7-0 victory at Owen Field in Norman, Okla. ``We 
expected to win and we had a lot of fun, and I bet the Mount Union 
players are having a lot of fun, too,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a certain amount of pressure, but when you're young,  
you don't think about it that much,'' said Jakie Sandefer of 
Houston, who's also involved in the petroleum industry and was a 
starting junior halfback in 1957. ``Now I look back and realize 
that, good gosh, what we did was almost impossible. But we did 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Recalling the end of the streak, Sandefer said, ``There was  
total devastation in the stadium. People didn't move for a long 
time after the game, and neither did we. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I'll never forget coach Wilkinson's words after the game.  
He told us, `I want to congratulate you. This is a record that will 
never be broken by a major college team. The only ones who never 
lose are the ones who never play.' 
</P>
<P>
	``So far, he's been right. And even if Mount Union breaks the  
record, they play at a different level than we did, so his 
prediction will remain correct. But what Mount Union's doing is 
still a magnificent accomplishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually the streak will end, and Dr. Robert Morford, a  
Lawton, Okla., dentist who was a sophomore tackle in 1957, said 
when that happens, the details of the first defeat will be 
remembered longer than most of the victories. 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning 47 is good, but losing one is what stands out,'' he  
said. ``So I hope these guys win the 47th and 48th and keep going. 
It's no fun to lose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once they were beaten, the Sooners didn't let it affect the rest  
of their season. ``Coach Wilkinson didn't practice on Sunday, but 
after Notre Dame, the players went out and practiced on their 
own,'' Morford said. ``We wanted to go out and get better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Thompson recalled, ``We didn't lose any more games that year  
and lost once the next year. So we got over it pretty quickly and 
we've benefited from it ever since.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
