<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Presses Japan on Auto Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Unhappy with lagging sales of Americans cars  
and auto parts in Japan, the Clinton administration is pressuring 
Japan to move more aggressively to reduce regulations the United 
States blames for making the problem worse. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the first seven months of this year, America's deficit  
with Japan just in autos and auto parts climbed to a record annual 
rate of $38 billion despite a 1995 trade agreement with Japan that 
was supposed to narrow the deficit by increasing U.S. sales in 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The two countries discussed the situation during talks Wednesday  
and Thursday in Vancouver, British Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior U.S. trade official told reporters Friday that the  
administration viewed the widening deficit as ``very troubling.'' 
The official spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	While both sides agreed Japan's weak economy was a factor in the  
growing trade gap, the U.S. official said the administration felt 
that now that Japan's economy was beginning to improve, the 
government needed to take ``concrete measures'' to reverse the 
trend. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is pushing Japan to adopt a number of  
deregulatory measures that it believes will spur sales of U.S. auto 
parts at repair shops by cutting government red tape. 
</P>
<P>
	In a report released in June, the administration said sales of  
U.S.-made cars in Japan had dropped 35 percent in 1998 and exports 
of U.S.-made auto parts were down 7.4 percent, the first decline in 
parts sales since the 1995 agreement took effect. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1995 auto deal was negotiated for the administration by  
former U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor. Agreement was 
achieved only after the United States threatened to ban sales of 
Japanese luxury cars in the U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the two countries fell to arguing over the details  
before the ink dried, with the Japanese maintaining they never 
promised to meet numerical targets for increased sales of autos and 
parts or for the expansion of dealerships in Japan carrying U.S. 
autos. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. side said there was no discussion at the Vancouver  
meeting over renewal of the 1995 agreement, which is due to expire 
at the end of next year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
