<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 15:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Garciaparra Expected To Play Game 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- AL batting champion Nomar Garciaparra sat out  
Boston's workout Friday to rest his ailing wrist but was expected 
to play in Game 3 Saturday in an effort to save the Red Sox from 
elimination. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, missing today's workout is no big deal,'' he said after  
his teammates took part in about an hour of light stretching and 
throwing at Fenway Park. ``I'll go out there tomorrow and see how 
it feels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said he had no doubt that  
Garciaparra would play Saturday, when the Indians could sweep the 
best-of-5 division series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until I hear anything different, that's my whole mental  
approach,'' Williams said. ``I think he feels that way, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra, who led the league with a .357 average, bruised his  
right wrist on Sept. 25 when Baltimore's Al Reyes hit him with a 
pitch. It didn't hurt him in the playoff opener, won by Cleveland 
3-2. He went 2-for-3 with a homer and double and scored both runs. 
</P>
<P>
	But in an 11-1 loss in Game 2 on Thursday, Garciaparra was  
0-for-3 with a strikeout and two groundouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said he talked to Garciaparra when he got to the  
ballpark Friday and told him there was no point in aggravating his 
condition during practice. In fact, Williams said he would have 
given the whole team the day off if it hadn't been required to be 
there for the media. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just took a precautionary approach,'' Williams said. ``It  
wouldn't have proven anything for him to work out today. ... It's 
been bothering him. So we just gave him the day off and we look 
forward to him having the opportunity to play tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the Red Sox are to survive, they will need him. With first  
baseman Mike Stanley (5-for-7) and second baseman Jose Offerman 
(2-for-6), Garciaparra has been one of the few productive Red Sox 
hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said he still had confidence in his hitters, and he  
attributed the problem to the fact that Cleveland's Game 1 starter, 
Bartolo Colon, throws 100 mph, and Game 2 starter Charles Nagy has 
been one of baseball's most consistent pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always feel like the guy with the ball in his hand has the  
advantage,'' Williams said. ``But we have good hitters in our 
lineup. We could break out just as easily as they did yesterday. We 
have that kind of team, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The offensive slump has revived questions about Boston's  
decision to let former AL MVP Mo Vaughn leave as a free agent in 
the offseason. While he was with the Red Sox, Vaughn was their best 
hitter while also serving as a fiery leader who could rally his 
teammates from deficits like the one they now face. 
</P>
<P>
	But Williams dismissed the suggestion.  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't need a Speaker of the House,'' he said. ``We need  
baseball players. And that's what we've got here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
