<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 8, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Asks To Delay Test Ban Vote  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton appealed to the Senate today  
to delay acting on the nuclear test ban treaty, saying a 
sure-to-fail vote would severely damage efforts to curb the spread 
of nuclear weapons. Clinton made one new concession to critics of 
the treaty -- he agreed the treaty vote could be put off beyond the 
2000 presidential election. Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., 
said a vote on the treaty is still on track for next Tuesday or 
Wednesday but that he would listen to anything the president has to 
say. 

</P>
<P>
	Arrest Made in US Embassy Bombings  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge today ordered Khalfan Khamis Mohamed,  
the latest suspect arrested in the attacks on two U.S. embassies in 
East Africa, held without bail under tight security. Mohamed was 
labeled a flight risk and a danger to the community. Mohamed's 
house allegedly was used as a bomb factory in the deadly attacks. 
He was arrested yesterday in South Africa and brought to the United 
States for trial. U.S. District Judge Leonard B. Sand told 
Mohamed's lawyer to quickly find experts in death penalty 
litigation in the event the government chooses a death penalty 
prosecution. 

</P>
<P>
	Bin Laden Group on Terrorism List  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department renewed a legal ban on  
any support for 27 foreign terrorist organizations today, adding a 
group headed by Osama bin Laden and removing Palestinian and 
Chilean groups, and Cambodia's Khmer Rouge. Al-Qaida, which the 
State Department says is headed by bin Laden, was added for its 
alleged role in plots to kill the pope and bomb U.S. airliners as 
well as the 1998 bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. 

</P>
<P>
	$1.2B Award in State Farm Lawsuit  
</P>
<P>
	MARION, Ill. (AP) -- A damage award to State Farm auto insurance  
customers swelled to nearly $1.2 billion after a judge ruled that 
the nation's largest auto insurer committed fraud by its use of 
questionable auto-body repair parts. Today's $730 million award of 
actual and punitive damages came on top of a jury's $456 million 
verdict. The initial award was already believed to be the largest 
ever against an insurer. At issue is the use of ``aftermarket'' 
auto parts, which are modeled on those made by the manufacturer but 
made without access to factory specifications. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Gives Fortier 12 Years Again  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A judge went well above sentencing  
guidelines and for a second time gave Michael Fortier 12 years in 
prison for not warning authorities about the plot to bomb the 
Oklahoma City federal building. The new sentence was ordered by a 
federal appeals court. U.S. District Judge G. Thomas Van Bebber 
said he could have issued a longer sentence but it would have 
appeared vindictive. 

</P>
<P>
	Chile Divided Over Pinochet Ruling  
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Opponents of Gen. Augusto Pinochet  
cheered in the streets today after a British magistrate ruled the 
former dictator should be extradited to Spain for trial. 
``Pinochet, prisoner! Pinochet, prisoner!'' hundreds of foes 
shouted as they marched in Santiago. Police looked on but there was 
no violence. Meanwhile, Chile's government redoubled pressure for 
Britain to free the general, warning prolonged detention could 
spark political problems for the country's young democracy. 

</P>
<P>
	Mexico Floods Kill 230  
</P>
<P>
	TEZIUTLAN, Mexico (AP) -- Soldiers and survivors searched  
desperately for people buried alive when hillsides collapsed in 
southeastern Mexico after more than a week of relentless rain. The 
bodies of at least 15 children were pulled from an elementary 
school that was buried during class. At least 230 people were 
confirmed dead from the floods, but the number ``is rising by the 
hour,'' President Ernesto Zedillo said. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Backs Jordan in Trade Group  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Jordan's King Abdullah II received assurance  
of U.S. support for his nation's entry into the World Trade 
Organization and made a pitch to American business executives for 
increased investment in the country. After meeting with Abdullah, 
Commerce Secretary William Daley said the economic reforms Abdullah 
has pushed Jordan to enact represented positive steps in lowering 
the country's trade barriers and bolstering its protections for 
U.S. copyrights and patents. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Climb: Dow Ends Up 112.71  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed sharply higher today, with the Dow  
industrials gaining 112.71 at 10,649.76. On the NYSE, losers led 
gainers 1,549-1,442. The Nasdaq gained 21.76 to 2,882.46. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets' Piazza Out of Game 3 Lineup  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York Mets catcher Mike Piazza was out of the  
starting lineup for Game 3 of the NL division series against 
Arizona tonight because of an injured left thumb. Todd Pratt was to 
take his place. The best-of-5 series is tied at one each. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  
  	   	
</P>
