<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Prices Plummet  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil prices plummeted Friday, capping a 16 percent slide  
this week on futures markets, as President Clinton said he is 
considering selling oil from strategic reserves and as a perception 
grew that OPEC members are starting to exceed production limits. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC's ability to stick to its quotas had helped lift crude oil  
futures to a 33-month high of $25.12 last week on the New York 
Mercantile Exchange, more than doubling from February's low of 
$11.26. But with a drop of $1.55 Friday, light, sweet crude for 
November delivery closed at $20.90 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, the release of U.S. Agriculture Department's  
crop production report pushed grain futures prices lower and 
soybean futures prices higher. 
</P>
<P>
	A lack of confidence in the ability of members of the  
Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries to maintain their 
production-reduction agreement caused another day of losses for 
crude oil futures, sending prices to a two-month low. 
</P>
<P>
	Various surveys estimate that September oil output ranged from  
26.17 million barrels a day to 26.41 million barrels a day, 
according to analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC has a daily production target, excluding Iraq, of 22.97  
million barrels a day. OPEC nations produced 23.5 million barrels a 
day, with Iraq adding 2.7 million barrels. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports that Iraq may be making another diplomatic effort to  
ease sanctions imposed after the Persian Gulf War also caused a 
ripple in the market, according to analyst Bill O'Grady of AG 
Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Grady noted that technical factors fueled Friday's selloff as  
oil fell below price levels viewed as important signposts. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding to the selloff were remarks Clinton in Ottawa during a  
joint news conference with Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien 
that the president is considering selling oil from the U.S. 
strategic petroleum reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we should look at the reserves, and the question of  
whether, if we released some oil from it for sale, if we could 
moderate the price some,'' Clinton said. He said no decision had 
been reached yet ``because I haven't been given a recommendation 
yet about whether we could have any appreciable impact on the 
Americans that are most disproportionately affected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Senator Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., last month sent a letter  
to the White House and the Department of Energy asking them to sell 
the oil to blunt the effect of OPEC's cutback in production. 
</P>
<P>
	However, O'Grady noted that with the market retreating, it would  
be unwise to tap into petroleum reserves at current price levels. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the drop in crude, November heating oil tumbled  
3.74 cents Friday to close at 53.72 cents a gallon on the Nymex; 
November unleaded gasoline was 3.61 cents lower at 59.15 cents a 
gallon and November natural gas was 5 cents higher at $2.692 per 
1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	North Sea Brent crude oil plunged $1.38 to close at $20.70 a  
barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain futures prices fell and soybean futures prices were higher  
on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures prices soared at the start of trading on news  
the USDA placed the 1999-2000 soybean crop at 2.9 billion bushels. 
That is 82 million bushels lower than the September estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures reached $5.06 a bushel, a three-month high, at  
one point in trading before falling back as profit-taking set in. 
Weighing on the market was concern about the soybean harvest, which 
is progressing briskly because of the ideal weather in the Midwest 
crop region. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures prices fell on the USDA data, released before the  
start of trading Friday, which placed the corn crop at 9.4 billion 
bushels, an 86 million bushel increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Also weighing on corn futures was the estimated size of China's  
corn crop. It was placed at 128 million metric tons, which could 
allow China to increase its corn exports at the expense of U.S. 
producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures prices fell after the USDA reported wheat stocks  
totaled 987 million bushels, an increase of 87 million bushels. 
World wheat stocks totaled 128.1 million metric tons, a nearly 4 
million metric ton increase from September. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery was 4 cents lower at $2.54 3/4 a  
bushel; December corn was 4 3/4 cents lower at $1.98 1/2 a bushel; 
December oats were 1 cent lower at $1.08 3/4 a bushel; November 
soybeans were 2 1/4 cents higher at $4.91 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
