<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals Give La Russa 2-Year Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Manager Tony La Russa signed a two-year  
contract extension through the 2001 season today with the St. Louis 
Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	La Russa joined the Cardinals in 1996, and has posted a 319-328  
record. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased to announce that Tony will remain the  
Cardinals' manager into the next century,'' general manager Walt 
Jocketty said. ``I know that Tony wants nothing more than to reward 
the Cardinals' fans for their unmatched support which has led to 
record attendance totals each of the past two seasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This year, La Russa became the 11th winningest manager of all  
time. He leads all active major league managers with 1,639 wins. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals finished 11 games below .500 this year at 75-86,  
in fourth place in the NL Central and 21 1/2 games behind first-place 
Houston, despite a major league-leading 65 home runs by Mark 
McGwire. 
</P>
<P>
	They lost starting pitcher Matt Morris during spring training  
with an arm injury and another starter, Donovan Osborne, early in 
the season. Outfielder Eric Davis was lost for the season with an 
injury while making a diving catch to preserve rookie Jose 
Jiminez's no-hitter June 25. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's last appearance in the postseason came in La Russa's  
first year in St. Louis. The Cardinals lost the 1996 NL 
Championship Series to Atlanta in seven games. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Tony) won't be satisfied until he can get the Cardinals back  
to the postseason,'' Jocketty said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
