<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UAW, Ford talk As Deadline Nears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- With a battle line drawn, the United Auto  
Workers continued negotiations Friday with Ford Motor Co. as a 
midnight strike deadline approached. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no word on any progress shortly before 10:30 p.m.,  
when the two sides still were bargaining 90 minutes before the 
union-set deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hopeful we can reach a settlement by the deadline,''  
Ford spokesman Nick Sharkey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Ford and the UAW have worked long hours this week trying to  
reach an agreement on a new contract for about 100,000 hourly 
workers. But there has been no round-the-clock bargaining yet -- a 
traditional sign a deal is close. 
</P>
<P>
	President Stephen P. Yokich told union members in a taped  
message earlier this week that Ford was being ``stubborn'' about 
accepting contracts agreed to by General Motors Corp. and 
DaimlerChrysler AG. 
</P>
<P>
	During negotiations in 1993 and 1996, the UAW found Ford's  
proposal best and settled with it first -- setting the pattern for 
the other two companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will continue to work and maybe before the company can  
really make a big mistake, they'll understand that they're not 
first this time, but third,'' Yokich said. 
</P>
<P>
	The UAW and Ford have enjoyed good relations for about 20 years,  
avoiding strikes like the one in Flint last year that shut down 
much of General Motors' production. Thanks in part to bulked-up 
production at Ford's truck and sport utility vehicle plants, the 
company made $6.6 billion in 1998; the average worker's profit 
sharing payment was $6,100. 
</P>
<P>
	But this year, UAW officials have said they were opposed to  
Ford's plans to spin off or sell its parts unit, which employs 
23,500 UAW workers. Union leaders have said a separate Visteon 
Automotive Systems could cut pay and jobs, even close plants to 
compete against other parts companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-year contracts negotiated with DaimlerChrysler, GM and  
GM's former parts operations included promises from the companies 
that they would not spin off, sell or close any division or factory 
-- a clause that could be causing problems for Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	The contracts also included 3 percent raises each year, a $1,350  
signing bonus and improved pensions. 
</P>
<P>
	But the UAW also negotiated some terms with GM and Delphi  
Automotive Systems that experts say could apply to Ford and 
Visteon. The contract for Delphi workers mirrors GM's deal; it also 
allows Delphi employees to transfer back to GM and retire by Jan. 1 
with a GM pension. 
</P>
<P>
	GM and Delphi workers are expected to complete voting on the new  
contract by next week. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 08:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chase Manhattan Moving N.Y. Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York City's largest corporate employer,  
Chase Manhattan Corporation, is moving 10 percent of its jobs -- 
about 3,500 positions -- to Florida, Texas and Massachusetts, the 
company has told its workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning next year, the company will move two entire ``back  
office'' units, from entry-level positions to senior managers, 
Chase spokesman Ken Herz said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	By relocating its workers, the bank will cut its costs  
significantly, Herz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he would not estimate the savings, Herz said they are so  
great that the city wouldn't have been able to match them. As a 
result, Chase didn't approach the city for financial or logistical 
help to keep the jobs in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Salaries, real estate costs, taxes, telecommunications charges  
and utilities costs are all lower in Tampa, Fla., and Dallas, where 
most of the jobs are to be moved, he said. Some jobs would also be 
moved to Lowell, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the businesses leaving New York transfers money for  
companies, and the other involves tracking and processing stock and 
bond trades. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Mayor Randy L. Levine said the city was sorry to see the  
jobs go, but added that the company had promised to keep its 
headquarters in the city and would expand its other operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The substantial exodus of jobs from the city is indicative of a  
trend begun in the late 1980s, when many Wall Street firms moved 
their record-keeping and data processing jobs to New Jersey and 
Florida. Since then, technological advances and mergers have 
prompted banks to cut the number of employees in the city. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1988 Chase received $235 million from the city when it agreed  
to move many back office employees to Brooklyn rather than New 
Jersey. Some of the 6,000 Chase jobs in Brooklyn are to be moved, 
though Herz said Chase planned to relocate other business units to 
fill those spaces. 
</P>
<P>
	While Chase said it would offer to relocate many of the  
employees whose jobs are being moved, some may be reluctant to 
leave New York because of family or other reasons. Also, the 
unusually good chances of finding work in the city could keep some 
from moving, corporate consultants said. The city's unemployment 
rate is 6.9 percent, down from about 10 percent in early 1997. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 15:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
