<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kramer To Start at QB for Chargers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The San Diego Chargers' feeble offense is in  
the hands of Erik Kramer, at least for one game. 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer will start at quarterback in place of injured Jim  
Harbaugh in Sunday's road game against the Detroit Lions, coach 
Mike Riley said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Harbaugh suffered two cracked ribs and a bruised throwing elbow  
in the first quarter of last Sunday's 21-14 win over the Kansas 
City Chiefs. 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer came in and threw two touchdown passes, but the defense  
saved the victory by intercepting Elvis Grbac four times, two of 
them setting up scores. San Diego gained only 132 yards and is 
ranked 29th in offense in the 31-team NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	Not only will the Chargers be facing one of their former  
coaches, Bobby Ross, but Kramer will be facing the team he was with 
from 1990-93. The Chargers and Lions are both 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Harbaugh is capable of playing but Riley would prefer that he  
spend the time mending. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no sense playing Jim if he's not 100 percent,'' Riley  
said. ``We have faith in Erik. I think it's a great situation for 
us, having a guy like Erik Kramer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Chargers are looking pretty smart for signing Kramer the  
night before training camp started, two days after his sudden 
release from the Chicago Bears. 
</P>
<P>
	Harbaugh has had a history of injuries and Ryan Leaf, benched  
midway through last year, aggravated a shoulder injury 20 minutes 
into the first training camp practice and had surgery. He won't be 
ready to play until late October. Even the emergency quarterback, 
wide receiver Mikhael Ricks, will probably miss this game with a 
neck injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm always happy to get on the field,'' said Kramer, who  
missed the last half of 1998 after undergoing surgery on his left 
knee and right shoulder. His last start was Oct. 25 at Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a long road,'' said Kramer, who admitted in training  
camp that he was still rusty from the shoulder surgery. ``I'm just 
excited to have an opportunity to be on a team with a chance to 
play. I've come back healthy. It took a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now it's up to him to do something with the offense. The  
Chargers' running game has been bottled up because the team can't 
pass. Last week, Kramer's 11-yard TD pass to Chris Penn -- one of 
several former Bears with the Chargers -- was the only completion to 
a wide receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we could double that, we'd be in a groove,'' Riley joked.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think our running game is there, but it's not very good  
right now because we can't do anything else,'' Riley said. ``We try 
to run, we get 2.3 yards. If we were throwing the ball and had some 
balance going, had a tempo going, we'd be running the ball OK. 
</P>
<P>
	``And we have to be consistent with it, scare people a little  
bit. Otherwise, it's all like pulling teeth. It's all really 
hard.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
