<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Gives Bombing Figure 12 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Going well above sentencing guidelines, a  
federal judge resentenced Michael Fortier to 12 years in prison 
today for failing to notify authorities about plans for the 
Oklahoma City bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier has already served a little more than four years in  
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge G. Thomas Van Bebber issued his ruling after  
hearing arguments from defense attorneys, prosecutors and a law 
professor representing victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ordered the resentencing  
because it said Van Bebber used wrong guidelines when he sentenced 
Fortier last year to 12 years in prison and a $200,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said Van Bebber should have used guidelines for  
involuntary manslaughter instead of first-degree murder. The 
manslaughter guidelines call for 51 months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	At the start of today's hearing, Van Bebber told Fortier he was  
contemplating a harsher sentence than the manslaughter guidelines 
call for. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
