<HEADLINE> Enron May Unload Portland GE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Enron Corp., which may consider  
recently-acquired Portland General Electric as a white elephant, 
still has to come up with a real one. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Enron bought PGE for $3.2 billion and in the  
giddiness of the moment promised to donate an elephant to Oregon 
Zoo. Although the chief executive of the Houston-based company has 
publicly pondered unloading PGE because it not providing the 
investment return it expected, Enron is still on the hook for one 
elephant. 
</P>
<P>
	Finding the pachyderm wasn't easy. But after two years, Enron  
has found an orphaned elephant that needs a new home. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless something happens out of the ordinary, it should go  
through, regardless of where Enron and PGE are,'' said Elaine 
Donaldson, an Enron spokeswoman in Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cost wasn't really an issue, it was more identifying the right  
elephant,'' said Donaldson. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-year-old elephant is in Malaysia and the zoo recently  
received rare permission from the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service to 
bring it to Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	It is illegal to buy or sell the elephant, so Malaysia would  
likely loan Chendra permanently to the zoo. The zoo, in turn, would 
provide expertise to Malaysia, perhaps offering training in 
elephant husbandry or help in tracking orangutans. 
</P>
<P>
	The intricacies of the elephant deal raise eyebrows even among  
the most hardened veterans of the utility-merger game. 
</P>
<P>
	ScottishPower, which received permission Wednesday from the  
Oregon Public Utility Commission to acquire PacifiCorp, has 
refrained from promising elephants, said spokeswoman Rachel 
Sherrard. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good grief, no. We're pragmatic Scots, you know that,''  
Sherrard said. ``I thought you were going to say, 'Would you adopt 
this elephant?' '' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
