<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Calif. Adopts Smog Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DIAMOND BAR, Calif. (AP) -- Under pressure from a federal judge,  
Southern California air quality regulators on Friday adopted what 
they described as the nation's toughest restrictions on 
ozone-depleting emissions from cleaning solvents. 
</P>
<P>
	The move by the South Coast Air Quality Management District  
board followed a ruling in August by U.S. District Judge Harry Hupp 
that the agency had to toughen the limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Solvents are used by scores of businesses to, among other  
things, flush paint guns, degrease auto tools, manufacture medical 
products, and clean aerospace equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The chemicals are problematic because they contain compounds  
that deplete the ozone, said Bill Kelly, an agency spokesman. The 
new standards, to be implemented in two steps in 2001 and 2005, 
will ultimately cut 15 tons of emissions into Southern California's 
air each day. He said the standards are the toughest in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The regional agency had submitted a 1994 air quality plan to the  
federal government, but then pulled 32 items from its list of 
smog-reducing strategies, saying emission levels and technology 
plans had changed. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, the Los Angeles-based Coalition for Clean Air sued  
the agency and demanded that it put back those items. The judge 
agreed. His draft decision, released Aug. 27, is expected to be 
finalized soon, said Sam Atwood, an agency spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives from companies and trade groups told the board  
Friday that they support the plan, especially after the agency 
agreed to evaluate whether the companies have access to products 
that help them meet the tighter limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Katy Wolf, executive director of Santa Monica-based Institute  
for Research and Technical Assistance, said some companies are 
already adopting the 2001 and 2005 requirements. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
