<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Awards $2.22M for Turbulence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A jury has awarded $2.22 million to 13 American  
Airlines passengers who suffered approximately 30 seconds worth of 
severe turbulence during a 1995 flight. 
</P>
<P>
	With the exception of one, none of the plaintiffs suffered  
lasting physical injuries. But the jury on Thursday agreed with 
their unique legal position that fear of death resulting from the 
incident was so damaging it deserved a large award usually given to 
those with physical injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``The real message is that it's not inconsequential when you  
scare people and they think they're going to die,'' said James P. 
Kreindler, a lawyer for the plaintiffs, who was among 101 people on 
the flight. 
</P>
<P>
	American Airlines had admitted liability but contested the  
amount that should be awarded for the turbulence aboard the June 
26, 1995, Los Angeles-to-New York flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Slitt, a spokesman for the Fort Worth, Texas-based airline,  
said he was disappointed by the size of the verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not studied it in detail,'' he said, adding that the  
airline would weigh its legal options after doing so. 
</P>
<P>
	Kreindler said the airline could have avoided the turbulence by  
steering around a storm and should have illuminated a seat belt 
sign to warn passengers about the possibility of rough weather 
ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Miriam Lewinger, a 74-year-old woman who was awarded $150,000,  
testified during the trial that she is still haunted by the 
screams, despite counseling she had received. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept hearing those kids, those children, seeing them running  
back and forth in the aisles,'' Ms. Lewinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	The turbulence hit while Flight 58 was over Minnesota. It made  
an emergency landing in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the plaintiffs' was Nancy Spielberg, the sister of  
filmmaker Steven Spielberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Spielberg's share came to $160,000. Her two daughters, ages  
6 and 2 during the turbulence, were awarded a total of $375,000. 
</P>
<P>
	She called the verdict a slap on the wrist for American  
Airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``They really need more like a punch in the face,'' she said.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
