<HEADLINE> Two More Positve Pan Am Drug Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Two more weightlifters from the Pan  
American Games have lost medals and pushed the total of positive 
drug tests from last summer's event to 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Results of the final two tests were released to Pan Am chief  
executive officer Don MacKenzie at a wrap-up meeting in Mexico last 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Both weightlifters -- silver medalist M. Sanchez Sanchez of Cuba  
and bronze medalist Edries Gonzalez of Puerto Rico -- competed in 
the 105-kilogram category, said vice president of sport Mike Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore said Cristian Escalante of Chile will now be awarded the  
silver medal and Plaiter Reyes of the Dominican Republic will get 
the bronze. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't know for which drugs Sanchez and Gonzalez had tested  
positive. 
</P>
<P>
	There were several high-profile doping cases during the Games,  
including Canadian roller hockey goalie Steve Vezina, whose 
positive test for the anabolic steroid nandrolone cost his team its 
gold medal, and men's high jump world record-holder Javier 
Sotomayor of Cuba, who tested positive for cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominican high jumper Juana Rosario Arrendel was stripped of her  
gold medal after testing positive for the steroid stanozolol. Two 
other Cuban weightlifters and two Mexican baseball players also 
tested positive for nandrolone, and one Mexican ballplayer was 
given a positive result after refusing to submit to a drug test. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
