<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Self Possessed Wins Kentucky Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Finally in the winner's circle at the  
Kentucky Futurity, trainer Ron Gurfein recalled the four failures 
that preceded Self Possessed's triumph in the third leg of the 
harness racing triple crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had four favorites go down. One got scratched, the other  
got interfered with, one got locked in and I forgot what the other 
one was,'' Gurfein said. ``It hasn't been a good race for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His luck turned Friday, thanks to a gritty performance by Self  
Possessed. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3-year-old colt staked his claim to harness racing horse of  
the year honors with a dominating win, sweeping both heats of the 
Futurity at The Red Mile and tying the stakes record with a 1:52 
3-5 in the second heat. 
</P>
<P>
	In the winner's circle, Gurfein and driver Mike Lachance  
re-enacted the kiss they exchanged after Self Possessed won the 
Hambletonian in August in a world-record time of 1:51 3-5. 
</P>
<P>
	In spite of that impressive performance, some had questioned  
Self Possessed after he came up short in last month's World 
Trotting Derby at the Illinois State Fair. There, he lost two of 
three heats to Enjoy Lavec, including the final raceoff by a head. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody said well, `He's got a chink in his armor, he can't  
go two heats,''' said Art Zubrod, manager of Self Possessed's 
majority owner, Brittany Farms. 
</P>
<P>
	The favorite in a field of 10 that started the Futurity, Self  
Possessed took the first-heat lead just past the half-mile, 
overtaking Angus Hall. He pulled away to win by four lengths over 
Enjoy Lavec, with Angus Hall third, two lengths farther back. 
</P>
<P>
	That set up a second heat in which the rest of the field -- minus  
Angus Hall, scratched for health reasons -- set a torrid pace off 
the start, hoping Self Possessed would wilt. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't, surging outside to take the lead on the backstretch  
and reaching the half-mile in :54 4-5. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought there was going to be maybe one (other horse) that  
was going to take a shot out of the gate at the most, but not the 
way it happened,'' said Lachance, who won his second Futurity. 
``That was a brutal half a mile, a half in 54. You've got to be a 
great horse to stand something like that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone knows that Lexington, when you have to go the first  
half fast, you walk home,'' Lachance added. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Self Possessed pushed his lead to five lengths at the  
three-quarter pole, then held off a late charge by Enjoy Lavec, who 
finished two lengths behind. Davanti was third, seven lengths back. 
</P>
<P>
	By winning both heats, Self Possessed avoided a final raceoff.  
</P>
<P>
	The colt paid $2.80 to win and $2.20 to place and show in the  
first heat. In the second heat, he paid $3.00 to win, $2.40 to 
place and $2.60 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he won the Hambletonian and Futurity, Self Possessed  
skipped the trotting triple crown's middle leg, the Yonkers Trot. 
Super Bowl remains the last horse to sweep the series, in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	Gurfein said he had no regrets about skipping Yonkers.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a very bad racetrack, it's a half-mile and I  
didn't want to compromise the rest of the year,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Self Possessed is scheduled to race once more, in the Oct. 29  
Breeders' Crown at Mohawk Raceway in Ontario, Canada, then will 
retire to stud. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's win was Self Possessed's 12th in 21 lifetime starts.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
