<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks Will Fine Sprewell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- The New York Knicks have decided to fine  
the missing Latrell Sprewell, who stayed absent from training camp 
Friday with no explanation. 
</P>
<P>
	The team will hold its final practice in Charleston on Saturday  
morning before returning to New York, and it now appears Sprewell 
will miss the entire camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times reported Saturday that Sprewell had driven  
across the country from Oakland, Calif., stopping in Milwaukee, and 
checked back into the hotel in Westchester County, N.Y. where he 
lived last season. A Knicks spokeswoman could not confirm the 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	``At some point, you have to take disciplinary action,'' said  
general manager Scott Layden, who would not disclose the exact 
amount of the fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks can fine Sprewell $2,500 for his first two missed  
practices and $5,000 for every missed practice thereafter. If the 
team fines him the maximum for every missed practice since 
Wednesday, Sprewell will be out $30,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Discipline is an important part of any team, and obviously  
it's a real important part of this team,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy 
said. ``It's not about anybody making an example of anybody, it's 
about doing the right things, doing what you're supposed to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I want to do more than anything is get it resolved so we  
can get on with the season,'' he said. ``I don't want to be talking 
about this every day for a long period of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell was excused from the first two days of camp so he could  
attend to the close of a civil trial in California stemming from a 
traffic accident he admittedly caused. Sprewell's agent, Robert 
Gist, last told the team that Sprewell would arrive by Wednesday 
night or Thursday morning, but there has been no sign of Sprewell -- 
or any word from him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe he doesn't have communication either,'' Layden said of  
Gist. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times said Gist finally called again late Friday. Layden did  
not immediately return a call seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell is entering the final season of his contract and will  
earn $9 million this season. The Knicks are eager to begin 
negotiating an extension, which makes Sprewell's unexplained 
absence all the more mysterious. 
</P>
<P>
	Layden said Sprewell's absence was not a holdout.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know he'll be here,'' said Marcus Camby, one of Sprewell's  
closest friends on the team. ``If something was really wrong, he 
definitely would have called me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other training camp news, third-string point guard Rick  
Brunson missed Friday's practices with a broken toe and forward 
Ivano Newbill sat out with a sprained ankle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
