<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rules Limiting Cable Ownership Eyed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a move that could impact how consumers will  
get high-speed Internet connections and a new generation of 
telephone service, the government is reconsidering rules that 
restrict the number of cable customers a single company can serve. 
</P>
<P>
	Any decision by the Federal Communications Commission also is  
expected to impact AT&AMP;T's proposed $58 billion purchase of 
MediaOne. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC is considering changes to its cap limiting a company's  
share of total cable households at 30 percent. Those rules -- 
required by a 1992 communications law -- were developed primarily to 
prevent a cable company from having too much control over 
programming and to ensure diversity in what people can watch. 
</P>
<P>
	But now that cable companies are beginning to offer high-speed  
Internet access and local phone service over their pipes, the FCC 
faces new challenges. Cable companies say they need to grow so they 
can compete in these new markets and are pushing for more leeway in 
this area. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission wants to see that happen, but also has to balance  
this with trying to ensure there is not too much concentration in 
cable TV programming, agency officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	The rise of competitors to cable may prompt the FCC to apply the  
30 percent limit to a wider market. That would enable cable 
companies to control a larger number of customers without running 
afoul of the law. 
</P>
<P>
	There are 66 million cable subscribers nationwide, according to  
the FCC. The multichannel video market -- which more broadly 
includes cable and its competitors -- has 80 million subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable companies, like AT&AMP;T, stand to gain if federal regulators  
relax the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the existing rules, AT&AMP;T's recent takeover of  
Tele-Communications Inc. brings the company close to or slightly 
above the 30 percent limit, according to FCC officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission currently is not enforcing the rules, which face  
challenges in court. But once it begins to hold companies to the 
limit, they will have two months to come under compliance. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's plan to purchase MediaOne -- a deal which would create the  
nation's largest cable TV company and provider of high-speed cable 
Internet services -- would put it above the current limits. 
</P>
<P>
	One reason for that is because AT&AMP;T would acquire MediaOne's 25  
percent stake in cable systems owned by Time Warner Inc. Under the 
FCC's existing rules, any stake over 5 percent counts as if the 
whole system is owned by that company. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T says it's ownership in Time Warner would not give it any  
control over programming, and therefore, should not go toward its 
cable audience limit. 
</P>
<P>
	``What the FCC has to do is take current conditions in the  
market into account in developing a rule that clearly relates to 
the statutory purpose of protecting video programmers,'' said Mark 
Rosenblum, vice president of law for AT&AMP;T Corp. ``We don't think 
that logical and sensible ownership rules should impede our 
transaction with MediaOne.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers groups disagree and fear a few players will end up  
controlling the market. 
</P>
<P>
	``It only takes a small stake in a broadly held company to  
influence its decisions on programming,'' said Gene Kimmelman, 
co-director of Consumers Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Others say the possibility of cable companies getting into the  
local phone market is not an adequate tradeoff for reducing 
diversity of ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is anybody who wants to deliver telephone or Internet  
services over cable can do it without owning the systems,'' said 
Andrew Schwartzman, president of the Media Access Project. ``It's 
blackmail.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 07:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ginsberg Items Offered at Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A ``glorious mess'' of Beat Generation poet  
Allen Ginsberg's belongings went on the auction block Thursday, 
including writings, photos with his Beat friends, even the beloved 
harmonium he played at many of his poetry readings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sotheby's auction titled ``Allen Ginsberg and Friends''  
offered photos of Ginsberg, nude with his longtime companion, poet 
Peter Orlovsky, and clothed with Bob Dylan, Jack Kerouac and 
William Burroughs. 
</P>
<P>
	The bearded, balding Ginsberg's blend of drug-inspired visions,  
hedonistic sex and gut-wrenching autobiography first emerged during 
the 1950s. He became the poet laureate of the Beat Generation and 
later was a guru to hippies, coining the term ``flower power'' 
during the mid-60s. 
</P>
<P>
	Letters written by Neal Cassady, the first great love of  
Ginsberg's life and the inspiration for the main character in 
Kerouac's classic ``On the Road,'' sold for $28,750. 
</P>
<P>
	An old friend of Ginsberg's who would not give his name spent  
$12,650 for the harmonium -- a small organ -- the poet played at 
readings. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsberg ``loved his life. He loved his friends. He loved these  
possessions and took every opportunity to enjoy them all,'' said 
Bill Morgan, the archivist for the poet's estate. 
</P>
<P>
	A first edition of his 1956 epic poem ``Howl'' sold for $16,100.  
The work, which dealt with his homosexuality and communist 
upbringing, was purchased by his German translator, Heiner Bastian. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsberg's apartment was ``organized chaos'' where everything  
was shared ``in that joy of 'show-and-tell' that Allen 
personified,'' said Morgan. ``It was a damn mess, it was a glorious 
damn mess!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsberg, who had been suffering from liver cancer, died April  
5, 1997 of a heart attack at 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsberg's heirs -- his brother's children and Orlovsky -- will  
benefit from the sale, which brought in a total of about $674,000. 
All prices include a 15 percent Sotheby's commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of souvenirs from Ginsberg's life were on the block --  
from paintings and near-pornography to his traditional Indian 
clothes and Buddhist meditation mats and beads. 
</P>
<P>
	Bastian, who bid by phone, also paid $17,250 for a well-known  
photograph of Kerouac smoking on a Manhattan fire escape, taken by 
Ginsberg. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest bid of the sale was $40,250, for a set of collages  
resembling doodles by Jean Michel Basquiat, a former graffiti 
artist who sometimes sketched alongside Ginsberg. Basquiat died in 
1988 of a drug overdose at age 27. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 07:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate OKs Hawke As Comptroller </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate on Thursday confirmed John D. Hawke  
Jr. to be comptroller of the currency, a post from which he will 
regulate nationally chartered banks. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton initially nominated Hawke, a former Treasury  
Department official, to the job in July 1998. But his confirmation 
was blocked for months by Democrats led by Sen. Paul Sarbanes of 
Maryland, who argued that Hawke hadn't been a strong enough 
consumer advocate in his prior job. 
</P>
<P>
	Last December, Clinton announced a one-year ``recess''  
appointment of Hawke to the job, using a constitutional power that 
lets the president temporarily make such appointments while 
Congress is not in session. He resubmitted the nomination in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate used a voice vote to affirm Hawke to what will be a  
five-year term. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawke had been undersecretary for domestic finance at the  
Treasury Department since June 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	As comptroller, he plays a key role in maintaining financial  
market stability and oversees some 2,600 banks nationwide. The 
office is part of the Treasury Department. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 09:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Needs Breather, not Penn State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- What Iowa needs on its football schedule  
right now is another Northern Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, what the Hawkeyes are getting is Penn State, which just  
beat Michigan State, 49-3. With Iowa at 1-3 and struggling on 
offense, this is not what the doctor would prescribe as a cure. 
</P>
<P>
	But like it or not, the No. 2 Nittany Lions visit Kinnick  
Stadium on Saturday. First-year Iowa coach Kirk Ferentz -- a Penn 
State fan while growing up in Pittsburgh -- is trying to take in all 
in stride. 
</P>
<P>
	``My experience is you really can't concern yourself a heck of a  
lot about your opponent,'' Ferentz said. ``Obviously, you've got to 
study, you've got to plan and those types of things. 
</P>
<P>
	``But over the long haul, you worry about your performance and  
how you conduct your business and what you do on a day-to-day 
basis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ferentz's main concern is trying to generate some offense. The  
Hawkeyes are averaging just 211 yards and 11 points a game, and 
other than a 24-0 victory over Northern Illinois, they haven't 
scored more than one touchdown in a game. 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa got on the board in last week's loss at No. 11 Michigan  
State only because Tim Dodge's 86-yard kickoff return put the 
Hawkeyes close enough to kick a field goal. 
</P>
<P>
	So why is Penn State coach Joe Paterno worried? First off,  
Paterno is always fretting about something. And second, he doesn't 
like surprises and wants his team to be ready for anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``In some cases, such as Iowa, they are very young in key spots  
and you never know when they are going to mature and all of a 
sudden rise up and play really well,'' he said. ``We are going out 
to a tough stadium to play in. If Iowa has some success, this will 
be a tough environment for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It certainly was a wild environment that last time Penn State  
played at Iowa in 1995. A Penn State helmet was stolen and fans 
pelted the field with beer cans, a full whiskey bottle, 
marshmallows and a frozen chicken. There was even a pig's head on 
the field afterwards, although no one reported actually seeing it 
fly out of the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've heard all about the pig's head,'' Penn State linebacker  
LaVar Arrington said. ``We've heard it's pretty wild playing out 
there. A pig's head -- that's abstract. You expect some confetti or 
some Coke cans. But I've never heard of a pig's head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State (5-0, 1-0) should be able to handle whatever is  
thrown its way Saturday. The Nittany Lions have won close games 
with Pittsburgh and Miami and blowouts with Akron and Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got a great football team,'' Ferentz said. ``There are  
no weak spots out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Ferentz, the game is just one more of those interesting  
twists in life. In high school, his dream had always been to play 
for Penn State. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was THE place at that time,'' he said. ``But I had a  
couple of problems: I was small and I was slow. They weren't 
looking for guys like me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ferentz ended up playing at Connecticut instead. But his wife,  
Mary, is the sister of former Penn State player Kevin Hart and his 
father-in-law played high school football with Paterno. And yes, 
Paterno was coaching Penn State back when Ferentz wanted to play 
there. Now, he's going to coach against Joe Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't really given it thought in terms of, `Geez, I'm on  
the field with him,''' Ferentz said. ``I probably won't think of it 
that way. I'm more worried about those 11 guys they've got inside 
the lines.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
