<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Document Implies U.S. Role in Chile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. intelligence may have played an  
``unfortunate part'' in the death of an American journalist at the 
hands of Chilean security forces in the days following a 1973 
military coup in Chile, according to a declassified State 
Department document released today. 
</P>
<P>
	The journalist, Charles Horman, was taken from his home about a  
week after the Sept. 11, 1973, coup and transported to a stadium, 
where suspected leftists were taken in the chaotic aftermath of the 
coup. 
</P>
<P>
	The document released to his widow, Joyce Horman of New York  
City, said that at best, the U.S. intelligence community's role in 
Horman's death ``was limited to providing or confirming information 
that helped motivate his murder by the government of Chile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``At worst, U.S. intelligence was aware the government of Chile  
saw Horman in a rather serious light and U.S. officials did nothing 
to discourage the logical outcome of the government of Chile's 
paranoia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His widow received the two-page document today from the National  
Security Archive, a research group at George Washington University. 
It was written Aug. 25, 1976, by the head of the State Department's 
office of Chilean affairs, Rudy Fimbres, R.S. Driscoll and W.V. 
Robertson, two other State Department officials who were not 
identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Horman was the subject of a 1982 movie, ``Missing,'' which  
suggested American complicity in his death and drew vigorous 
objections from State Department officials, including then 
Nathaniel Davis, then the U.S. ambassador to Chile. 
</P>
<P>
	``This case remains bothersome,'' the State Department document  
said. ``The connotations for the executive (branch) are not good. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the Hill (Congress), academic community, the press and the  
Horman family, the intimations are of negligence on our part, or 
worse, complicity in Horman's death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The document made available to Mrs. Horman is part of a larger  
release planned today of government documents related to the 1973 
coup in Chile. The release came just hours after a British 
magistrate in London ruled that former Chilean dictator Augusto 
Pinochet be extradited to Spain to stand trial on charges of 
torture. 
</P>
<P>
	Juan Garces, a Spanish lawyer who appeared with Mrs. Horman at a  
news conference, said he received the news from London with ``great 
satisfaction'' and that the verdict proves that dictators ``can't 
find refuge in any part of the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pinochet and his military officers overthrew Salvador Allende, a  
Marxist who had been chosen to lead Chile in a democratic election 
-- an election that caused the Nixon administration to fear that 
Chile could become a communist foothold in South America. 
</P>
<P>
	After Pinochet was arrested in London last October, President  
Clinton issued an order requiring government agencies to declassify 
U.S. documents relating to human rights abuses, terrorism and other 
acts of political violence in Chile between 1968 and 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 6,000 records were released in June. Today's release was  
to include about 350 documents from the State Department, 160 from 
the CIA, 115 from the National Archives, 430 from the FBI and 60 
from the Defense Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Kornbluh, senior analyst at the National Security Archive,  
a research group at George Washington University that gave the 
document to Mrs. Horman, criticized today's release of an estimated 
1,100 government documents, saying it excludes information about 
the CIA's own secret operations in Chile. 
</P>
<P>
	``We adamantly believe that all U.S. records regarding the  
planning and actual efforts to block, undermine and overthrow the 
Allende government, which include kidnapping, coup plotting and 
other acts of political violence between 1970 to 1973'' should be 
released, Kornbluh wrote Monday in a letter to the National 
Security Council. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry Kissinger, then Nixon's national security adviser, had  
insisted the United States had no direct involvement in the coup. 
</P>
<P>
	CIA spokesman Mark Mansfield said the CIA is cooperating with  
the declassification project and will be searching files related to 
its own operations in Chile, including covert activities, and 
declassifying some of them in time for a third release of documents 
planned for next year. 
</P>
<P>
	David Leavy, a spokesman for the National Security Council, said  
those criticizing the CIA should wait until all documents are 
released before accusing the government of keeping certain 
information under wraps. ``The CIA is going to look at the 
operations files,'' Leavy said. ``There will be more coming out 
down the road.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
