<DOCNO> APW19991008.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 08:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Debates Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate plunged into debate on a global  
nuclear test-ban treaty today and Democrats immediately served 
notice they will move to put off a vote indefinitely rather than 
face near-certain defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling the march toward a vote ``pigheaded,'' Senate Minority  
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told reporters today that negotiations 
were continuing with Republican leaders in hopes of postponing the 
vote now scheduled for Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Should they fail, Democrats will make use of a seldom-used  
parliamentary procedure that would force the Senate out of it's 
treaty-considering mode and block further action on the treaty, 
Daschle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a move would require only a 51-vote majority, rather than  
the two-thirds majority -- or 67 votes -- needed to ratify a treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle said he believed he could win enough Republican support  
for the move to prevail, since some influential Republicans who 
oppose the treaty have been among those calling for a delay. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that U.S. allies in Europe were condemning the Senate for  
moving toward expected rejection of the treaty, Daschle said, ``We 
ought to get real about how we debate something of this import. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our allies ... think we're nuts,'' Daschle said.  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, senators debated the merits of the Comprehensive Test  
Ban Treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, one of only two Republicans  
who have indicated they support the pact, told colleagues the 
treaty was one of the most important international agreements of 
the century. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not expect it to be ratified,'' Specter said. ``The  
picture is clear that there are not enough senators to provide the 
two-thirds constitutional margin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., an opponent, said the treaty ``will  
prevent us from making our weapons as safe as they can be and it 
will not stop proliferation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the administration appealed for a delay. Secretary  
of State Madeleine Albright said rejection of the treaty ``would be 
a national security tragedy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But despite her blunt words to the Senate Foreign Relations  
Committee, and an appeal by President Clinton to ``do what's right 
for America,'' the Senate went ahead with debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., indicated a final vote is  
still planned on the treaty as early as Tuesday evening. 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty needs 67 votes to be ratified, or a two-thirds  
majority, if all 100 senators vote. But it has generated scant 
Republican support and even supporters concede they could be 15-20 
votes short. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, Republicans who often side with the administration  
on international matters have joined in opposing the treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	``The treaty is flawed with an ineffective verification regime  
and a practically nonexistent enforcement process,'' said Sen. Dick 
Lugar, R-Ind., a senior member of the Foreign Relations Committee 
and former vice chairman of the Senate Arms Control Observer Group. 
</P>
<P>
	In an article published today in The New York Times, French  
President Jacques Chirac, British Prime Minister Tony Blair and 
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder urged the Senate to approve the 
treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decisions we take now will help determine, for generations  
to come, the safety of the world we bequeath to our children,'' 
they wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Failure to ratify the treaty, the three leaders warned, ``will  
be a failure in our struggle against proliferation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright, in her Senate testimony, noted that presidents have  
been seeking some form of a nuclear test ban since President 
Eisenhower in 1958. 
</P>
<P>
	She said ``the leadership ought to find a way to give the treaty  
the careful consideration it deserves at a later date.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,  
said if Clinton wants to call off the vote, he must request the 
treaty be withdrawn from consideration until after next year's 
presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty has languished before the Senate for two years. But  
the Foreign Relations Committee held its first hearing on the pact 
just Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The rush to a vote, orchestrated by Lott and Helms, angered  
Senate Democrats. And it put them in the awkward position of now 
seeking a delay on the treaty they have long advocated. 
</P>
<P>
	``Does anyone in this chamber seriously believe we can give the  
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty the consideration it deserves in the 
amount of time that has been set aside to debate it?'' said Sen. 
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Thursday, Clinton invoked ``moral responsibility'' in  
seeking to reverse the tide running against the pact. 
</P>
<P>
	He said ``future generations won't forgive us if we fail that  
responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he was not trying to ``beat up'' Republican  
opponents but was asking that ``we do what is in the national 
interest. Let's just do what's right for America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the Senate votes on and rejects the treaty next week, it  
would be the first time an arms control pact was turned down on 
Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	However, President Carter withdrew an arms reduction treaty --  
SALT I -- from the Senate in 1980 after the Soviet invasion of 
Afghanistan made the treaty's rejection likely. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
