<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Apologizes for Irish Comment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- Acknowledging a gaffe, President Clinton  
apologized. He said he didn't mean to offend anyone by comparing 
the troubled peace process in Northern Ireland to a ``couple of 
drunks'' who can't leave a bar. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Rev. Ian Paisley, leader of Northern Ireland's most  
hard-line Protestant party, the Democratic Unionists, called 
Clinton's metaphor an insult to the people of Northern Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, appearing at the inauguration of the U.S. Embassy  
building here on Friday, described how he had spent ``enormous 
amounts of time'' to get the people of Northern Ireland to ``get 
over 600 years of religious fights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then, he added:  
</P>
<P>
	``And every time they make an agreement to do it,'' he  
continued, ``they're like a couple of drunks walking out of the bar 
for the last time. When they get to the swinging door, they turn 
around and go back in and say, 'I just can't quite get there.''' 
</P>
<P>
	The critical reaction from across the Atlantic was swift,  
forcing the White House to issue a statement in the president's 
name. 
</P>
<P>
	``Earlier today, in a discussion of the Irish peace process, I  
used a metaphor that was inappropriate,'' said Clinton in the 
statement. ``I want to express my regret for any offense my remark 
caused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The major Catholic-supported party in Northern Ireland, the  
pacifist Social Democratic and Labor Party, called the remark 
``obviously off the cuff'' and said it ``reflected the reality that 
the president, like so many of us, is justifiably frustrated with 
the slow pace of progress in implementing the Good Friday agreement 
in full.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paisley, whose party opposes the Good Friday peace accord, but  
is entitled to posts within the Protestant-Catholic administration 
that local politicians have been trying to create, was less 
understanding. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a highly offensive and insulting remark to the people  
of Northern Ireland,'' Paisley declared 
</P>
<P>
	National Security Council spokesman David Leavy said in  
Washington that Clinton was expressing his frustration at all sides 
in the Northern Ireland dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly the president didn't mean to cause offense to any  
group of people, but he is clearly frustrated that both sides can't 
seize this moment of peace and make progress in implementing the 
Good Friday accords,'' Leavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the peace process has been ``mired in issues for  
far too long.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
