<HEADLINE> Highlights of Unemployment Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some details of the employment report:  
</P>
<P>
	--The unemployment rate for blacks rose to 8.3 percent in  
September from August's 7.8 percent but was still lower than July's 
rate of 8.8 percent, the Labor Department said. The black 
unemployment rate hit a record low of 7.3 percent in June. 
</P>
<P>
	--The unemployment rate for Hispanics crept up to 6.7 percent in  
September from 6.5 percent in August. Hispanic unemployment was at 
a record low rate of 5.8 percent in March. 
</P>
<P>
	--The unemployment rate for whites edged down to 3.6 percent in  
September from 3.7 percent the month before. 
</P>
<P>
	--The jobless rate for adult women was unchanged at 3.7 percent,  
matching the August rate, while the rate for adult men dipped to 
3.4 percent in September from 3.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--The unemployment rate for teen-agers climbed again to 15  
percent from 13.5 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
