<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Main Index Falls / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo's benchmark stock index closed lower Friday  
on profit-taking following six consecutive sessions of gains. The 
dollar traded lower against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 74.37  
points, or 0.41 percent, to end the day at 18,062.18. The average 
closed up 240.13 points, or 1.34 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. dollar was trading at 107.72 yen, down 0.20 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo but above its level of 107.49 yen late 
Thursday in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices opened lower on profit-taking and a report in the  
Nihon Keizai economic daily that the three-party ruling coalition 
agreed to call on the Bank of Japan to ease monetary policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Too much pressure on the BOJ is not necessarily good,'' said  
Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi, strategist at Daiwa Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The BOJ has come under intense pressure for a monetary easing as  
the yen has surged against the dollar in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese currency has strengthened largely on optimism that  
the economy is recovering from its worst slump in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese authorities fear, however, that too strong a yen could  
hurt that recovery by making Japanese products more expensive 
overseas, thus damaging the earnings of exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Players expected the market to remain cautious ahead of a  
central bank policy board meeting Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average closed down  
51.29, or 0.5 percent, at 10,537.05 on Thursday as investors took 
profits and awaited Friday's release of U.S. jobless figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo stock price index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 5.79 points, or 0.38 percent, to finish at 
1,530.83. The TOPIX closed up 12.51 points, or 0.83 percent, the 
previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar fell as traders awaited the Bank  
of Japan meeting next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's decline followed comments by Japanese Prime  
Minister Keizo Obuchi and Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa that an 
extra budget planned for later this fiscal year will probably 
exceed $92 billion, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government spending is expected to help support Japan's  
nascent economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro bought 115.34 yen at  
mid-afternoon, down from 115.38 yen late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7600 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.7350 percent. Its 
price fell 0.21 points to 99.48. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
