<HEADLINE> Motorist Who Struck King Penalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGOR, Maine (AP) -- The motorist whose van struck and injured  
Stephen King won't be driving anywhere for at least the next six 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Smith, who pleaded innocent to charges of aggravated  
assault and driving to endanger, said he surrendered his license 
after Secretary of State Dan Gwadosky ordered the suspension 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the horror novelist said he is giving $100,000 to  
each of the two hospitals that treated him after he was struck by 
the van on June 19 as he was walking along the shoulder of a road. 
</P>
<P>
	He suffered multiple broken bones in his right leg and hip, as  
well as a collapsed lung, broken ribs and a scalp laceration. 
</P>
<P>
	King, who is recuperating at his Bangor home, has said he does  
not intend to sue Smith but believes that the state should revoke 
his license permanently. 
  	   	
</P>
