<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 15:16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sharks Off to Best Start Yet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Granted, the season is young. Still, the  
San Jose Sharks are off to a special start. 
</P>
<P>
	When Mike Ricci scored his second goal of the game, in overtime  
Thursday night, the Sharks not only beat the Edmonton Oilers 3-2 
but extended their season-opening run to three straight wins, the 
team's strongest start in their eight-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't want to chase teams all year, we want teams to chase  
us,'' said San Jose right wing Owen Nolan, who has scored at least 
one goal in each of the first three games and has five overall 
after collecting only 19 all last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a stronger team now. The majority of the guys were here  
last year and know the system. This win is a great builder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	San Jose has been a more offensive team so far this season while  
getting strong play in goal from Mike Vernon and Steve Shields. 
</P>
<P>
	Ricci, meanwhile, was the eighth player to score this season for  
the Sharks, who have outscored the opposition 15-6. 
</P>
<P>
	San Jose's power play, which struggled last season, also has  
been much more effective. The Sharks have converted seven of 21 
power-play chances, including two Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what you want,'' said Sharks defenseman Gary Suter,  
healthy again after missing virtually all last season with a torn 
triceps tendon. ``A good power play is going to win a lot of 
games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The latest victory illustrated that point.  
</P>
<P>
	Ricci's game-winner came on a power-play goal, San Jose's second  
of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to take advantage of others' mistakes,'' Ricci said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks skated with the man advantage throughout the extra  
period after Josef Beranek drew a five-minute major and game 
misconduct for checking rookie defenseman Brad Stuart from behind 
into the boards. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're playing with confidence,'' Edmonton coach Kevin Lowe  
said. ``Talent-wise, they are a little more skilled than they 
started last season. And that has translated into some early 
success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nolan in particular and the Sharks as a whole have benefited  
from the re-signing of playmaking center Vincent Damphousse. A late 
season acquisition from Montreal last year, Damphousse returned to 
San Jose rather than pursue other free agency offers and he has 
helped convert the Sharks' once-sputtering offense into a 
productive unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Wing Jeff Friesen and center Patrick Marleau also have benefited  
from the presence of the veteran Damphousse, who has at least one 
assist in each of the first three games and six overall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't seen a player like Vinny since Igor Larionov was  
here,'' Sharks general manager Dean Lombardi said. ``He's a better 
player than I ever thought.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks, who never have finished a season above .500, have a  
chance to complete their opening four-game homestand with a perfect 
record Saturday night. However, they'll be facing the defending 
Stanley Cup champion Dallas Stars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
