<HEADLINE> Harnischfeger May Sell Beloit Corp. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Harnischfeger Industries Inc. is considering  
selling its Beloit Corp. unit, which manufactures equipment used in 
papermaking. 
</P>
<P>
	Harnischfeger, of suburban St. Francis, has received some  
interest in all or part of Beloit, the company said Friday in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Harnischfeger, the world's largest producer of mining equipment,  
owns 80 percent of the Beloit Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Harnischfeger's announcement came about four months after it  
filed for financial reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal 
bankruptcy law. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Beloit announced plans to close its manufacturing  
operations in Beloit and Rockton, Ill., cutting 350 jobs. The 
company cited a soft Asian market and poor demand for its 
papermaking equipment as reasons for the cuts that are expected to 
be completed by Jan. 31, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Beloit sales have fallen to $830 million last year from nearly  
$1.3 billion in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline at Beloit Corp. has been a factor in 115-year-old  
Harnischfeger's mounting losses, which reached $90.7 million in the 
first six months of fiscal 1999, just before the company filed for 
bankruptcy. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
