<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Convicts Munchausen Mom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- A woman who prosecutors said  
repeatedly made her daughter sick in order to get attention was 
convicted of child abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	A circuit court jury took eight hours to find Kathy Bush guilty  
Thursday of aggravated child abuse and fraud. Mrs. Bush, 42, burst 
into tears as the verdict was read. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors told jurors that Mrs. Bush fabricated illnesses in  
her daughter, Jennifer, now 12, in an attempt to gain attention and 
sympathy for herself. Psychiatrists call the phenomenon Munchausen 
syndrome by proxy, but the judge didn't allow prosecutors to use 
the specific term. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense told the jury that the daughter was chronically ill  
with a rare gastrointestinal disorder and was not properly treated 
by the medical profession. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the state started investigating in April 1996,  
Jennifer had been hospitalized 200 times and had undergone about 40 
operations, including removal of her gall bladder, appendix and a 
portion of her intestines. 
</P>
<P>
	She hasn't been hospitalized since she was taken from her  
mother. Her family has not been allowed to visit since May. 
</P>
<P>
	Jennifer's father, Craig Bush, emotionally leapt to Mrs. Bush's  
defense after the verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's innocent. There hasn't been justice served,'' Bush said.  
``They've broken up a beautiful family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Robert Buschel criticized the jury and blasted  
the medical basis laid out in the legal proceeding. He called the 
concept of Munchausen syndrome by proxy ``voodoo psychology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But juror Steve Jordan noted the large amount of evidence  
presented in the three-month trial, including the child's medical 
history and testimony from doctors and nurses. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just one thing after another,'' Jordan said. ``It was  
just building block on top of building block, and there was really 
no way to refute it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Mrs. Bush nor her daughter Jennifer was called as a  
witness. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Mrs. Bush did everything she could to keep her  
daughter Jennifer sick, even altering her medicine to exacerbate 
her symptoms. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentencing is set for Nov. 12.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
