<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 a.m EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Oct. 8, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Gandhi May Face Erosion of Power  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- After years of decline, the Congress  
party pinned its hopes on Sonia Gandhi to help it return to power, 
hoping to draw strength from the Nehru-Gandhi dynasty -- instead, it 
suffered its worst drubbing at the polls. Although Mrs. Gandhi 
easily won both seats she contested, her party lost parliamentary 
elections to Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee's alliance. ``We 
accept unhesitatingly the verdict of the people,'' Mrs. Gandhi said 
in a statement carried by the Press Trust of India news agency. 
``The results call for introspection, frank assessment and 
determined action. We will attend to this in the coming days.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Mexico Tries To Account for Dead  
</P>
<P>
	TEZIUTLAN, Mexico (AP) -- Now that rains have given way to gray  
skies in most of the Mexico's flooded region, officials are trying 
to get a full accounting of the dead. They say 166 are confirmed 
dead here in Puebla state alone and the toll is expected rise. 
Mudslides killed 22 in Chiconcuautla villages, 22 more in 
Camocuautla and uncounted others in dozens of obscure towns, where 
roads were washed away by the storms, frustrating rescue efforts. 
Right now, Mexican officials say the total dead is at least 218. 

</P>
<P>
	London Train Crash Victims Mourned  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Laying flowers and saying prayers, a few dozen  
mourners transformed a mass of twisted metal, charred human remains 
and scattered belongings into a memorial yesterday at the site of a 
massive train collision. They sobbed and hugged each other in a 
quiet, heartwrenching display of grief. In the commuter town of 
Reading, dozens of people waited for police to confirm the loss of 
a loved one still missing from Tuesday's crash. A bouquet lay in 
the town center with a note attached: ``Daddy come home I love you 
Clare.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Democrats Hail HMO Bill's Passage  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Proclaiming a big victory on patients' rights,  
House Democrats celebrated passage of a sweeping bill meant to rein 
in HMOs, while acknowledging that it could be difficult to get the 
Senate to go along. The bipartisan measure was approved yesterday 
by a wide margin, 275-151, giving House Democrats virtually 
everything they wanted, including a patient's right to sue, but 
setting up potentially contentious negotiations with the Senate, 
which passed a considerably more modest version earlier this year. 
All sides agreed that the politically charged battle to give 
patients more leverage against HMOs was far from over. 

</P>
<P>
	Pinochet Ruling Due in London  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- After nearly a year in custody for Augusto  
Pinochet and four major court decisions, the latest ruling in the 
case against the former dictator may still not be the final word on 
whether he can immediately return home or must face trial in Spain. 
A London magistrate is due to rule today on whether the 83-year-old 
general should be extradited to Spain to stand trial on torture 
charges, in a case that has sparked strong emotions in Britain and 
Chile. Both sides, however, can launch appeals, which means that no 
matter how Deputy Chief Magistrate Ronald Bartle rules, Pinochet 
will likely remain under house arrest in London for a while longer. 

</P>
<P>
	Scientists Decry Altered Food Hype  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal agencies responsible for approving  
genetically engineered crops and biotech foods insist they can 
prevent products from getting to market that could be dangerous to 
consumers or the environment. ``We're very confident about the 
assurances that are put forward,'' said James Maryanski, 
biotechnology coordinator for the Food and Drug Administration's 
food safety office. Jane Anderson, an EPA official, told the Senate 
Agriculture Committee yesterday that the government's regulatory 
system ``is based on the most rigorous scientific information 
available, is credible, is defensible and will serve to protect the 
environment and public health.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stocks Close Down  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average closed at 18,062.18  
points, down 74.37 points on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today.In New 
York yesterday, the Dow industrials fell 51.29 to 10,537.05. The 
Nasdaq rose 3.49 to 2,860.70. 

</P>
<P>
	Ali's Daughter Making Debut  
</P>
<P>
	VERONA, N.Y. (AP) -- Laila Ali, the second-youngest of Muhammad  
Ali's nine children, will make her debut tonight at Turning Stone 
Casino against April Fowler, a veteran of one pro fight. Laila 
promised that her infectious smile, which lit up a room full of 
microphones and cameras, would soon disappear. ``When you see me 
tomorrow, you're going to see a whole 'nother look,'' she promised. 
``Right now, I have cameras in my face and I'm a very charming 
person. That other side of me is showing, but tomorrow is going to 
be a whole 'nother story.'' The 27-year-old Fowler was not 
impressed. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
