<DOCNO> APW19991008.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 13:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Mailings Net Many Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley is raising about $4 for every $1  
he spends on direct mail, an unusually high success rate that has 
helped him take in more money than Vice President Al Gore during 
the last three months. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley has spent $237,000 on mailings that brought in $1.05  
million in campaign contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	Many candidates often lose money when they send out letters in  
search of contributions, considering it an investment in building a 
donor list that they can use again and again. In presidential 
elections, such a list is doubly valuable because the government 
will match contributions of $250 or less. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, candidates have to send out thousands of solicitations  
just to find a few donors; more than 95 percent of those who 
receive requests for donations simply throw the letter away. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why list building and list development and that fund  
raising is so expensive,'' fund-raising consultant Keith Davis 
said. ``The return is so low.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Bradley has defied the odds, according to the fund-raising  
figures released by his campaign. He has raised an estimated $6.7 
million during the last three months to $6.5 million for Gore and 
has found more than 25,000 people willing to give to his campaign 
for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Contributors responded to letters like this one: ``While the  
pundits and pollsters see my race as an uphill climb, countless 
Democrats and other voters refuse to see this contest decided 
before they've had a chance to speak. If you are among them, then I 
urge you to join me in fighting for a vision of leadership that can 
carry our values, and our party, to victory in November 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A supporter of overhauling the campaign finance laws, Bradley  
noted in his fund-raising letters that he is not accepting 
political action committee contributions. In fact, neither is Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the $1 million in direct mail contributions, Bradley has  
raised another $760,000 through his campaign web site. Bradley 
successfully asked the Federal Election Commission earlier this 
year to allow donations made by credit card -- the only way someone 
can contribute through the Internet -- to be eligible for federal 
matching funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shows there is a steadily growing level of grassroots  
support for Bill Bradley,'' campaign spokesman Tony Wyche said. 
</P>
<P>
	And Bradley is already asking his new friends to give again.  
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to people who already gave, Bradley predicted the  
nomination in both parties may be wrapped up by March, a timetable 
he said he can accept. ``But I must have your financial help now,'' 
he wrote.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 12:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cornell Gets $100 Million Gift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) -- An anonymous donor is giving Cornell  
University $100 million to build new residence halls and student 
commons. 
</P>
<P>
	The gift matches the largest single gift in the Ivy League  
school's history and is the 23rd donation of $100 million or more 
given to an American college, according to the Chronicle of Higher 
Education. 
</P>
<P>
	The pledge is expected to cover about half the cost of new  
housing planned on Cornell's West Campus. The university also has 
set aside $65 million to build two new dormitories on its North 
Campus. 
</P>
<P>
	``This extraordinary commitment will play a major role in our  
goal to make Cornell the best research university for undergraduate 
education in the world,'' Cornell President Hunter R. Rawlings said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Sanford I. Weill, co-chairman of Citigroup Inc., and  
his wife, Joan, pledged $100 million to support Cornell's medical 
school in New York. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
