<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Climb: Dow Ends Up 112.71 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks overcame a volatile start to the session  
Friday and closed sharply higher as investors shrugged off worries 
about inflation and turned their focus to positive earnings news 
expected next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average gained 112.71 at 10,649.76. The  
blue-chip index rose 376.76 this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also moved higher. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 rose 18.38 to 1,336.02, and the Nasdaq composite index 
gained 25.87 to close at 2,886.57. 
</P>
<P>
	All three indexes had their best weekly gains since the week  
ending July 2, when the Dow climbed 586.68. 
</P>
<P>
	Falling oil prices and some bargain hunting helped feed the  
market's gains. In addition, investors were anticipating strong 
earnings reports when companies begin releasing third-quarter 
results next week. 
</P>
<P>
	These factors helped lift stocks from an early morning slump  
caused by uncertainty over the government's employment report, and 
whether it indicated that inflation was accelerating. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market had to make a decision whether they thought the  
jobs report was going to push the Federal Reserve over the edge'' 
and decide to raise interest rates again, said Hugh Johnson, chief 
investment officer at First Albany Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``The answer was no, and that helped get the market going  
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were confused by the employment report because it gave  
mixed signals. On one hand, the Labor Department reported employers 
cut their payrolls by 8,000 jobs in September, the first drop since 
January 1996. Analysts had expected companies to add 220,000 jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline was mostly attributed to Hurricane Floyd, which cut  
into hiring at companies along the East Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	But even with the decline in jobs, wages rose in September.  
Average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures, grew 
by 0.5 percent to $13.37 in September, much sharper than the 0.2 
percent increase in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors liked the decline in job growth but were concerned  
that the rising wages could mean inflation is picking up momentum 
and may prompt the Fed to boost rates for the third time this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market reacted to the upside and the downside of the jobs  
report,'' Ricky Harrington, technical analyst at Wachovia 
Securities in Charlotte, N.C. ``There is a lot of uncertainty in 
the market and this report just shows the nervous atmosphere that 
is out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts also noted that there was a meaningful change this week  
in what stocks investors were buying. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of technology and Internet shares, which have led the  
market in recent months, there was lots of buying of big names in 
other sectors, namely consumer, drug and transportation stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, we are seeing a rapid rotation in the market,''  
said Alan Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The small-cap stocks, however, lagged behind the broader market.  
That was reflected in the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies, 
which fell 0.40 to 427.71. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson &AMP; Johnson led the Dow higher, climbing 4 1/2 to 98 3/4. Other  
gainers included American Express, up 3 3/16 at 149 11/16; 
Wal-Mart, up 4 1/16 at 55 3/8; and General Electric, up 2 7/8 at 124 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox was one of the biggest losers in the market, falling 10 1/2  
to 32 1/4 after the copier maker warned third-quarter earnings would 
be lower than analyst expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	A slump in oil prices hurt oil company stocks, including  
Atlantic Richfield, down 3 13/32 to 85 9/16, and Royal Dutch Shell, 
down 1 3/16 at 57 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a by a narrow margin  
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 1.08 billion 
shares vs. 974.86 million on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.42 percent,  
Germany's DAX index was flat, Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 1 percent, 
and France's AC-40 fell 0.4 percent. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
