<HEADLINE> Jackson Divorcing Second Wife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The wife of pop superstar Michael Jackson  
filed for divorce today, ending a nearly three-year marriage that 
produced two children. 
</P>
<P>
	Papers filed on behalf of Deborah Rowe Jackson in Los Angeles  
County Superior Court cited irreconcilable differences. It said the 
couple had been separated since July 15. 
</P>
<P>
	The divorce petition said both parties reached a confidential  
agreement regarding property and debts. They did not indicate 
whether a custody agreement had been reached for the couple's 
children, 2-year-old Michael Joseph Jackson Jr. and 1-year-old 
Paris-Michael Katherine Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson and his wife ``mutually agreed to end their marriage,''  
spokesman Howard J. Rubenstein said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Michael and Debbie remain friends, and they ask that the  
public respect their desire not to further comment or speculate 
upon the reasons for their decision,'' his statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone call from New York, he declined to provide other  
details and said neither Jackson nor his wife would be making any 
statements. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubenstein said he didn't know the whereabouts of the  
multiplatinum-selling singer, whose hits include ``Thriller'' and 
``Billie Jean.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calls to the attorneys representing Jackson and Ms. Rowe were  
not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Jackson said: ``Debbie and I love each other for  
all the things you'll never see on stage or in pictures. ... I fell 
for the beautiful, unpretentious, giving person that she is, and 
she fell for me just being me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Jackson told a London tabloid newspaper, The Mirror:  
``I love my wife, and we have a happy marriage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, 41, married Ms. Rowe, a nurse in his plastic surgeon's  
office, on Nov. 15, 1996, the same year he and Lisa Marie Presley, 
daughter of Elvis Presley, ended their two-year marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, Jackson won a lawsuit claiming he violated a settlement  
stemming from accusations that he molested a 13-year-old boy. An 
arbitrator entered a judgment in favor of Jackson in a suit filed 
by the boy's father. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson reached an out-of-court settlement of a molestation  
lawsuit in 1994. But the father filed another suit in 1996, 
claiming that his reputation and his son's were harmed when Jackson 
called the allegation ``lies, lies, lies, lies'' in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegations against Jackson were investigated by authorities  
in Santa Barbara and Los Angeles counties, but Jackson was not 
charged with any crime. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 12:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Museum Battle Shifts to Courthouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's decision to pull a  
multimillion-dollar subsidy for a Brooklyn museum because of an 
exhibit he found offensive ``is a First Amendment catastrophe,'' a 
museum lawyer charged today. 
</P>
<P>
	During a federal court hearing, attorney Floyd Abrams compared  
the city's response to the controversial ``Sensation'' exhibit to a 
book burning. He said threats to cut off financing and evict the 
Brooklyn Museum of Art from a city-owned building were ``a form of 
destruction of free expression.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is no less evil than burning a painting,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	An attorney for the city, Leonard Koerner, denied it was  
suppressing free speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not stopping the exhibit,'' he said. ``We are stopping  
the funding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The museum has asked U.S. District Judge Nina Gershon to grant  
an injunction barring the city from withholding $7.2 million in 
annual financing. At the close of the hearing, Gershon said she 
wanted to see more written arguments before ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit of contemporary British art, which opened last  
weekend, includes a painting of the Virgin Mary decorated with 
elephant dung; another of a serial child-killer whose face is 
formed with hundreds of children's handprints; and a bisected pig 
floating in formaldehyde. 
</P>
<P>
	In court papers filed earlier this week, museum director Arnold  
Lehman asserted that city officials were briefed months ago about 
what the museum was planning but that no objections were raised. 
</P>
<P>
	But Giuliani claims officials were misled about the content.  
Last month, after the Republican mayor labeled the Virgin Mary 
painting and other works ``sick stuff'' and ``Catholic-bashing,'' 
the city sued in state court to evict the museum from a site it has 
held for more than a century. 
</P>
<P>
	A brief filed Thursday by City Council Speaker Peter Vallone,  
Public Advocate Mark Green and other local Democrats argues that 
Giuliani, a Republican, violated the Constitution and the City 
Charter by withholding funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Far worse than an offensive painting or exhibit is a mayor  
trying to bully people into silence,'' Green said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Civil Liberties Union, the Metropolitan Museum of  
Art and other cultural institutions have opposed Giuliani in 
similar papers. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute could have political ramifications. Giuliani is  
weighing a run for the U.S. Senate next year, and first lady 
Hillary Rodham Clinton is considering running as the Democratic 
candidate. She has said she does not approve of the art exhibit but 
opposes cutting off funds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991008.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 09:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Xerox Warns of Earnings Shortfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Shares of Xerox Corp. plunged more than  
25 percent today after the information services company warned its 
third-quarter earnings would fall because of increased pressure 
from competitors and lower productivity from its sales force. 
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading on the New York Stock Exchange, shares of  
Xerox were down $11 to $31.75. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Xerox said it expects a 10 percent to 12 percent  
drop in earnings per share from 53 cents in the same period a year 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had been expecting Xerox to earn 58 cents a share for  
the three-month period ending Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales productivity was affected by the continued realignment of  
its sales force, Xerox said. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox announced in April that it was reorganizing its  
14,000-person sales force in a push to boost sales of ``bundled'' 
services to corporate customers, integrating fax machines, 
printers, copiers and PC software. The company said it planned to 
move its sales force away from geographical coverage toward 
coverage of specific industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox said third-quarter results were also hurt by economic  
weakness in Brazil, which was forced to devalue its currency 
earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue was also weaker than anticipated both in the United  
States and Europe, particularly in September. 
</P>
<P>
	The company plans to announce third quarter results on Oct. 18.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
