<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Subway Series Not Ideal for NBC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	While New Yorkers are pulling for a Subway Series that would  
send the city into a frenzy, one team from the Big Apple would be 
plenty for NBC. 
</P>
<P>
	If either the Yankees or Mets make the World Series, most of the  
city will watch anyway. If both teams make it, however, some fans 
around the country are faced with a dilemma. 
</P>
<P>
	Which team to root for? Against?  
</P>
<P>
	For NBC, a Subway Series eliminates a second market from another  
region. 
</P>
<P>
	``In New York, it would be beyond words,'' said NBC's Bob  
Costas. ``But in truth, this is a different time than the '40s or 
'50s when the Brooklyn Dodgers were more of a national team. ... I 
don't think a New York series would be a big deal in Iowa. The idea 
that the whole country would be buzzing I don't think would be 
true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While ratings in New York would certainly improve for the first  
Subway Series in 43 years, the numbers probably wouldn't jump 
enough to make up the difference for the lack of a second home-team 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever marginal increase you get in New York from having  
both teams is not as significant as you might think,'' said NBC 
spokesman Ed Markey. 
</P>
<P>
	Equally as important as the teams that make the World Series is  
the level of competitiveness. Last year's series between the San 
Diego Padres and Yankees had a low 14.1 rating even though it had a 
representative from each side of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because it was a sweep for the Yankees.  
</P>
<P>
	Even the 1997 World Series between Florida and Cleveland, two  
fairly low-profile teams, had a 16.8 rating on NBC. That's because 
it went down to a seventh game. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it goes seven games, it's going to get a great rating no  
matter who makes it,'' Markey said. 
</P>
<P>
	An all-New York finale wouldn't have much impact on advertisers,  
either. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great for the city, but I don't think it would boost  
numbers nationally,'' said Steve Grubbs, a media buyer at BBDO 
advertising agency. ``The ad inventory has nearly all been bought, 
anyway. So it wouldn't make much of a difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two advertising buyers, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
NBC was getting $350,000 to $400,000 for each 30-second commercial. 
Fox received about $300,000 per spot last year. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STILL FUMING:* Golfers aren't second-guessed and criticized  
nearly as much as other professional athletes, but when opinionated 
NBC analyst Johnny Miller let his feelings be known during the 
Ryder Cup last month, the Americans showed how thin-skinned they 
really are. 
</P>
<P>
	``It mystifies me that he's supposed to be a reporter or an  
analyst, and he becomes a critic,'' said Justin Leonard's Ryder Cup 
teammate, Davis Love III, who said he might tell NBC he won't talk 
to them if Miller keeps it up. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller had said Leonard should stay home and watch on TV after  
struggling through the first day and a half of competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``With Johnny, he's not out interviewing players anyway,'' said  
Paul Azinger. ``I don't think Johnny hurt his credibility. I think 
players have always had funny feelings about Johnny, but the 
general public loves him.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *JAIL TALK:* Bryant Gumbel doesn't have much sympathy for Denny  
McLain. 
</P>
<P>
	Gumbel was the first to interview the last 30-game winner on  
television since McLain returned to prison, where he is serving an 
eight-year sentence for a pension-fund swindle. The interview is 
part of HBO's ``Real Sports,'' which debuts Tuesday at 10 p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	``He got very emotional at times,'' Gumbel said. ``Denny's an  
interesting guy. I hate to say people should pity him because he's 
done way too much in his life for that. He's basically convinced 
himself that he's never done anything wrong. It's really 
frightening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gumbel also talked to McLain's ex-wife and daughter, who have  
not visited him in prison in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he has done to his wife is really sad,'' Gumbel said.  
``His baseball pension money has been garnisheed by the government. 
When she sells the house, the money will go to the government. 
She's living day by day and really has no money. Denny has just 
left everyone in his wake out to lunch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUBE BITS:* CBS analyst Brent Jones, who roomed with Steve  
Young for 10 years when they played together in San Francisco, 
isn't sure whether Young will retire. ``He's taken this much more 
serious than he has in the past with concussions.'' ... Brandi 
Chastain's debut as correspondent of the nationally syndicated 
``More Than a Game'' program, with CNN-SI's Fred Hickman, will be 
Nov. 5-7. ... ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' posted a national 
rating of a 14.0/24, 26 percent higher than last year, and the show 
is up 13 percent overall in the first four weeks since the start 
time was switched back to 9 p.m. EDT. 
</P>
</TEXT>
