<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Co. Settles Soc. Security Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A businessman has agreed to pay an $845,000  
fine to settle charges his company mailed millions of households a 
$15 offer for services that the Social Security Administration 
provides for free. 
</P>
<P>
	Darrin Gleeman, president of Federal Record Service Corp.,  
agreed to pay $195,000 of the fine within 30 days and the rest in 
deductions from his and his wife's earnings for the next decade, 
Social Security officials said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gleeman also agreed to dissolve his company.  
</P>
<P>
	``This case sends a clear message to the direct mail industry:  
bilking consumers under Social Security's good name will not be 
tolerated,'' said Social Security's acting inspector general, James 
G. Huse Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	Gleeman's attorney, Kerry Lawrence, said the settlement was not  
an admission of wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Federal Record Service and its president, Darrin Gleeman,  
continue to maintain that the business was 100 percent legitimate 
and aboveboard,'' Lawrence said. ``But based on the government's 
actions in court and the anticipated expenses in fighting the case, 
Federal Record Service determined it was in their best interest to 
put the matter behind them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to the government's lawsuit, filed in May, Federal  
Record Service sent letters to newlyweds or families with new 
babies. In the letters, the company offered, for a $15 fee, to help 
obtain a new Social Security number and card for a newborn or an 
updated card for a bride who changed her name. 
</P>
<P>
	Forms for both purposes can be obtained for free at local Social  
Security offices or by calling a toll-free government number. So 
the company would simply mail out the appropriate free form and 
pocket the $15, government investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	The alleged scam operated for several years out of offices in  
New York, also using a mailing address in Washington, D.C. A 
related Florida company of the same name and its operator, listed 
in the lawsuit as Jay Seinfeld, were not part of the settlement and 
still face mail fraud charges. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
