<DOCNO> APW19991008.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 18:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Stands Firm on Cuba Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- GOP presidential hopeful George W. Bush  
harshly criticized Cuban President Fidel Castro's communist regime 
Friday and said the U.S. embargo should stand until the island is 
free. 
</P>
<P>
	``Castro's day is coming,'' the Texas governor told a packed  
ballroom at Florida's Republican Party convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling Castro a ``revolutionary relic at war with time and at  
war with his own people,'' he reiterated his stance that sanctions 
against the regime must remain until freedom of speech, the press 
and religion comes to Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	The pressure, he added, should not be eased ``until the  
persecuted are set free and the exiled are welcomed home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also promised to rebuild morale in the U.S. military, which  
he said is at an all-time low. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our greatest export to the world has been, is, and always will  
be the incredible freedom we understand in America,'' he said. 
``This freedom must be spread throughout all the Americas. This 
freedom is meant for all our neighbors. This freedom is meant for 
Cuba.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, leading in national Republican polls, is a heavy favorite  
in Florida, where brother Jeb is governor and chairman of his 
campaign for the March 14 state primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the Republicans milling around the convention were  
wearing buttons, hats or T-shirts declaring support for the Texas 
governor. Still, Bush remembered how high his father, President 
George Bush, was riding in polls right after the Persian Gulf War 
and how far he fell before losing the 1992 election. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jeb and I suffered through one of the worst years of our  
life,'' Bush said before his speech. ``We saw a great man go from 
92 to the 30s so I take nothing for granted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state Republican party tried to play down the importance of  
the presidential race at the convention -- which the other GOP 
candidates avoided. Party officials instead cast the event as a 
chance to trade ideas and celebrate Republican control of the 
state's government for the first time in a century. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said he supported his brother's position against oil  
drilling off the Florida coast. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
