<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Fired Over Racist Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Three doctors were barred from working at a  
hospital and fired from a radiology practice for making racist 
remarks that were caught on a hospital tape-recorder that they 
thought was shut off. 
</P>
<P>
	The comments were recorded by a medical transcriber, Barbara  
Jewel Hopson, who sued the doctors, the Atlanta Medical Center, a 
radiology contractor and a transcription company. Ms. Hopson, who 
is black, alleged she was fired after she complained. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. John Bisese, Dr. Kenneth Brinn and a third doctor whose name  
was not released were fired Tuesday by the radiology contractor. A 
fourth doctor named in the lawsuit was cleared. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Jim Lathren, the medical center's chief executive, said  
the doctors would no longer work at the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The doctors were dictating notes about a patient Aug. 5. The  
comments came after they apparently thought the tape-recorder was 
shut off, and were heard Ms. Hopson, who was hired by the hospital 
to transcribe the notes. 
</P>
<P>
	One doctor used a racial epithet to refer to blacks, and the  
others made disparaging comments. The doctors either did not return 
calls seeking comment or referred questions to lawyers who did not 
call. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hopson said she was fired after she complained to the  
doctors and the hospital two weeks after she first raised the issue 
with Peachtree Associates, the transcription company. The company 
said she was transferred to another hospital after Atlanta Medical 
Center requested the switch. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit, which seeks unspecified compensatory and punitive  
damages, was pending. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
