<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SBC, Ameritech Complete Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- SBC Communications said Friday it has officially  
completed its $74 billion purchase of Ameritech, a merger of Baby 
Bells that creates the nation's largest local phone company. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, cleared by federal regulators two days earlier, cuts  
the number of regional Bell monopolies to four, down from the 
original seven created by the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T. SBC had already 
acquired one of the original seven, Pacific Telesis, while another, 
Nynex, was acquired by Bell Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	The new SBC provides local phone service in most of the  
Southwest, Midwest and California with 59 million access lines. It 
also becomes the nation's third largest wireless company with 10.1 
million domestic subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	However, SBC may not remain the biggest local phone company for  
long. The FCC is still reviewing Bell Atlantic's proposed deal with 
GTE. If allowed to combine, those two companies would trump SBC as 
the nation's largest local phone company. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC adopted several conditions to ensure the SBC-Ameritech  
deal would serve the public interest. The new SBC must enter 30 new 
markets within 30 months to compete with established local phone 
companies. SBC is also required to provide deep discounts on key 
pieces of its local access lines to rivals who want to lease them. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
