<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida State Penalizes Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Peter Warrick admitted what he did was  
wrong after the Heisman Trophy hopeful and a Florida State teammate 
were arrested on charges of stealing clothing from a department 
store. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick was indefinitely suspended, and Laveranues Coles, who  
was on probation because of past legal and academic difficulties, 
was kicked off the team. Both players are wide receivers. 
</P>
<P>
	They were arrested Thursday and released without bond on felony  
charges of grand theft. They were accused of paying only $21.40 for 
clothing worth $412.38 on Sept. 29. A Dillard's clerk who rang up 
the deep discount also was charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State coach Bobby Bowden said he did not get a chance to  
meet with Coles, but talked privately with Warrick. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's very remorseful,'' Bowden said. ``I said, `Pete, do you  
realize you were wrong?' And he said `Yes, I realize I was wrong.' 
That's the main thing. He knows that he broke a rule, and if you 
break a rule, this is the consequences that you get.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden, however, said he did not feel betrayed.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know boys are boys, and some of them seem to find adversity  
more than others,'' Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, nicknamed ``Trouble'' by his grandmother, is one of those  
people. He was charged last year with hitting his stepmother 
outside her home. He was suspended for last year's opener against 
Texas A&AMP;M and later served 150 hours of community service for the 
misdemeanor battery charge. He also was suspended for this year's 
opener for academic reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles' eligibility for the 1999 season was in limbo for more  
than two months while school officials made sure he took no money 
from a sports agent to attend a party in Houston. Coles reimbursed 
a girlfriend for an airplane ticket and apologized to teammates 
before being reinstated. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, Florida State Athletics Director Dave Hart  
described Warrick as a ``good citizen'' although, he too, had a 
prior run-in with the law. Disorderly conduct and resisting arrest 
charges against Warrick last year over an altercation in the 
parking lot of a Tampa fast-food restaurant eventually were 
dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrest put Warrick's Heisman Trophy hopes in jeopardy, but  
William J. Dockery, president of the Downtown Athletic Club in New 
York, which awards the Heisman, said Warrick remains eligible for 
the trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	``If any candidate is convicted of a felony, he would no longer  
be eligible to receive the Heisman Trophy,'' Dockery said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden said Warrick's only hope of returning for the rest of his  
senior season might be to get the charge reduced to a misdemeanor. 
School rules prohibit an athlete facing a felony from playing until 
the case is resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``A misdemeanor puts it in our hands,'' Bowden said.  
</P>
<P>
	An off-duty police officer saw and taped Coles purchasing two  
bags of clothing, one right after another, on video surveillance 
equipment. Police said Coles handed the first bag to Warrick. 
Neither bag contained enough merchandise -- $300 -- to make the 
charge a felony. However, Assistant State Attorney Warren Goodman 
said the purchases were considered a single transaction so the 
amounts were totaled. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick will be allowed to practice with the team, but was not  
there Thursday. Quarterback Chris Weinke said the players have not 
been distracted from their game Saturday against Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``My focus has been on the game, will be on the game and will  
continue to be on the game for the next few days,'' Weinke said. 
``That stuff is out of our hands. We can't control it. We can 
control what we do on the field.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
