</P>
<P>
	Unemployment Rate Unchanged  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's unemployment rate was unchanged  
at 4.2 percent in September, the lowest rate in nearly three 
decades, even though the number of payroll jobs actually fell last 
month as Hurricane Floyd cut into hiring. The Labor Department 
reported today that September's rate matched August's rate. The 
nation's jobless rate has been below 4.4 percent since March. 
Employers cut payroll jobs in September by 8,000. 

</P>
<P>
	Xerox Warns of Earnings Shortfall  
</P>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Shares of Xerox Corp. plunged today after  
the information services company warned its third-quarter earnings 
would fall because of increased pressure from competitors and lower 
productivity from its sales force. Xerox said it expects a 10 
percent to 12 percent drop in earnings per share from 53 cents in 
the same period a year ago. Analysts had been expecting Xerox to 
earn 58 cents a share for the three-month period ending Sept. 30. 
Sales productivity was affected by the continued realignment of its 
sales force, Xerox said. The company's stock fell 10 1/4 to 32 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	After-Hours Stock Quotes Delayed  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq Stock Market and the New York Stock  
Exchange have postponed for a second time plans to extend the 
operation of their stock quote tickers to accommodate after-hours 
traders. The tickers provide the stock price information that 
scrolls across the bottom of television screens and is distributed 
to millions of investors via the Internet. Nasdaq today set a new 
target date of Oct. 25, subject to approval by the Securities and 
Exchange Commission. A NYSE spokesman said the exchange hasn't set 
a date and is awaiting SEC approval of the plan. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Cuts Up To 1,000 PC Div. Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM is cutting up to 10 percent of its personal  
computer workforce, or up to 1,000 workers, in a cost-cutting 
effort to turn around the division, which lost nearly $1 billion 
last year. The 5 percent to 10 percent reduction in the 
10,000-person staff will mostly hit marketing employees as the 
company consolidates its staff for different brands -- including 
Aptiva PCs, ThinkPad laptops and Netfinity computer servers -- under 
one marketing umbrella. IBM, which employs 291,000 people overall, 
does not expect any layoffs and said it will offer affected 
employees jobs in other divisions. IBM stock was down 3 at 113 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Air Canada Wants Onex Offer Nixed  
</P>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Air Canada sent a letter to shareholders today  
asking them to vote against the $772 million cash and stock bid 
from Onex Corp. and American Airlines. Air Canada also asked its 
investors to ratify a poison pill defense, which would discourage 
hostile takeovers by making them prohibitively expensive. The 
airline sent the letter after Onex won court permission to call a 
shareholder meeting and force a vote on its offer of $5.31 a share 
for the Montreal-based airline. The meeting is set for Nov. 8. 

</P>
<P>
	Roche To Sell Some Genentech Shares  
</P>
<P>
	SOUTH SAN FRANCISCO, Calif. (AP) -- Genentech Inc. shares tumbled  
today after it was disclosed that its controlling shareholder, 
Roche Holdings Inc., plans to sell a 15.6 percent stake in the 
biotechnology firm. Roche, the Swiss pharmaceutical maker which 
controls about 83 percent of Genentech, plans to sell about 22 
million Genentech shares on the open market. Genentech, which makes 
growth hormones and treatments for non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and 
cystic fibrosis, made the disclosure about Roche's plans as it 
reported yesterday a 6 percent rise in earnings before charges for 
the third quarter. Genentech stock was down 17 5/16 at 155 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	Nike Discloses Factory Locations  
</P>
<P>
	BEAVERTON, Ore. (AP) -- Nike, the world's largest manufacturer of  
athletic shoes, disclosed the domestic and overseas factories where 
its college-licensed products are made after student activists 
fighting sweatshop conditions demanded disclosure. Beaverton-based 
Nike disclosed the factory sites yesterday on its Web site, 
www.nikebiz.com, listing addresses where shoes and clothing are 
made for five universities: Arizona, Duke, Georgetown, Michigan and 
North Carolina. The five universities, after student protests, had 
said they would cut ties with Nike and other companies that failed 
to disclose manufacturing information by March. 

</P>
<P>
	JAMA Names Woman New Editor  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A vice dean of Johns Hopkins University School  
of Medicine was named today as editor of the American Medical 
Association's influential journal, making her the first female 
editor in its 116-year history. At a Manhattan news conference, Dr. 
Catherine D. De Angelis was introduced as editor of the Journal of 
the American Medical Association, succeeding Dr. George Lundberg. 
Lundberg's firing in January provoked a controversy over the 
journal's editorial independence. De Angelis is the editor of the 
Archives of Pediatrics and Adolescent Medicine, published by the 
AMA, as well as a member of JAMA's editorial board. 

</P>
<P>
	NatWest Chief Executive Resigns  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The hostile takeover bid of National Westminster  
Bank PLC's by the Bank of Scotland has resulted in the resignation 
of Natwest's chief executive. NatWest said today that Derek 
Wanless' departure was part of wider boardroom shakeup that was a 
direct response to the Scottish bank's $34.4 billion bid, launched 
last month. Sir David Rowland, currently NatWest chairman, will 
take on the additional role of group chief executive, the company 
said, and Ron Sandler, formerly chief executive of Lloyds of 
London, has been appointed chief operating officer. 

</P>
<P>
	Delta Sells Stock in SAirGroup  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines has sold its 525,000 shares of  
stock in SAirGroup, the parent company of Swissair. The transaction 
will result in a before-tax gain of about $29 million and cash 
proceeds of about $114 million, the Atlanta-based airlines said 
today. Delta's shares in SAirGroup amounted to about a 5 percent 
stake in the Swiss company. Delta had held the stock since 1989. 

</P>
<P>
	European Stocks Close Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed mixed today, with oil  
stocks slipping the most as prices fell and telecommunications 
shares rose on talk of consolidation. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 
614 European companies rose 0.80 points, or 0.3 percent, to close 
at 312.37. The worst performing index was energy, with a drop of 
2.4 percent, followed by chemicals, which lost 1.0 percent. The Dow 
Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks 310 companies in countries 
that joined the single currency, closed down 0.56 points at 327.22. 
London's FTSE 100 index of blue-chip shares closed with a loss of 
1.0 point to 6199.4. The Paris CAC-40 index fell 0.4 percent to 
4,721.93, and Milan's MIBtel index fell 0.4 percent to 33,903. 

</P>
