<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clemens To Pitch in Home State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- The main reason Roger Clemens considered  
playing for the Houston Astros or Texas Rangers was to try and 
fulfill his World Series dream in front of his family and friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he ended up with the New York Yankees, Clemens will  
still share part of his postseason with those closest to him when 
he starts Game 3 of the AL division series Saturday night against 
Texas at The Ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pitching in New York, I might not have had the opportunity for  
a lot of my siblings to see it live. As we speak, they're en 
route,'' Clemens said Friday afternoon. ``I've also got some 
college teammates who are going to be in the area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens' first postseason start in four years comes with the  
Yankees one victory from reaching the ALCS. A strong outing, even 
against a struggling Rangers lineup, would begin to make up for a 
rocky regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens was 14-10 with a 4.60 ERA -- unimpressive numbers for a  
guy who won the previous two AL Cy Young Awards. He was 1-1 with a 
4.96 ERA against the Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roger Clemens has a presence about him when he walks on the  
field,'' Texas manager Johnny Oates said. ``Any time Roger takes 
the mound there's that possibility of an outstanding game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros and Rangers tried getting Clemens from the Blue Jays  
this past offseason. Texas came closest, only to have the Yankees 
make a better offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens said he wanted to go to the defending World Series  
champions all along because they were a good bet to do it again and 
he wanted to help. 
</P>
<P>
	While that angered some fans in his home state, Clemens still  
has plenty of supporters here. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of my roots are back at the University of Texas, so I  
have a lot of well-wishers and people coming from Austin, Houston 
and so on,'' he said. ``It's going to be special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The excitement for this start has been building since manager  
Joe Torre set his postseason rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept getting messages throughout the week about this is what  
we've all been waiting for, go out there and get 'em. It's neat to 
hear those,'' Clemens said. 
</P>
<P>
	A World Series championship is the only thing missing from  
Clemens' impressive career resume. He's won five Cy Youngs and 
pitched in the postseason in 1986, '88, '90 and '95. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've pretty much accomplished just about anything you would  
want to accomplish in 16 years of doing this,'' he said. ``You sit 
there selfishly saying that, but that's the only way you can look 
at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens hasn't pitched in nine days, which could be a problem.  
Sometimes too much rest makes him lose command. That can especially 
work against him in an emotional game like this one. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's one of the most intense people I've ever coached,''  
Yankees pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre said. ``When his juices get 
flowing, sometimes it's difficult to control them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens seemed pretty relaxed Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Having heard that Torre called him ``a shirt-and-tie guy'' in  
contrast to the guy he was traded for, David Wells, Clemens wore a 
yellow tie under his Yankees windbreaker, then pulled it out early 
in his news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``How does that look?'' he asked.  
</P>
<P>
	Clemens will be making his 10th postseason start. He's 1-2 with  
a 3.88 ERA. He hasn't won since his second outing, 13 years ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
