<DOCNO> APW19991008.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-08 07:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Limon Brilliant in Dance Premiere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Limon Dance Company took brilliant looks  
forward and back on its opening night with the New York premiere of 
``The Plain Sense of Things'' and the 50th anniversary performance 
of Jose Limon's masterpiece, ``The Moor's Pavane.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a reception before Tuesday's opening at the Joyce Theater,  
the company presented dancer Mikhail Baryshnikov with a photo of 
Limon dancing his solo ``Chaconne,'' framed with a piece of his 
costume. 
</P>
<P>
	Baryshnikov has been performing ``Chaconne'' in his tours with  
the White Oak Project. Marge Champion made the presentation, citing 
Baryshnikov for ``attracting a new audience to modern dance, 
raising consciousness about our art form and bringing greater 
visibility to the work of Jose Limon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mexican-born Limon was a magnetic dancer and a passionate  
choreographer who came to the United States with his parents at age 
7 in 1915. After he saw his first dance concert, he entered the 
dance school of Doris Humphrey and Charles Weidman, and performed 
in their company for 10 years until 1940. After serving in the Army 
in World War II, he formed his own company, which had its first 
performance on Broadway in 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	Limon choreographed to show emotions and man's fate. He remained  
committed to high tragedy, drawn from history and literature, and 
had no interest in the trend to movement for movement's sake that 
entered modern dance in the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	Carla Maxwell, who danced in the Limon Company before his death  
in 1972, has been artistic director since 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Limon's work, ``The Plain Sense of Things,'' places the dancers  
in a community. No matter how they twirl, reach, lift each other in 
partnering or stand measured distances from one another, they 
convey a sense that they are part of a group. The dance was 
inspired by the paintings of Edward Hopper. 
</P>
<P>
	The sense of an outsider is especially strong in the third  
section of four, titled ``Singing Beyond What You Can Hear.'' Nina 
Watt seemed lost and pensive, sad not to be included in the trio of 
Mary Ford, Carla Maxwell and Carlos Orta, but she is no happier 
when they do include her and fearfully runs away from them. 
</P>
<P>
	Music for the dance was a recording of Philip Glass' ``The  
Saxophone Quartet.'' The work is melodic with minimalist 
underpinnings. David Ferri's lighting put a spotlight on some 
dancers, kept some in shadow while three footlights made huge 
shadows on the back wall. The dance had its premiere in July in San 
Jose, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Moor's Pavane,'' which followed, was first performed on  
Aug. 17, 1949, at the American Dance Festival in New London, Conn., 
with Limon as the Moor. Program notes say Limon didn't so much 
intend to depict ``Othello'' but an Everyman, his treacherous 
friend and their wives. 
</P>
<P>
	His choreography is rich with nuance, and the cast on Tuesday  
brought it out tellingly. The Moor was danced by Carlos Orta. 
Bradon McDonald was the friend. Roxane D'Orleans Juste, danced the 
Moor's wife as a loving innocent. And instead of the put-upon wife 
the friend's wife can be, Carla Maxwell portrayed her as a woman 
who sees a chance for power. 
</P>
<P>
	A sextet performed the music by Purcell.  
</P>
<P>
	The evening ended with Limon's ``The Winged.''  
</P>
<P>
	The company will dance at the Joyce Theater through Oct. 17. It  
will perform Antony Tudor's 1937 ``Dark Elegies'' Oct. 12, 14, 16 
and 17. The company is the first modern-dance company to perform a 
Tudor ballet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
